<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Monday, November 1, on the New York Times
wire. For questions, please call Greg Ambrose at 415-777-7219 or
the business desk at 415-536-5172. For business stories running in
main news, call the news desk at 415-777-7074.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ONLINE _  &LR; Tom Johnson, an avid collector of Franciscan pottery and
an eBay buyer and seller, started his own online business in San
Francisco last year to sell antiques, fine art and collectibles.
Rather than buy and sell their own wares, Johnson and his partner
in Michigan elected to display stuff owned by others and take a 2
percent to 10 percent commission of the sales price. Getting online
is becoming more of a necessity for the 20 million U.S. small
businesses that account for nearly half of all employment and a
third of economic output. By PETER SINTON
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOFA _  &LR; In an apparent effort to cut costs, North Carolina's
Bank of America said it has put off installing its own computer and
management systems in its recently acquired California branches
until 2001, as much as a year later than originally planned. Making
the switch is one of the last and biggest steps in combining San
Francisco's old BofA and the former NationsBank. By SAM ZUCKERMAN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LEAVE _  &LR; President Clinton announced a proposal yesterday that
would let states pay unemployment benefits to parents taking time
off from work to care for a new baby. If the proposal, which does
not require congressional approval, takes effect as expected by
next spring, it would be up to each state to pass legislation
tapping into unemployment funds for paid parental leaves. By DAVID
LAZARUS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GROW _  &LR; I have an idea for a marketing/advertising campaign for
a very large, very well-known company but I lack advertising
experience and am not sure what my next step should be. Who should
I call and how can I protect my interest in these ideas? If by some
minor miracle I could finagle an appointment, what happens if they
say ``thanks, but no thanks'' and then later I see my ideas used?
Does copyright protection apply to something like this? By PETER
SINTON
</P>
