<HEADER>
A5823 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-LEAVE--FAMILY-SFCHRON     12-01 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAVE--FAMILY-SFCHRONICLE </SLUG>
  
 Clinton Proposes Giving Parents Paid Leave to Take Care
of  Newborns 
 &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
President Clinton announced a proposal Tuesday that would let
states pay unemployment benefits to parents taking time off from
work to care for a new baby.
<P>
   If the proposal, which does not require congressional approval,
takes effect as expected by next spring, it would be up to each
state to pass legislation tapping into unemployment funds for paid
parental leaves.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear how the proposal would affect California. The state
is already one of a handful that permit paid childbirth leaves
under its disability insurance program. Most women qualify for six
weeks of payments after giving birth.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Gov. Gray Davis approved raising the weekly
disability benefit limit from $336, to $490. He also authorized a
study into expanding paid leave beyond the standard six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say it is unlikely that the state would shift gears and
switch from its present disability-based program to an
unemployment-based system.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it ain't broke, don't fix it,'' said Donna Lenhoff, general
counsel for the National Partnership for Women and Families in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   She said use of unemployment funds for parental time off likely
will be explored by states that do not have programs to subsidize
absences from work because of new babies.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the governor's office said the new proposal is
being studied but that it is too soon to say whether California may
alter its benefits program for childbirth leaves.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Other States
</P>
<P>
   Aside from California, only Hawaii, New York, New Jersey and
Rhode Island have authorized use of disability insurance for
childbirth leaves.
</P>
<P>
   But with many states now flush with cash thanks to the booming
economy, the federal government thinks many state legislatures will
embrace the use of unemployment insurance surpluses to fund new
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Current federal rules do not allow use of unemployment funds for
childbirth leaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it will strengthen parents' bonds with both their
children and their jobs,'' Clinton said in a White House news
conference before departing for a three-day Democratic fund-raising
trip to the West Coast, as well as a stop at the World Trade
Organization summit in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the eve of this new century, we ought to set a goal that
all parents can take the time they need for their families without
losing the income they need to support them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Family and Medical Leave Act, which was passed in
1993, parents are entitled to up to 12 weeks of unpaid leave to
look after a new baby.
</P>
<P>
   Many Parents Forgo System
</P>
<P>
   However, a 1996 study found that many parents forgo unpaid leave
because they cannot afford the loss of income. One in 10 of those
taking unpaid leave ended up on welfare while off the job,
according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new rule would give options to states that wouldn't
otherwise have them,'' said Lisa Ecks, legislative representative
with the California Labor Federation in Sacramento. ``It gives
states a way to open the door for wage replacement for people who
are between a rock and a hard place.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the business community is opposed to use of
unemployment insurance for parental leaves. Employers are
responsible for funding the program through payroll taxes, and they
fear an increase in payments.
</P>
<P>
   Disability insurance, on the other hand, is paid by workers
through taxes on their paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Businesses Criticize Measure
</P>
<P>
   ``The unemployment rate may be relatively low right now, but
what happens when the party's over?'' asked Dan Danner, senior vice
president of the National Federation of Independent Businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someday, unemployment is going to rise again, and there's a
good chance the only way the government could pay for both this new
benefit and unemployment insurance is to increase payroll taxes,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the U.S. Chamber of Commerce has written to the
Labor Department to warn that using unemployment funds for parental
time off would open a Pandora's box.
</P>
<P>
   Sally Paxton, the U.S. Labor Department's deputy solicitor, said
in a conference call with reporters that each state would be free
to decide the terms of its leave program.
</P>
<P>
   She said the ``model legislation'' put together by the federal
government features 12-week leaves for both mothers and fathers,
with benefits running about $200 a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This proposal is good for families and employers,'' Paxton
said. ``This proposal is about investing in the workforce of
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed rule will be published Friday for a 45-day comment
period. A final rule is expected to be issued by January 17 and
would take effect within several months thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   California provides approximately $1.8billion in total
disability payments each year, according to the state Employment
Development Department. A breakdown for childbirth payments was not
available.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
