<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SIXERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIXERS TOP KNICKS, 74-70 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ It seems milk lasts longer than the expiration
date on the New York Knicks' feel-good moments. Twenty four hours
ago, they were popping out points like candy from a Pez dispenser
and tapping their toes to the beat of a blowout victory against
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   But instead continuing their blissful pattern, the Knicks
curdled at the sight of the Sixers' harassing defense and were left
futilely scraping for points at the First Union Center on Tuesday
night as their two-game winning streak ended, 74-70.
</P>
<P>
   They struggled to put back-to-back possessions together against
a Philadelphia Sixers team that played without Allen Iverson. The
Knicks finished the night shooting 30 percent and turned the ball
over 19 times, getting 18 points out of Latrell Sprewell (6 for 18
with 6 turnovers) and 20 points from Allan Houston (5 for 15).
</P>
<P>
   The Sixers were led by Larry Hughes's 25 points to boost a team
that shot 38.7 percent and made just 14 of 28 free throws. In many
ways, the Knicks' frustrating night of groping for their groove
mirrored their season. They left the court with a 8-8 record, as
did the Sixers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strange,'' Sprewell said. ``We can't get on a roll this
season. We get two wins in a row and then we can't get that third.
We haven't been able to put that run together.''
</P>
<P>
   There was only one offensive run on Tuesday night that mattered.
And the Sixers' claimed it. They did not have Iverson but they had
his stunt double, the springing Hughes. He's almost as explosive,
just as braided, nearly as many tattoos and capable of taking over
a game.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes tortured Houston to open the fourth quarter with a wild
streak. He put together a string that included a dunk off a follow,
a jumper, a 3-point shot and a 3-point play made with a contorted
baseline move that drew a foul on the bewildered Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hughes hurt us,'' Knicks Coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ``We
thought we had them stopped, but then he gave them life.''
</P>
<P>
   For Hughes' effort, the Sixers had a 61-50 lead with 8 minutes
16 seconds left in the game. But with a little effort from John
Wallace and Kurt Thomas, the Knicks were within, 67-64, with 2
minutes remaining. Twice in the closing 21 seconds, the Knicks had
a chance to tie the game. But Houston missed an open 3-pointer and
Sprewell put on his pattened step-back-behind-the-arch 3-pointer
but was errant with 11 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was rushed and you're thinking of everything, the clock,
everything,'' Sprewell said. `'But it just didn't fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing fell right for the Knicks. Without a post presence, the
Sixers could blanket Houston and Sprewell and focus all their
attention on them. ``It's hard for us to win when those two guys
don't shoot reasonably well,'' Van Gundy said.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell and Houston had no help. Unlike their wins against
Orlando and Dallas, the support system disappeared overnight.
Thomas finished 1 for 10 and Charlie Ward was 0 for 2.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the league's new rule to promote more fluid and
graceful game was not applying to Tuesday night's first half. The
same Ward who scored a career-high 25 points against Dallas, had
three fouls and no points in the first quarter _ and Iverson wasn't
on the floor. The same Thomas who opened up against Dallas with 10
points in the opening minutes ended the first half with 1 point and
was 0 for 4 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   There was no support for the sagging combo of Houston and
Sprewell. Together, they ended the first half 6 for 19 with six
turnovers. It was a relief for them to be playing an equally
malfunctioning Sixers' team. The Knicks finished the first half
shooting 25.7 percent while the Sixers hit 38.2 percent, turned the
ball over 12 times and converted just 4 of 13 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   What was the encore? There seemed to be little room for these
two teams to look worse. But they managed to open the third quarter
with a combined four turnovers in 59 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The Sixers did unearth some semblance of an offense when Tyrone
Hill opened up with two baseline jumpers to put his team up, 37-33,
early in the third. The Sixers went ahead 41-35 after Sprewell's
fourth turnover of the game resulted in a fast-break layup by Aaron
McKie with 7 minutes remaining. After a flurry of misses and
mistakes by the Sixers, Sprewell, who had missed six shots in a
row, came up with a drive on a hop inside the paint and then a
jumper to pull the Knicks within 47-45 with 46.7 seconds left in
the third. The Knicks did not escape without one more turnover that
led to a layup by Larry Hughes, but not to be outdone, the Sixers
allowed Houston to sprint through the paint and draw a foul with
one-tenth of a second remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Houston hit both free throws, to leave the Knicks behind, 49-47,
entering the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, the Knicks were still in this game despite the
eyesore they were co-producing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
