r f BC-GROW--COLUMN-SFCHRONI     12-01 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW--COLUMN-SFCHRONICLE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
</HEADLINE>
   Protecting Your Idea Until It Can Be Sold 
 &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;         c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Q: &LR;  I have an idea for a marketing/advertising campaign for a &LR; 
 &LR; very large, very well-known company but I lack advertising &LR; 
 &LR; experience and am not sure what my next step should be. Who &LR; 
 &LR; should I call and how can I protect my interest in these ideas? &LR; 
 &LR; If by some minor miracle I could finagle an appointment, what &LR; 
 &LR; happens if they say ``thanks, but no thanks'' and then later I &LR; 
 &LR; see my ideas used? Does copyright protection apply to something &LR; 
 &LR; like this? &LR;
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: Ideas by themselves cannot be copyrighted. That means
``anyone who releases them into the marketplace risks having them
ripped off,'' according to lawyer Debora Jacobs, author of ``Small
Business Legal Smarts (Bloomberg Press, $16.95). However, if you
can put your idea in a tangible form like a song, slogan, picture,
cartoon or brochure, you have a better chance of protecting it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; It sounds like you have no connection with the company, so the
first thing to do would be finding the appropriate person to deal
with, such as the marketing vice president or product manager.
Jacobs recommends phoning that person and trying to set up a
face-to-face meeting. Going through the advertising agency
increases the layers of people and the chances that your idea, if
it is truly a bright one, could be stolen.
</P>
<P>
   If your contact asks for more information before setting up a
meeting, you can ask the person to sign an agreement not to
disclose your topics of discussion. However, if the person refuses,
you might not have many options.
</P>
<P>
   You can also write a letter describing your idea in writing, for
example, a slogan, and attach a copyright notice with it plus your
name and date. That puts the recipient on notice that you have
registered a copyright or plan to do so.
</P>
<P>
   This won't guarantee that someone won't take your idea, but it
should lessen the chances.
</P>
<P>
   For more information and details on how to apply for a copyright
online, contact the U.S. Copyright Office at  &LR; lcweb.loc.gov &LR; 
 &LR; /copyright &LR; . Also check out chapters on intellectual property
protection in business books like Jacobs'.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that a lot of people have ``better ideas'' for
other people's businesses, and the one you are trying to reach may
have heard it all before. On the other hand, businesses often pay
big bucks for marketing ideas that ignite sales. If yours is one of
them and the company expresses an interest, Jacobs suggests you
might ask for a modest lump-sum payment plus a bonus tied to sales
increases.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, you would want an agreement in writing and likely
would need to consult a lawyer who specializes in intellectual
property to hash out the details.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; More on SEPs
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Q: I'm self-employed with one employee who works 28 hours per
week. I have an SEP IRA but can't seem to get a straight answer
from a CPA or tax attorney as to the requirements for setting up a
retirement account for my employee and funding it. How long can I
keep the employee out? One year, three years or not at all? And is
there an hourly or annual minimum pay requirement?
</P>
<P>
   A: The custodian for your Simplified Employee Pension plan
should have the answers. When employers set up an SEP IRA, they
must specify the requirements for employees. Employees older than
21 cannot be excluded from the plan, according to Danville CPA Mary
Kay Foss.
</P>
<P>
   Employers have the option to include younger workers, and they
also can elect to exclude any worker who has not been with the
company for as much as three years or makes less than $400
annually.
</P>
<P>
   In simple terms, once an employee has been with you at least
three years, is over 21 or makes $400 or more, you have no choice
but to include them in your SEP plan.
</P>
<P>
   IRS Form 5305-SEP lists all the requirements in the instructions
printed on the form. Foss notes that many employers do not
anticipate having employees when they establish such a plan. She
also sees some stingy employers drop their SEP plans and adopt
less-costly retirement plans just before employees become eligible
for coverage.
</P>
<P>
   You should consult a plan administration company for more
information.
</P>
<P>
   Ooops
</P>
<P>
   Apologies to reader Gretchen Beck, whose name I misspelled in
last week's column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
