<HEADLINE>
FREE SMOKES ARE MAILED TO ARIZONANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE MCCLOY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - Rob Evans quit his pack-a-day habit when a heart
attack nearly killed him in 1990. Now, out of the blue, R.J.
Reynolds Tobacco Co. is mailing him free packs of Winstons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked,'' the 51-year-old Tempe social worker said
Tuesday, Nov. 30.
</P>
<P>
   So were other Phoenix area residents who within the past month
received unsolicited canisters or book-size parcels containing two
to four packets of cigarettes. One of the recipients was a woman
whose toddler opened the family mail to find the free smokes.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on the complaints of Evans and several others, Arizona
Attorney General Janet Napolitano has demanded an explanation from
R.J. Reynolds and threatened to get a court order to stop the
mailing.
</P>
<P>
   Napolitano accused the tobacco company of violating an agreement
to settle a lawsuit by Arizona and other states for the health care
costs of poor people who smoke. The agreement bans any marketing
that could put cigarettes into the hands of anyone under 21.
</P>
<P>
   She also announced a hotline set up to log complaints from the
public. The number is (602) 542-5763 and, for people living out of
the Phoenix area, toll-free 1-800-352-8431.
</P>
<P>
   R.J. Reynolds representative John Singleton said no cigarettes
should have been mailed to anyone who had not certified in writing
that he was 21 or older. ``What we're being accused of wouldn't
happen under our procedures,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Christensen of the Arizona Department of Health Services
said the state spends about $15 million a year on advertising to
prevent young people from smoking. ``Suddenly, there's this
scheme,'' he said. ``Providing addiction starter kits. This is
really amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   The toddler's mother, whose name was not released by
Napolitano's office, fumed in a complaint to the attorney general.
``Did you know that my 4-year-old was playing with cigarettes?''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Napolitano said other complaints came from people who had quit
smoking for health reasons or were taking medication to end their
nicotine addiction.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona has yet to ratify its $3 billion share of the master
settlement because of a dispute in the state Supreme Court over
claims by Maricopa and other counties for a 32 percent share.
</P>
<P>
   That does not prevent Arizona from seeking a court order to stop
the cigarette mailings as well as seeking a possible civil fine,
Napolitano said. She has demanded a meeting with R.J. Reynolds
officials, as required by the master lawsuit settlement, before
taking court action.
</P>
<P>
   Singleton said R.J. Reynolds will explain the cigarette mailing.
``It is our intention to comply with the letter and the spirit of
the master settlement in every aspect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Napolitano was not so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are thinly disguised efforts to target youth,'' she
said. ``To get kids who may pick them up in the mail first _ to get
them to start smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   The mailings are addressed to specific individuals and contain a
``Dear Smoker'' questionnaire that asks the recipient to respond
after smoking ``enough of the cigarettes to form an opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it means `form an addiction,' '' Napolitano said.
</P>
<P>
   Evans said his 20-year-old son is trying desperately to quit
smoking. ``I can't imagine that these tobacco companies conceive
that it would be OK to send these cigarettes through the mail,'' he
said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mike McCloy may be reached at (602) 444-8111 or at
mike.mccloy(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
