<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THUGS AND GOONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS for changes in 9th, 10th and 11th grafs, bgng: Bruce
Teitelbaum.) 
(jt) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ James Carville is sorry he called the mayor of New
York a thug.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really shouldn't have used that word,'' the Democratic
strategist concedes. ``There is actually a better word: goon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was gonna use bully. And tyrant, but that was too regal, too
much like George III. Mean-spirited? The congressional Republicans
have already stolen that word. So I'm kinda left with goon.''
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Washington's pit bull pitted against New York's pit
bull.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giuliani and I _ that's perfect,'' Carville exults. ``He and I
are at about the same level. Yeah, I'm sort of a political goon.
But I ain't running for Senate. He's a man without any public
compassion and he fights with everybody over everything. It would
be like having me for a senator. It would be a big disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   As he goes after ``the Murdoch/Giuliani crowd,'' the War Room
general who strafed Gennifer Flowers, George Bush, Paula Jones,
Kenneth Starr and Benjamin Netanyahu now has opponents worthy of
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least I don't go pickin' on the lame, the halt and the
blind,'' Carville says. ``Giuliani loves to attack little people.
He enjoys it.''
</P>
<P>
   On ``Meet the Press'' last Sunday, the bald, boisterous one said
he had called Hillary Rodham Clinton's campaign to offer to rant at
Rudy: ``Corporal Cueball is volunteering. I'm going to New York,
I'm setting up committees, and we're going to call it the Committee
to Combat Thuggery, and we're going to take on all these thugs in
the Giuliani campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Teitelbaum, a Giuliani adviser, ripostes: ``I find it
fascinating that we're accused of being negative by the same people
who are calling us thugs.'' He decried ``the imported nasty
tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   Some in the mayor's camp feel the word ``thugs'' was intended to
conjure up the image of an Italian gang. Carville denies any
Godfather-esque implications: ``What else do you call somebody who
jails the homeless at Thanksgiving? The Godfather would have never
jailed 100 homeless people. He would have sent them out some
soup.''
</P>
<P>
   As his ``cueballers'' cheer on Hillary and keep tabs on Rudy, he
will wave a red flag. ``I can be the rodeo clown to Giuliani's
bull, to try to deflect the bull away,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But won't the presence of the ragin' Cajun just enhance the
impression of outsiders descending on Gotham?
</P>
<P>
   ``If Rudy Giuliani can go to Texas and raise money,'' Carville
says, ``we can go to New York and raise Cain.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic barker will not be able to toy with this
righteous prosecutor as he toyed with the last. Ken Starr was naive
and politically inept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every now and then you get a perfect fat pitch you get to
clobber,'' Carville says happily.
</P>
<P>
   In his new book, ``Stickin','' he sums up his method of
vengeful, partisan attack: ``It's hard for somebody to hit you when
you have your fist in their face.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what Mrs. Clinton had done to earn Pat Moynihan's seat,
Carville shot back: ``She's been on the board of directors of
Wal-Mart. How many people have run for the Senate on less than
that?''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about George Stephanopoulos' observation in Newsweek that
Mrs. Clinton can be ``a clumsy tactician prone to
second-guessing,'' Carville agreed. ``She can be a little
hard-headed from time to time.'' But he predicted: ``she's going to
wear very well. I think she's got a really good personality. She's
fun. There are some people who don't like ambitious women and they
ain't going to vote for her. We've lost 'em. Never had 'em. Not
going to get 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   While it has been wonderfully effective, Carville's tactic of
demonizing attackers of the Clintons has a way of preventing
ethical questions from being aired, and allowed Bill Clinton to
evade responsibility for his own bad behavior. When does a
strategist become an enabler?
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably am,'' he replies. ``That is a legitimate
observation. But I ain't going to fall out with anybody but my wife
over sex. And you know what? That son of a ... has always been good
to me. He has always been good to my mother. In the end, by and
large, I think he is a pretty kind guy. And to me, he has never
committed the ultimate sin and that is being gratuitously cruel to
little people and that is what I don't like about Giuliani.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
