A5833 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BOFA--COMPUTERS-SFCHR     12-01 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOFA--COMPUTERS-SFCHRONICLE </SLUG>
  
 Bank Delays Installation of New Computer System  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
In an apparent effort to cut costs, North Carolina's Bank of
America said it has put off installing its own computer and
management systems in its recently acquired California branches
until 2001, as much as a year later than originally planned.
<P>
   Making the switch is one of the last and biggest steps in
combining San Francisco's old BofA and the former NationsBank.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes at a time when BofA is struggling to meet
analysts' earnings estimates. It is carrying out a wide-ranging
program to shed staff and slash expenses, especially in the Bay
Area.
</P>
<P>
   BofA ``is getting very aggressive in trying to get cost
savings,'' said Joseph Morford, an analyst with the brokerage firm
Dain Rauscher Wessels. BofA's cost-cutting program reflects the
tough time the bank seems to be having generating income matching
Wall Street expectations, Morford said.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank acquired roughly 1,000 branches in California when
it bought BofA.
</P>
<P>
   It eventually plans to convert all of these branches into a
``model branch'' system developed by the old NationsBank. The
conversion involves changing the computer, staffing and incentive
pay systems to generate more income from customers.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the computer system would provide information about
customers' banking history that would help employees sell more
products.
</P>
<P>
   The conversion was supposed to be completed in the fall of 2000.
Now BofA says it won't be finished until sometime in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   BofA spokesman Peter Magnani called the postponement ``a prudent
business decision,'' saying it provides more time for staff
training and frees up resources that can be invested elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   BofA employees, who asked not to be identified, said they were
told the postponement of systems conversions seemed to be an effort
to accelerate cost savings and hold off on costly merger
integration expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts project that it will cost more than $1 billion to
convert all the branches of the former BofA to the new system.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only branches in several Southwestern states have been
changed over.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Tejera, an analyst with the Seattle brokerage firm Ragen
MacKenzie, said the delay is ``troublesome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer you postpone it, the longer you postpone the
revenue benefits of the merger,'' Tejera said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say BofA's revenue squeeze is forcing it to scramble to
meet profit expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the bank filed documents with the Securities and
Exchange Commission showing that its third-quarter profit was
boosted by several ununusual items.
</P>
<P>
   Without those items, which were not disclosed when BofA
originally reported earnings in October, the bank would have fallen
short of Wall Street expectations.
</P>
<P>
   BofA's stock has fallen about 9 percent since the disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   In another apparent cost-cutting move, the bank seems to be
handing out pink slips faster and more broadly than originally
expected, employees said.
</P>
<P>
   Several dozen San Francisco finance staff members have lost
their jobs in the past few weeks as corporate financial reporting
operations were closed in the city. Employees estimate that several
hundred Northern California jobs have been eliminated in the past
few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   BofA declined to provide specific information. ``We have said
consistently that there were going to be job reductions both in
California and throughout the system, both merger related and
because the business environment is constantly changing,'' Magnani
said. ``We're not going to quantify the reductions locally.
</P>
<P>
   The bank has said it expects to lay off between 5,000 and 8,000
employees nationwide ut of an original head count of roughly
180,000 when the two banks combined.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
