<HEADER>
A5834 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-GRAVES-MISSING-AZR &LR;      12-01 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAVES-MISSING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG EVILS SHROUD BORDER IN COLD FEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT FLANNERY AND DENNIS WAGNER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (JUAREZ, MEXICO) - As U.S. and Mexican officials began to
unearth corpses here Tuesday, Nov. 30, they also were exhuming a
cold fear buried along the drug-bloodied border.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, people have simply disappeared in this
city of 1.5 million people, suspected casualties of narco violence
and the powerful Carrillo Fuentes cartel. Others have been gunned
down in the streets amid ruthless drug-trafficking wars.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Alonso Aguilar, 33, was one who vanished.
</P>
<P>
   On the afternoon of May 1, 1998, two men dressed in black
fatigues showed up to talk to Aguilar, an auto-body repairman.
Alonso's brother, Roman, says nobody knew whether they were police
or thugs. The gunmen hauled Alonso away in a gray car. His wife and
six children never heard from him again.
</P>
<P>
   `We began to worry because he never came home,'' Roman Alonso
said &UR; Tuesday, Nov. 30, standing outside the massive gates of the
ranch where authorities were digging for bodies. He was circulating
a flier with his brother's picture. ``We don't know why they took
him.''
</P>
<P>
   A few miles away, Mayor Gustavo Elizondo complained that his
city's dark reputation is undeserved and that Juarez is a victim of
drug trafficking by outsiders. ``The Juarez Cartel is made up of
South Americans, some Mexicans, and some bad Americans,'' groused
the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   But local residents say there is no concealing the reality that
blood runs often in the streets of Juarez. Just last week, a man
was gunned down while dining at a popular downtown restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   `They don't know if he was killed over a woman, money or
drugs,'' said ice-cream vendor Salvador Martinez, 43, shrugging his
shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Most of this mayhem is blamed on the Juarez Cartel, among
Mexico's four largest. Amado Carrillo-Fuentes took over the
syndicate in 1992 when kingpin Rafael Aguilar Guajardo, once a
Mexican drug agent, was shot down in Cancun. As the Colombian
cartels faltered under U.S. pressure, Carrillo expanded his power
and political influence.
</P>
<P>
   Among those suspected of taking bribes: former Mexican drug czar
Jesus Gutierrez Rebollo, who was arrested by the Mexican government
in 1997 and sentenced to 32 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Carrillo died in July 1997 of complications from plastic
surgery. Today, the cartel persists under several leaders,
including Amado's brother, Vicente Carrillo, who faces criminal
charges in Mexico and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Many Mexicans, untrusting of authorities and the media, believe
Amado Carrillo lives on, and his death was a ruse. But U.S.
authorities verified the autopsy results, and scientific evidence
was bolstered by a leadership war that ensued. After Carrillo's
death, drug gangsters in Juarez waged a fierce power struggle,
murdering an estimated 60 people.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of such dangers, residents take stoic comfort in the
knowledge that most of the casualties were somehow linked to
trafficking activities.
</P>
<P>
   `You have to get on with life,'' said Nathanael Castillo, 35, a
mechanic who lives and works near the burial ranch. `The ones who
find trouble are usually those who go looking for it.''
</P>
<P>
   `People are used to dead people turning up every day,'' agreed
Martinez. ``I think a lot of families will be waiting now for word
about loved ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Many street poles in Juarez have crosses painted on them to
commemorate what locals call ``los desaparecidos.'' The loss of
loved ones left friends and relatives scarred, and the discovery of
mass graves has re-opened those wounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is terrible,'' said Jaime Hervella, co-director of the El
Paso-based Relatives of Disappeared Persons. Hervella has a list of
196 people whose whereabouts are unknown. Among them is his godson,
a U.S. Navy veteran and communications expert whose technology
helped Mexican authorities capture drug shipments.
</P>
<P>
   The missing are not just drug traffickers and informants, but a
cross-section of U.S. and Mexican citizens. Hervella said it is
unclear why some people get kidnapped, and it is even more
uncertain what becomes of them. In many cases, however, witnesses
reported that the body snatchers were dressed as police or
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The El Paso organization pressured the Mexican government into
assigning four special prosecutors in the past three years - none
of whom unraveled the mystery.
</P>
<P>
   If some of the victims are discovered in a mass burial, Hervella
said, it will bring the anguish of finality. ``Up 'til now, we all
had hope that our loved ones would be found in military jails,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, federal agents in Arizona say they've never seen a
comparable homicide spree along the Sonoran border. There are
scores of drug-related murders here each year, but the closest
parallel occurred in 1989 when 13 murder victims were found in a
well outside of Agua Prieta, across the border from Douglas. Jim
Molesa, DEA spokesman in Phoenix, said those killings were
attributed to Hector Fragoso Burgueno, the leader of a
marijuana-smuggling syndicate. Fragoso also was implicated that
year in the slaughter of five men in a Tucson shed. Molesa said he
was arrested by U.S. authorities and extradited to Mexico for
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona authorities say early reports from Juarez also are
surprising because many victims purportedly were government
informants.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Hall, an FBI special agent in Phoenix, said no bureau sources
have been murdered in Arizona during the recent past. Molesa said
one DEA informant was gunned down in Tucson this year by drug
gangsters, but that case did not involve Mexican syndicates.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Molesa said, U.S. law officers are finding it
increasingly difficult to operate in Mexico because of fear and
corruption. Just last week, a pair of agents from the DEA and FBI
were held at gunpoint by a dozen men - including some wearing
Tamaluipas state police uniforms - near Matamoros.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen reportedly wanted to kidnap a suspected informant who
was with the agents. Molesa said one of the assailants, suspected
narco-trafficker Oziel Cardenas Guillen, threatened the agents
saying, `This is my country, my territory. I control it here. You
don't. So get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Molesa said revelations in Juarez suggest that the organization
there was very sloppy, or hellbent on sending ``a distinct
message'' to rivals and snitches. The latter explanation is more
likely, he added.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
