<HEADER>
A5836 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-ONLINE--BUSINSSES-SFC     12-01 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE--BUSINSSES-SFCHRONICLE </SLUG>
  
 New services help small businesses get online  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR; T om Johnson, an avid collector of Franciscan pottery and an
eBay buyer and seller, started his own online business in San
Francisco last year to sell antiques, fine art and collectibles.
<P>
   Rather than buy and sell their own wares, Johnson and his
partner in Michigan elected to display stuff owned by others and
take a 2 percent to 10 percent commission of the sales price.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Ruby Lane ( &LR; www.rubylane.com &LR; ) has about 20,000 items for
sale at any time from more than 200 individuals and dealers and
generates more than $10,000 a month in revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Getting online is becoming more of a necessity for the 20
million U.S. small businesses that account for nearly half of all
employment and a third of economic output. According to recent
surveys, nearly a quarter of all U.S. households bought something
over the Internet during the past year and online sales are
projected to mushroom from $20billion this year to $184 billion in
five years.
</P>
<P>
   About a third of small businesses have a Web presence, compared
with 19 percent a year ago, and 71 percent of those who sell online
view the Internet as ``essential'' to their development.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the optimism, more than 40 percent of small businesses
say they have neither the staff nor the time to maintain a Web
site, according to Prodigy Communications Corp. And the smaller the
company, the greater the problem. Only 1 in 4 companies with fewer
than 10 employees has an Internet presence.
</P>
<P>
   Although Johnson and his partner both worked in computers and
high-tech consulting, they found that to make their virtual gallery
a success, they needed some sophisticated online services.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, a growing number of large companies like Microsoft,
Yahoo! &LR;  and IBM, and Internet startups have created Web portals to
meet the needs of small and growing businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is partial to an online marketing and management product
called ClickTrade created by San Francisco's Link Exchange. As a
sign of the company's strategic promise, it was acquired for
$265million a year ago by Microsoft and is now the center of
Microsoft's bCentral suite of services for online businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ClickTrade helps businesses drive traffic to their Web sites by
setting up affiliate networks with other sites. Ruby Lane, for
example, uses it to pay more than 1,100 partners a 3-cent to
10-cent commission for every person who clicks on Ruby Lane's link
from their site. On top of that, it pays 30 percent of the total
commissions to bCentral to handle the cumbersome chores of sending
affiliates their commission checks and providing detailed reports
of all the online activity.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson figures the service is well worth it. ``For every $100
we spend, we get more than $200 in revenues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Launched in mid-October, Microsoft's bCentral helps businesses
in three key areas: getting started online by connecting to the Web
and building a Web site, promoting and marketing online, and
managing more effectively.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is hardly alone in storming the business-to-business
(B2B) market. AOL, Citibank, Excite, IBM, Intuit, Yahoo and others
have started online portals to connect to businesses. A growing
number of local companies including Bigstep.com, eCongo.com and
Freemerchant.com are even offering businesses free services to
create a Web site, set up a virtual store, market and manage it,
and track the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the Oklahoma land rush,'' said small-business
analyst Raymond Boggs of IDC in Framingham, Mass. ``Established
companies and new ones like DigitalWork.com, Encanto Networks and
SmartAge are all getting into the B2B space.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for small businesses is figuring out what they
need and paying for only the options they need. That can be
daunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's equivalent to 1905, when there were about 200
automakers,'' said Boggs. ``You could wait about 15 years until you
have a Big 3.'' But he recommends finding a service provider you
feel comfortable with and making the leap. ``Even if you pick the
wrong one, it will probably put you in better shape than not
picking anyone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, many small businesses remain skeptical. One of the
problems is the ``fear factor,'' according to Microsoft bCentral
Group Product Manager Jon Elvekrog. In addition, he noted,
``Business information is scattered across the Web, and a lot of
sites offer static information. For example, they give you
information about how to run an ad campaign rather than tools to
let you just do it.''
</P>
<P>
   To help businesses get started online, bCentral offers Internet
access from $21.95 to $80 a month (depending on the speed), domain
name registration for $35 a year and, coming soon, Web site
building and hosting services with prices starting at $19.95 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   BCentral's marketing services come in packages for $19.99 a
month to $599 a year. Offerings also are available a la carte:
</P>
<P>
   Web site listings on up to 400 search engines for $59.
</P>
<P>
   Affordable ads for as little as $100 on leading Web sites such
as Yahoo and MSN.com.
</P>
<P>
   Free ad exchanges with 450,000 other business Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Affiliate program in which a business pays a fee to other Web
sites that send it customers.
</P>
<P>
   BCentral also offers services to help small businesses manage
their online operations: shopping for office supplies, comparing
shipping rates, booking business travel and checking customers'
credit.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Amy Ossenbruggen, who recently started the Amy Oh Designs
jewelry business in San Francisco, is a fan of several bCentral
online tools, including ClickTrade, Banner Network to swap ads with
other online sites and ListBot to build an online customer mailing
list. The services ``are useful in building clientele and keeping
in touch with your customers,'' Ossenbruggen said.
</P>
<P>
   But another San Francisco merchant has yet to commit. Pete
Mulvihill, general manager of Green Apple Books and Music on
Clement Street, said he was approached by Microsoft and is
intrigued by it bCentral services.
</P>
<P>
   But he is uncertain just which bCentral plan to buy. With 20,000
used books in inventory, he figures bCentral's most basic plan is
insufficient and its most expensive plan may be more than he needs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
