r e BC-TV-GOODY-AZR &LR;      12-01 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE AS CAPT. KIRK? IT'S
 `ULTIMATE TREK'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ 
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  (UNDATED) - It would be easy to
dismiss Ultimate Trek: Star Trek's Greatest Moments as a show that
appeals only to hard-core fans of the series.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But what's the point? That's true of all Star Trek shows from
the original to the ensuing knockoffs. Trekkies love all things
Trek; the rest of us scratch our heads and wonder whether a pocket
protector is really a necessary fashion accessory.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, there have been some strong television moments in the
four series. And the goal of Ultimate Trek is to dole those out in
easy-to-digest snippets: ``Ultimate Time-Travel Moments,''
``Ultimate Vil lains,'' ``Ultimate One-Liners,'' that kind of
thing.
</P>
<P>
   As a concept, it's rather spotty. If you buy into the whole Star
Trek universe, it's a show that demands your attention for an
entire hour. Whatever merits any of the series have, limited though
they may be, are lost in the cut-and-paste format.
</P>
<P>
   But Ultimate Trek is still worth watching even if you don't know
that Tiberius is James Kirk's middle name, and the reason is
simple: Jason Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   If you loved Alexander as George Costanza on Seinfeld, wait till
you catch him as Capt. Kirk. He appears as the captain of the
Enterprise during bits that set up the clips - something about how
a Y2K bug will destroy the Star Trek signal, a development he and
Spock and Dr. McCoy must prevent.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the specious plot. Just sit back and enjoy Alexander, who
has William Shatner's bizarre acting mannerisms down cold. The
goofy toupee and the too-tight shirt are just gravy.
</P>
<P>
   Gravy for the viewer, that is. Al exander said seeing himself
squeezed into the captain's outfit made a lasting impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I not only started a crash diet, I'm seriously considering
plastic surgery, liposuction, whatever it takes,'' he said in a
conference call last week.
</P>
<P>
   Don't think for a moment that Alexander is ridiculing Shatner in
his hilarious performance. Quite the contrary. As anyone who has
heard him on Howard Stern's radio show can attest, Alexander, who
once appeared in an episode of Star Trek: Voyager, is a
full-fledged Trekkie.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the original series goes and the films go, I'm damn
near an authority,'' he said. ``It would frighten you how much I
know about it. Because it certainly fright ens me.''
</P>
<P>
   To hear Alexander tell it, Shatner is a major reason for his
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even want to be an actor,'' he said. ``I just wanted
to captain the Enterprise. I thought that was a wonderful career
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   One he now has achieved. Seriously, though, he loves Shatner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really, by and large, Shat ner's performance that took
these ridiculous production situations and turned them into rather
compelling stories,'' Alexander said. ``He was so invested in the
importance - the universal importance - of that stuff that it
really made it very, very exciting work.''
</P>
<P>
   If he sounds like a Frenchman talking about Jerry Lewis, you
should hear Alexander rave about why the show remains popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Trek really does its home work as far as its science
goes and its commitment to pulling off effects and pulling off the
creation of the physical world of the future,'' he said. ``I think
true, die-hard science-fiction fans like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always has a sense of humor about itself. It's also always
had a sense of not importance as much as a mission, in a way. All
the series have tried to tackle issues that are relevant to all of
us and to do it in a way that encompasses this entertainment. And
because they're able to abstract it into this future world, it
seems to have very little threat to a viewer.''
</P>
<P>
   Whew. Fan. Big fan. So much so that Alexander contends that his
acting is full of Shatner's quirks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ever see me do stage work or some of my more dramatic
work, you will actually notice that I have inherited that sort of
halting, search ing, staccato rhythm of Shatner from time to
time,'' Alexander said, ``his emphasis on unusual parts of any
given line of dialogue. . . . Not the larger-than-life movements
that he does but some of the smaller tics, I actually sort of
picked up. I have to concentrate not to do them.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he has played his dream role, perhaps Alexander can
answer the ultimate Star Trek question: What accounts for pudgy
Capt. Kirk's status as an interspecies babe magnet?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a great line in one of the Batman films where a girl
is coming on to Batman and he says, `It must be the car. Chicks
love the car.' It might be true of the ship. He's got a pretty
impressive ship there that he's totally in charge of.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be the sense of command. . . . It could be he's got
that little phaser thing on the hip. It could be the flying double
drop-kick. I don't know. It may be just all in his attitude. But
whatever it is, it sure as hell is working.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, it fails to work for Alexander's Kirk during an Ultimate
Trek bit, one that contains the best moment of the show. When Kirk,
Spock and McCoy see Borg Lingerie, they naturally assume it's a
shop run by the evil Borg. Rushing inside, they are instead greeted
by several beauti ful women wearing bras and panties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Has it been seven years already?'' the Spock character asks,
and that tells you all you need to know. If you get that joke,
you'll love Ultimate Trek. If you don't, you'll wonder what all the
fuss is over.
</P>
<P>
   Again. Reach Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8974 or at bill.goody
koontz &LR; pni.com via e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
