<HEADER>
A5838 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-CELEBRATE-AZR &LR;      12-01 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELEBRATE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAXPAYERS TO GET LESS BANG FOR MORE BUCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - Phoenix taxpayers may foot much of the $1.5 million
tab for the city's downtown New Year's Eve bash.
</P>
<P>
   And they'll get less bang for their buck.
</P>
<P>
   With a month to go, Phoenix Celebration 2000 was dramatically
scaled back because corporate sponsors were reluctant to kick in
money.
</P>
<P>
   The party's planning committee also has met behind closed doors
since July, skirting the Arizona Open Meeting Law, even though it's
spending $525,000 of city money.
</P>
<P>
   Despite two years of planning, the glitches are not altogether
unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city said it wanted a millennium event that would be very
big scale, that would be affordable to virtually everyone in the
city, and that's a tough thing to pull off,'' said Grant Woods,
chairman of the party's planning committee, Citizens for the
Community Celebration Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The New Year's Eve party will feature 34 bands, including the
Gin Blossoms, Three Dog Night and Waylon Jennings, on three stages
in downtown Phoenix. Tickets are $10 in advance and $15 on the day
of the show.
</P>
<P>
   But the event originally was a much grander affair. Six stages
were to feature a variety of acts from the decades of the 1940s and
on.
</P>
<P>
   All that changed in early September when it became clear that
corporate sponsors weren't kicking in the money to defray the
original cost estimate of $2.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became apparent that somewhere, somehow they were going to
have to pare down the number of acts, the physical size and the
special effects,'' said Mike Whiting, a city administrator in
charge of the celebration.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, Nov. 29, the committee had raised $245,000, a far
cry from the $2 million originally planned.
</P>
<P>
   With the downscaled event came contracts that the committee
suddenly couldn't afford to honor. But in doing so, the committee
and city staff angered the agents that had lined up 15 entertainers
that were canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they said they were canceling the contracts, I told them
they couldn't do that,'' said Charlie Johnston, who, as owner of
Select Artists Associates and a committee member, had negotiated
for the acts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Grant (Woods), `You're going to get a lot of lawsuits.'
''
</P>
<P>
   He was right. Two weeks after they were canceled, the talent
agency representing three bands fired off a terse letter to Phoenix
Mayor Skip Rimsza, demanding that its $100,000 contract be honored.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent letters from the William Morris Agency made it clear
that it would sue to get its money. The city later caved in, and
the bands will perform as part of the Celebration 2000 party.
</P>
<P>
   The flap prompted Johnston, a volunteer on the original panel
and its successor, to resign and demand that his name be taken off
all the committee's bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I`ve been in business for 34 years. My credibility was on the
line. It was a devasting experience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston also wasn't happy with the way the committee's
accounting was handled.
</P>
<P>
   City records indicate that the committee filed its articles of
incorporation as a non-profit, tax-exempt entity with the Arizona
Corporation Commission in April. In mid-June, the city gave the
committee a $25,000 grant as seed money.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, the city lent the committee $500,000 with the
stipulation that $100,000 be repaid before the Celebration 2000
party.
</P>
<P>
   But those transfers took place before the city had officially
contracted with the committee to host the party.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston said he wasn't comfortable with the financial setup.
</P>
<P>
   It also is unclear whether the committee will be able to repay
the balance of the $500,000 loan.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent budget for the event puts the party's costs at
nearly $1.5 million, with more than $824,000 going to the artists,
accommodations and booking agents.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what the committee plans to do in the case of a shortfall,
the city's Whiting said, ``I prefer to just think we're going to be
very successful.''
</P>
<P>
   But Woods had a different answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the city will pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the party makes or loses money depends, in large part,
on how many people show up for it.
</P>
<P>
   The panel estimates 115,000 people will attend, which may be
overly optimistic for a first-time event. Across town, organizers
of the Tempe Block Party are expecting 150,000 for its 15th annual
bash.
</P>
<P>
   But organizers of both events admit that estimating crowds this
year is tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a one-time event, and we haven't done it before,''
Whiting said. ``But I think our estimates are very conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   The city plans to sponsor a New Year's Eve bash next year for
what purists would call the real turn of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   But Woods has a suggestion if the city decides to go ahead with
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``My advice for the next year is to reverse roles and have city
staff run the operation with input from a volunteer committee,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Doing so would mean the city would have to request bids from
contractors and meet in public under the public open meetings law.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll just have to do that,'' Woods said. ``It's too
difficult to do something this big (by) depending on volunteers.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kerry Fehr-Snyder can be reached at (602) 444-8975 or at
kerry.fehr-snyder(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
