<HEADLINE>
POLLUTION ALERT IS ON FOR THE PHOENIX AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY JO PITZL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - For the first time in four years, Phoenix area
pollution levels for carbon monoxide violated federal health
standards on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The violation triggered a high-pollution alert that will last
through at least 10 a.m. today, Dec. 1. If a second reading above
federal health standards is recorded this year, Phoenix's hopes of
shedding its ``serious'' label for carbon monoxide will be at risk.
</P>
<P>
   The spike in pollution readings at a west-central Phoenix site
surprised and perplexed air-quality officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very sharp peak,'' said Jo Crumbaker, air-quality
manager for Maricopa County's Environmental Services Department.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, carbon monoxide levels build gradually, fueled by
vehicle exhaust trapped in stagnant air. But Monday's, Nov. 29,
midday reading of 6.8 parts per million had jumped to 9.9 ppm by 11
p.m. and peaked at 10.5 ppm by 1 a.m. Tuesday, Nov. 30. Readings
exceeding 9 ppm are unhealthful, according to the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The high readings were recorded by a pollution monitor near the
intersection of Grand Avenue, Thomas Road and 27th Avenue. Because
the two high readings occurred within the same time frame, they
count as one violation.
</P>
<P>
   Crumbaker said county environmental officials don't know why the
carbon monoxide readings jumped so far, so fast. A quick check
Tuesday, Nov. 30, showed the monitor was working properly.
</P>
<P>
   A second round of high readings likely would doom attempts to
get the EPA to reclassify the Phoenix area's carbon monoxide levels
and declare them in compliance with health standards.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix area also is rated ``serious'' for ozone and
particulate pollution, and prospects for complying with federal
standards are dim. In November, the EPA said it would impose limits
on new or expanding businesses by March unless the Phoenix could
come up with a sufficient plan to fight particulate pollution. By
September, Arizona could face the loss of federal
highway-construction funds if a plan is not in place.
</P>
<P>
   During the high-pollution advisory, Phoenix area residents are
asked to reduce their driving and to use transit, carpool or
combine their trips. A ban on wood-burning fireplaces also is in
effect, except for those homes with EPA-approved wood stoves and
fireplace inserts. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mary Jo Pitzl can be reached at (602) 444-8963 or at
maryjo.pitzl(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-99 0016EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
