<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-WIZARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS COLLAPSE, LOSE TO WIZARDS, 85-78 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Nets lost a 15-point lead in the
third quarter, they lost their offense in the closing minutes, and
they lost another disheartening game. Failing to score for more
than five minutes down the stretch, the woeful Nets (2-13) were
beaten by the Washington Wizards, 85-78, Tuesday night at
Continental Arena. It was the Nets' 10th loss in their last 11
games, and this defeat was more painful because they actually
controlled play for most of the game, before scoring just 11 points
in the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   With the game hanging in the balance, the Nets collapsed. After
a tip-in by Jamie Feick gave the Nets a 77-73 lead with 5 minutes
53 seconds to play, they never scored another field goal. Every
Nets player in the game faltered down the stretch, from Keith Van
Horn, who had a game-high 24 points but missed a crucial jumper, to
Stephon Marbury (14 points), who had two turnovers and missed a
3-pointer during the final four minutes. As the Nets looked at each
other and waited for someone to step forward, nobody did. The
Wizards (5-10) are one of the two teams the Nets have beaten this
season, but the Nets found still another way to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Washington took its first lead since the first quarter on a
3-point play by Juwan Howard (23 points) as he made a layup while
being fouled by Johnny Newman with 4:25 left. Howard added the free
throw to put the Wizards ahead, 78-77, and one could sense the Nets
wilting.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hamilton (14 points), a rookie from the University of
Connecticut, followed with a key 3-pointer that gave Washington an
81-77 lead with 2:39 left. After both teams missed shots, Feick (15
points, 16 rebounds) made one of two free throws to cut
Washington's lead to 81-78 with 48.1 seconds left, but New Jersey
scored no more.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Williams provided the final dagger when he made a
sensational over-the-shoulder tip-in of an air ball by Tracy
Murray; it gave the Wizards an 83-78 lead with 24.9 seconds to
play. The Nets called a timeout and huddled dejectedly around their
beleaguered head coach, Don Casey, but it was another night when
neither Casey nor his players had answers.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets led by 67-52 late in the third quarter, but Washington
closed within 67-59 by the start of the fourth quarter, setting the
stage for its come-from-behind victory.
</P>
<P>
   Playing one of their strongest halves of the season, the Nets
controlled play and led, 49-35. There were two keys for the Nets:
the return of Kerry Kittles, and the return of Van Horn's jump
shot.
</P>
<P>
   In only his second game this season, and his first game since
Nov. 15, Kittles tested his sore right knee and looked as if he had
hardly been away. Kittles started at shooting guard, made his first
two shots and contributed 8 first-half points in 18 solid minutes.
Though he wore a protective wrap on his knee, Kittles ran without a
limp, moved well and elevated strongly on his shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had a lot of practice time, but I have to go out and
see what I can do,'' Kittles said before the game. ``This is like
my everything _ my practice, my training camp, my preseason. The
difference is, these are real games.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kittles finished the game with those same 8 points in 33
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn broke a shooting slump to lead all first-half scorers
with 16 points but finished 7 for 20.
</P>
<P>
   And the Nets' injury woes continued. Their starting center, Jim
McIlvaine, bruised his back in a hard first-quarter fall and did
not return. The backup guard Lucious Harris (stomach flu) was also
forced to leave in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   When the second half began, the Nets had just nine available
players. The injured Jayson Williams, Kendall Gill and Scott
Burrell were on the bench in street clothes, and Casey wondered
what else could go wrong. ``Am I paying for past sins?'' Casey said
as he passed the scorer's table before the second half.
</P>
</TEXT>
