<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5851 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-BRICK-ATTACK-450&AMP;A     12-01 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRICK-ATTACK-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC POLICE CHARGE PANHANDLER IN BRICK ATTACK ON WOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.:: The following is an added starter on Page 1 of The N.Y.
Times)  
 (bl)  
 By JUAN FORERO and JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A panhandler with a criminal record that stretches
back nearly two decades was arrested Tuesday and charged with
attempted murder in the Nov. 16 brick attack of a young woman on a
midtown Manhattan street after a witness to the assault identified
him in a lineup, police officials said Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The man, identified by police as Paris Drake, 31, was charged
with attempted murder in the second-degree, assault and weapons
possession in the attack, which left Nicole Barrett, a 27-year-old
office worker, with a critical head injury that required two
operations at Bellevue Hospital Center. Drake was expected to be
arraigned Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir announced the arrest late
Tuesday night at the Midtown South police precinct on West 35th
Street, where he heralded the work of detectives and said he had
told the Barrett family of the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stopped and saw the Barrett family before coming here,''
Safir said. ``I'm not going to tell you what they said, but you can
probably guess that they were relieved.''
</P>
<P>
   The highly publicized attack immediately led to speculation by
police that a person who was homeless and possibly mentally ill was
responsible, and three days later Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's
administration announced that the homeless had no right to sleep on
city streets and would face arrest for refusing shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Although police arrested more than 100 homeless people since the
measure was announced, city officials said Tuesday that it was not
clear if Drake was homeless, nor was there any indication that he
had a history of mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   Olga Beck, a spokeswoman for the city's Department of Homeless
Services, checked the department's computer data base and said
there was no record that Drake had ever been in the city's homeless
shelter system.
</P>
<P>
   Drake became a prime suspect when an inmate on Rikers Island
told the authorities that Drake, who had been arrested Nov. 23 on a
low-level drug charge and was being held on Rikers, bragged about
the attack to the inmate, said law enforcement officials. The
inmate was released into the custody of detectives, who drove him
around midtown Monday until he spotted Drake at the Port Authority
Bus Terminal and pointed him out, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Drake underwent hours of questioning by detectives, police
officials said, and did not confess to the crime. But Tuesday, law
enforcement officials said one of several witnesses to the attack
brought in for a police lineup positively identified Drake as Ms.
Barrett's assailant. Investigators also believed that Drake closely
resembled the sketch of the suspect that was made public after the
attack.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Monday, after Drake was first detained, however, prosecutors
from the Manhattan district attorney's Office were hesitant about
the police case because no one had positively identified Drake as
the assailant, said one law enforcement official. Early Tuesday,
prosecutors remained reluctant to file charges, the official said,
but then Drake was identified in the lineup and an assistant
district attorney arrived at the precinct to review evidence and
found it in order.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials also said Drake, with his long
criminal record, fit the profile of a violent and dangerous
criminal. First arrested in 1982, when he was 14, Drake would be
arrested nearly 21 more times, mostly on drug-related charges. He
has spent more than seven of the last 10 years in state prisons on
charges ranging from drug dealing to assaulting a prison guard.
Officials said that on every occasion, Drake's requests for early
parole were denied and he served the maximum sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a guy that the parole board wanted to keep in. Every
opportunity it had, the parole board held him,'' said Tom Grant,
spokesman for the New York State Division of Parole. ``They had a
pretty good beat on him. It looks like he didn't do well in a
corrections setting.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Drake did find his way onto the street. This year, Drake _
after a finishing a prison term in upstate New York _ was arrested
at least twice on low-level drug charges, according to two law
enforcement officials. The latest arrest came Nov. 23, just six
days after the attack on Ms. Barrett, when Drake was sent to Rikers
on the drug charge. ``He has been a career criminal. He has a rap
sheet pages long,'' said a law enforcement official familiar with
Drake's record.
</P>
<P>
   Safir reiterated his criticism of the criminal justice system
Tuesday night, alluding to the fact that Drake had committed a
crime while on parole in the past. Drake was not on parole when Ms.
Barrett was attacked, however. ``You have to wonder about the
criminal justice system when someone like this is out on the
streets,'' said Safir, who has called for parole to be abolished.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Drake used a paving stone to bash Ms. Barrett from
behind as she prepared to cross Madison Avenue at 42nd Street, an
unprovoked assault that reminded New Yorkers that despite the drop
in crime in recent years, random violence can easily shatter
perceptions of a safe city. The attack also cast a public eye on
the issue of mentally unstable homeless people because officials
initially believed the attacker was homeless, like several other
mentally disturbed people who in recent years have committed random
violent crimes that have brought attention to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barrrett was admitted to Bellevue Hospital Center in
critical condition and underwent two operations to relieve the
pressure on her brain caused by a skull fracture she suffered. The
young woman, who received flowers and cards from hundreds of
well-wishers and was visited by Giuliani and Safir, has since been
moved out of the intensive care unit and is now alert and able to
talk with her family.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
