L.A. POLICE COMMISSION OKs AMMO SALES BAN 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Beth Barrett  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Police Commission has narrowly
recommended banning the sale of live ammunition within the city.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-2 vote Tuesday on what would be one of the most sweeping
bans in the country sends the issue to the City Council's Public
Safety Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The measure allows the sale of ammunition only to active and
retired peace officers and military personnel for official duties
as well as at firing ranges where all the bullets would have to be
consumed. Antique ammunition and blank ammunition also would be
exempted under the provision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is broad-based,'' said Assistant City Attorney Henry
Morris.
</P>
<P>
   The commission delayed consideration of an alternate plan that
would have set up a permit system to buy and sell ammunition until
the staffing implications can be further studied.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the ban, including parents who had lost children
to gun violence, said it was a step toward further reducing crime
in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Theo Milonopoulos, 12, of Studio City, about 11 miles northwest
of downtown Los Angeles, has been a youth leader in the
anti-violence movement since the 1997 North Hollywood bank robbery
shootout near his neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we feel as though we've given a voice to all the kids
in the city,'' Milonopoulos said. ``We all need to stand up for the
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Dean Hansell initially hesitated to move forward on
the recommendation, citing state laws that could leave the city
open to legal challenges. California Attorney General Bill Lockyer
has been asked to review a previous ruling that the state preempts
local governments in regulating the sale of ammunition. Hansell
voted with the majority after commissioners said the council
committee was ready to move ahead on the proposal. Hansell was
joined by commission president Gerald L. Chaleff and commissioner
T. Warren Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Chaleff said that while he remained concerned how effective such
a ban would be in light of nearby cities continuing to sell
ammunition, he was persuaded L.A. needs to start somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes making a statement is enough,'' Chaleff said.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioners Herbert F. Boeckmann and Raquelle de la Rocha
dissented.
</P>
<P>
   Boeckmann said the commission should not rush to put in place a
``quick fix'' that might not work, saying the focus on gun violence
should be on the perpetrators of criminal acts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is totally the wrong way to go about this, it goes
against our rights,'' Boeckmann said.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rocha said a complete ban would be ``too extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   National Rifle Association of America officials said the city
was trying to end-run state laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this was any other civil right, but guns, the city would
never dream of doing this,'' said Attorney Chuck Michel, who
equated the measure with trying to ban abortions by banning medical
instruments. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-99 0102EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991201.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
