<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5875 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-UH-SEARCH-HNS &LR;      12-01 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UH-SEARCH </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY WIZIG  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
In the best of all college football worlds, the University of
Houston's current search for a new football coach would conclude in
about 10 days with the hiring of the next Bill Yeoman.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember, however, that Yeoman's qualities _ burnished first on
Earl Blaik's Army staff that also included Vince Lombardi, then
honed by Duffy Daugherty at Michigan State _ were not readily
apparent in wins and losses after Yeoman's arrival at UH. In fact,
Yeoman and the athletic director who hired him, the late Harry
Fouke, were both hung in effigy during 2-8 and 2-6-1 campaigns in
Yeoman's second and third seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The next hire will be the Cougars' ninth since the program began
in 1946, not a high rate of turnover but one that is skewed by
Yeoman's 25 seasons. These days, no coach, unless he is named
Paterno or Bowden (Bobby, that is) sticks around for that number of
heartaches and highs.
</P>
<P>
   One important part of the decision that faces UH athletic
director Chet Gladchuk is picking a coach who not only can
reinvigorate the school's mostly lethargic alumni (and others who
might buy season tickets or contribute financially) but also would
not leave shortly after the job looks like it is on the way to
getting done.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, legal ways such as buyout penalties to
guard against that, but even that method is not foolproof, as
Tulane discovered a year ago when Clemson was convinced Tommy
Bowden was its man.
</P>
<P>
   So it is that current Oklahoma State assistant head coach Tommy
Kaiser likely would fulfill the loyalty quotient as a UH alumnus
(he played football and baseball) and former assistant coach. He
also understands the high school recruiting environment in Texas as
well as UH's place in the city's congested sports environment.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser has made it clear he is interested in the position.
Whether that interest is mutual is hard to tell. Gladchuk says he
has had many inquiries _ ``some of them surprising'' _ since the
Nov. 21 dismissal of Kim Helton, whose seven seasons and 24 wins do
not begin to tell the full story via won-lost percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser's name joins a number of others that have surfaced since
the job came open. Former Auburn coach Terry Bowden, one of the
most widely rumored, is also one of the most interesting. But he
recently signed an extension with ABC to remain in the TV studio,
and there probably would be higher-profile, higher-paying
opportunities than UH in the future if Bowden really wants to
return to the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Former Texas coach John Mackovic, also in the TV analyst's chair
these days, is not interested.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Rodriguez, currently Tommy Bowden's offensive coordinator
at Clemson and before that at Tulane, seems qualified to be a
Division I-A head coach, and a highly successful one at that.
Rodriguez was an interim head coach at Tulane and impressed with
his skill at that job until he was surprisingly bypassed when
Bowden's old job was filled.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say Rodriguez is expected to be the next coach at Texas
Tech, possibly as early as Dec. 7, the first day the position could
be filled under state employment guidelines. Rodriguez interviewed
with Tech officials once, then returned to Lubbock with his wife
last Friday to consider a new house.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma offensive coordinator Mike Leach, who formerly tutored
quarterback Tim Couch at Kentucky, also interviewed at Tech but has
been noncommittal about other positions while the Sooners prepare
for a bowl. His interest in UH, if any, is hard to gauge.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who insist that Jack Pardee, the former Cougars
and Houston Oilers head coach, is ready to step away from his
current life on the ranch and into the film room again. Pardee, for
all his immense pro and collegiate experience, may not fully
realize the task at hand.
</P>
<P>
   One current Division I-A head coach whose name has surfaced at
UH and North Carolina State is Louisiana Tech's Jack Bicknell III,
whose first season with the Bulldogs produced an 8-3 record.
Louisiana Tech quarterback Tim Rattay had run-and-shoot-type
passing figures in the kind of offensive system that might entice
paying customers to UH's Robertson Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Bicknell's father, Jack Bicknell, coached Doug Flutie at Boston
College and against Yeoman's Cougars in the 1985 Cotton Bowl.
Gladchuk was the AD at Boston College before he came to UH and
after the elder Bicknell had left BC. The hiring of the son would
make for a nice story line, but the young Bicknell just completed
the first year of a five-year contract. Associates say he is happy
in Ruston, La., where Tech faces the tough prospect of one more
season as an independent before joining the Western Athletic
Conference in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   UH's reported commitment to significantly increase the $300,000
annual financial package paid to Helton, perhaps to as much as
$500,000, might sway Bicknell. It seemingly will not do so with
Rodriguez, who could expect to receive that much, or slightly more,
at Tech as Spike Dykes' successor.
</P>
<P>
   Gladchuk says head coaching experience at the Division I-Alevel
``would be another feather in the cap'' for candidates but not
necessarily decisive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not precluding anyone,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Gladchuk's vision of the new man includes one who understands
the Cougars' past accomplishments and tradition; can build
relationships with Texas high school coaches; can excite alumni and
embrace UH fans; brings a knowledge of the technical aspects of the
game; and, perhaps most important, is able to lead the program.
</P>
<P>
   All things considered, it sounds like another Yeoman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
