<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5876 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     12-01 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRAN BLINEBURY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
PHOENIX _ Out of the frying pan and into the microwave.
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the anger-filled intensity of Canada's boorish reception to
the trapdoor welcome mat Jason Kidd will have rolled out in the
desert, Steve Francis just moves on to the next hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   Next up: The Kid vs. Kidd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man,'' said the Rockets rookie as he relaxed wearing his fancy
print boxer shorts and a broad smile, ``it doesn't ever get any
easier in the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a lot of ways, it doesn't get much harder, either.
</P>
<P>
   As his career unfolds over the next decade, there will surely
not be many nights like Monday, when he was treated slightly better
than an ax murderer by a Vancouver crowd that for a while had a lot
of good, clean, pumped-up fun and then eventually stepped over the
line. Way over.
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing to wave signs that mocked him and to chant his
name in a singsong voice, but quite another to toss lemons and
tomatoes and change onto the court. You see, it's a simple
boundary, really, and maybe the Canadians will eventually learn it
if one of their teams sticks around long enough to finally make the
playoffs: You keep the produce in the refrigerator and the loose
change in your pocket.
</P>
<P>
   And while it is acceptable to taunt Francis for acting _ in
their eyes _ like a spoiled brat who rejected their team and their
entire frozen way of life, it is way beyond any standard of good
taste to bring members of his family into the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothered me that some of the people near our bench were
yelling things about my grandmother and about my mom being dead,''
Francis said. ``That really shocked me.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet he never let that show. Instead he showed them.
</P>
<P>
   If several years down the line Francis blossoms into the
superstar the Rockets believe he'll become, that first night in
front of the raucous crowd inside General Motors Place might be
viewed as a pivotal point in his development.
</P>
<P>
   Because for all the emotions churning inside him, he never let
them boil over into his job. This truly was the best we have seen
of Francis to date. He was explosive and yet under control. He was
the star soloist of the show and yet kept his place within the
Rockets' orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   For all the gaudy numbers he carried with him through customs
and out of Canada _ 24 points, 10 assists and nine rebounds _ the
most impressive was the zero in the turnover department.
</P>
<P>
   Francis ran the fast break when he could but for the first time
this year never ran ahead of himself or his teammates. He didn't
try to force the spectacular pass but fed the other Rockets a
steady diet of opportunities for good shots.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared, in a way, the rowdy atmosphere worked to his
benefit. It made him concentrate harder, focus his attention more
directly on the task at hand while he blocked out the distractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I think it helped,'' Francis said. ``I knew that if I
got caught up in all of the stuff, then it was going to spread to
the whole team. The coach told me to just stay into the game. And I
called my grandmother in the afternoon, and she told me the same
thing. She said it was going to be bad. But I didn't know how bad.
It was a lot worse than anything I've ever experienced before at
any level.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet there he was throughout the night, bouncing around like a
kindergartner at recess, grinning and laughing and letting his
former University of Maryland teammate Obinna Ekezie know all about
it after his flamboyant bounce-the-ball-off-the-glass-one-handed
layup, drawing a technical foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just asking Obinna how he liked that one,'' Francis
said. ``And the ref thought I was taunting. I knew then that I had
to pull it back a notch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vancouver media called him sullen and sour, which is
actually anything but his engaging, childlike personality. He tried
to explain how much he enjoys living and playing in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``They love me there,'' Francis said. ``I'm like a baby Hakeem.
I do everything they ask. If they want me to go out into the
community, I go out into the community. If they want me to stay
after practice, I stay after practice. That's the way I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Bubbly and upbeat, coachable and eager to learn, proud of the
way he stood up to the situation in Vancouver but aware enough to
know a whole new challenge awaits tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be humble after something like that,'' Francis
said. ``It's one game. And now I get Jason Kidd, one of the great
point guards. The thing I've learned about the NBA is that the ball
keeps rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   One month in, and The Kid is growing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
