<DOCNO> NYT19991201.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5877 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-OLAJUWON-     12-01 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-OLAJUWON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
PHOENIX _ At first glance it would seem typical of the Rockets'
season that on the day Hakeem Olajuwon was found to have a hernia,
extending his stay on the shelf to as much as six weeks, it was
considered good news.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But this reaction was not the result of calluses from the
November to forget. Nor have the Rockets ceased to value the
talents of their 16-year icon.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing the Rockets needed was to add injury to insult.
But if Olajuwon must be hurt and lost, the Rockets believe he could
prove better off with the more serious but more easily repaired
injury.
</P>
<P>
   The inguinal hernia will require surgery this morning, a
45-minute outpatient procedure. But rather than the initially
diagnosed muscle strain that was causing so much pain in Olajuwon's
groin, the hernia should be less likely to cause ongoing problems.
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon can rehabilitate. And team physicians believe when
Olajuwon returns, he will be able to leave the injury behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``All in all, even though it sounds worse, it probably is better
in the long haul than a true groin problem,'' Rockets team
physician Dr. Walter Lowe said Tuesday. ``A groin injury can be so
unpredictable and cause recurring problems. (With the hernia) he
can be taken care of, get well and come back without any symptoms
at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may keep him out a couple more weeks than an isolated minor
groin strain. But with this, he can be well and able to play
through this year and the rest of his career. It's something that
can be fixed and heal and (he can) be back on the basketball court
fairly quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe said the injury probably occurred when Olajuwon reached to
knock the ball from Trail Blazers center Arvydas Sabonis on Friday.
But he said chronic groin problems made Olajuwon, 36, susceptible
to the more severe groin injury and the hernia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hernias are often the straw that broke the camel's back,''
Lowe said. ``He's had soreness off and on, nothing to limit his
agility but enough that he could be hurt with the wrong twist and
pressure. We should downplay the groin strain. The pain and
swelling is from the hernia.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Rockets, the loss of Olajuwon could be considered the
latest bit of misfortune. But if they can find the bright side in
the discovery of the hernia, they also can accept the latest bit of
news well-trained for dealing with adversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always concerned about the players and their health and
well-being,'' coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. ``It's good to hear the
doctor has that positive outlook on it. It's part of the business.
We can't use that as an excuse and have to keep striving to get
better. It gives a lot of guys an opportunity to play and be
involved offensively. We did go to Hakeem a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary recipient of the extra playing time has been center
Kelvin Cato. He played 32 minutes against the Grizzlies on Monday,
scoring 13 points, grabbing 10 rebounds and blocking five shots. He
had 13 points and 12 rebounds against the Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no difference whether you start or come off the bench,
you still have a job to do,'' Cato said. ``I do have to just stay
down. I can't get into foul trouble, so I can stay on the floor.
But that's it. I just know I have to go play, whether it's 10
minutes, 12 minutes or 30 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets have worked with Cato to make him more disciplined
defensively. But the motivation has not been solely to avoid foul
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need him to play solid defense where people have got to go
through you, not by you because you left your feet,'' Tomjanovich
said.
</P>
<P>
   With Cato unavailable to come off the bench, Tomjanovich has
added rookie Kenny Thomas to the rotation. Carlos Rogers also has
worked at center and both forward spots. But he was already getting
playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas had not played in a game that had not been decided. But
he played 20 minutes against the Grizzlies. He made just two of
eight shots, but one came down the stretch in the fourth quarter.
He grabbed six rebounds and was effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to keep going to him and see what he's got,''
Tomjanovich said. ``I'm sure he'll have his ups and downs. But I
was very pleased with how he played.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this stuff is new to him, just being in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   But even with Thomas in the mix, the changes in the rotation
could be more complicated than making Cato a starter and giving
minutes to Thomas. Cato is not considered an inside, post-up player
through whom to run the offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets have worked to add more variety and motion to the
offense. But if Charles Barkley and Steve Francis sit at the same
time, the Rockets can be without a player to initiate or create
half-court offense. If Cato and Barkley sit at the same time, they
can be left without a rebounding force. When the Rockets go deep
into the bench, only Cuttino Mobley can consistently get his own
shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to keep looking at how we substitute,''
Tomjanovich said. ``We had gotten into a rotation with Dream and
Charles.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the Rockets this season, even when things work, they
don't seem to last. At least Tuesday, when they received bad news,
they found some good _ a turn of events they would like to turn
into a trend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
