r a BC-FORECAST-SOCAL-LADN     12-01 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORECAST-SOCAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG L.A. AREA ECONOMY PREDICTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(also moving on the financial and national wires)  
By Gregory J. Wilcox  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Southern California is powering into 2000 thanks
to a surprisingly strong economy that is being fueled in part by
Asia's recovery, according to a forecast to be released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The outlying areas of Ventura County and the Inland Empire north
and east of Los Angeles are expected to record the biggest gains in
nonfarm employment through 2001, according to the semiannual report
from the Los Angeles Economic Development Corp., while sprawling
Los Angeles County will record smaller, but still solid, growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tremendous amount of momentum in the economy,''
said Jack Kyser, chief economist for the nonprofit LAEDC.
</P>
<P>
   During the next two years, Ventura County's nonfarm employment
is expected to grow by 3.9 percent. It will be followed by the
Riverside-San Bernardino region with a growth rate of 3.8 percent,
Orange County with a 2.9 percent rate and Los Angeles with a 1.9
percent rate.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura County's economy added 10,000 new jobs during 1998, an
amount that will probably be equaled this year and surpassed in the
next two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ventura County economy has gone on a tear all of a sudden.
Did somebody give them a big jolt of vitamins?'' Kyser said,
half-jokingly.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those jobs are in the high-technology sector, he pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles will also reach two major milestones by the close of
2000. The county is expected to recover all the nonfarm jobs lost
during the economic restructuring of the early 1990s, by most
accounts the deepest slump since the Great Depression, and its
population will break the 10 million mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``So if you are feeling pinched for space, you are,'' Kyser
said.
</P>
<P>
   The new forecast, an update from a preliminary report issued in
July, benefits from watching the region's economy grow quicker than
expected during the ensuing five months. During the first part of
the next decade, the growth will slow from the current pace but
remain solid nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Gibson, chief economist for the California Department of
Finance, said that Kyser's assessment matches up well with the
state forecast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing certainly has been the confirmation that the
Asian economies are recovering,'' Gibson said. ``That had been the
expectation with fingers crossed warily. Now the evidence is
overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, international trade and tourism are two of the Southern
California sectors that will benefit the most in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden the export activity went from a negative to a
positive. We've almost had to run to keep up with the numbers that
are coming out on exports,'' Kyser said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest impact from the surge in these sectors will occur in
the communities surrounding the ports of Long Beach and Los
Angeles, the South Bay, East Los Angeles County and the Inland
Empire. A ripple effect will be felt in the San Gabriel and San
Fernando valleys.
</P>
<P>
   The entertainment sector will also be pulled along by the Asian
rebound, especially independents looking for distribution deals.
When the Far East's economy headed south, a lot of those
distribution deals dried up.
</P>
<P>
   Now South Korean buyers are coming back into a market that could
get even bigger with China's participation in the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   While Kyser's forecast bodes well for the region, he did sound
several cautionary notes. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   -- Consumer exhaustion will be a major concern next year as the
debt ratio approaches what is considered the ``red zone,'' where 20
percent of personal income is tied up with installment payments.
``We could strangle ourselves with slick plastic,'' Kyser said.
</P>
<P>
   -- The run-up in equity prices, while making lots of people
rich, is creating an asset bubble that concerns some financial
wizards, especially Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan.
Fears of a market meltdown will persist into 2000, and a 30 percent
market loss in one or two consecutive trading days could be
catastrophic to consumer confidence.
</P>
<P>
   -- Labor shortages could derail economic growth next year by
sending manufacturers overseas.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-99 0135EST &QL; 
