r a BC-GUNS-MARCH-LADN     12-01 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-MARCH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLION MOMS TO MARCH ON D.C.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(also moving on California news wire)  
By Robert Monroe  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It took the shooting that wounded Loren Lieb's
5-year-old son to push gun control to the forefront of her mind.
</P>
<P>
   The gunshot wounds borne by Lieb's son, Joshua Stepakoff, in the
wake of an Aug. 10 attack on the North Valley Jewish Community
Center near Los Angeles have become emblematic of the scar that
hate crimes have left nationwide. Now Lieb is a member of a
movement to band 1 million women together next Mother's Day to
demand gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things that you think is always in someone
else's back yard,'' Lieb said.
</P>
<P>
   A resident of Northridge, 25 miles northwest of Los Angeles, she
said Joshua to this day speaks little about the traumatic event.
She was one of several mothers who joined Sen. Dianne Feinstein in
rallying local support Tuesday for the Million Mom March scheduled
for May 14 in Washington, D.C. She could be among as many as 50
from the Jewish Community Center to take part.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Powers, California coordinator of the event, said she had
horrific memories after a gunman stormed the center _ while her
son, Nathan, 5, was there _ and wounded three children, a teen-ager
and an adult before killing a mail carrier. She sought counseling
but decided she needed to do more.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard about the march, I thought that's the way I can
participate,'' Powers said.
</P>
<P>
   She hopes to see 20,000 women from California join the march in
which they will lobby for gun-control measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way that they will break this deadlock is to have the
mothers of America come back to Washington and say enough is
enough,'' said Feinstein during the rally at the Sportsmen's Lodge
in Studio City, about 11 miles northwest of downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   After the attack in which Joshua and four others were wounded _
a white supremacist has been charged with the crimes _ the Jewish
Community Center board president, Nancy Parris-Moskowitz, learned
of the march from Feinstein at a prayer breakfast hosted by
President Bill Clinton. She took the news back to the parents.
</P>
<P>
   Powers called for retailers to support the event and said
mothers, in return, would patronize the stores. She said the
march's power could prompt substantial changes in gun-control laws
that organizers say have been stymied for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a million moms standing up and being a force in
Congress can make a difference,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The bills for which march supporters advocate passage deal with
loopholes in sales of guns at gun shows, trigger locks,
availability of assault weapons and regulations limiting who can
legally use guns.
</P>
<P>
   Joy Turner, a 48-year-old resident of the city of Lawndale about
19 miles south of Los Angeles, said time has not dulled the pain
she feels over her son Hank, who was shot and killed by two other
young men in 1989, But she said her spirits are raised by the idea
of the march. She and her granddaughter, 5, rang a ceremonial bell
Tuesday in memory of children killed by guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thought of seeing one million women united in a common
cause other than shopping is (it's) going to be an awesome sight,''
said Turner, honorary chairwoman of Women Against Gun Violence.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-99 0136EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991201.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 01:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5882 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-GHOST--EMPLOYEES-LADN     12-01 0431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GHOST--EMPLOYEES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAUSD INVESTIGATOR WANTS FUNDS TO STUDY PAYROLL ABUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(also running on California wire)  
By Greg Gittrich  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Unified's top investigator says he
needs more money to fully investigate fraud and waste in the school
district's $5 billion payroll, having already uncovered ``ghost
employees'' and other abuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the payroll system is now set up creates a great
opportunity for people to commit fraud,'' said Don Mullinax,
director of the LAUSD Internal Audits and Special Investigations
Branch.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Caprice Young, who heads the budget and audit
subcommittee, said she will push for an immediate and extensive
investigation of the financial malfeasance, which was reported last
week by the Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have millions and millions of dollars that are being wasted
and misused,'' Young said. ``It's infuriating that the district's
financial systems are in a such a complete disarray. The money
being lost should be going to the classrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   A former investigator for the U.S. Senate, Mullinax on Tuesday
detailed the problems in a Nov. 18 memorandum to the district's
Chief Operating Officer Howard Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to find out what other school districts and large
companies in the private sector do,'' Mullinax said. ``I couldn't
afford within my current budget to investigate the problem and look
for answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax's initial review of the payroll showed employees often
fail to sign in and out as required and improperly change entries
on their time cards. He also concluded that the district is paying
out ``excessive amounts of overtime with little, if any, evidence
of approval.''
</P>
<P>
   He also charged the district regularly cuts checks for ``ghost
employees'' _ people who either don't work for the district or who
fail to show up to their assigned posts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't change the payroll system, we are just setting
ourselves up,'' Mullinax said. ``The district's system is one of
the most antiquated that I have ever seen. We're moving into the
21st century and everyone else is going to leave us standing here
holding our stubby pencils.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullinax and Young estimated a review of the payroll system
would cost ``several thousand dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Young, senior administrators who prepared the
budget for the 1999-2000 fiscal year did not view fixing the
payroll problems as a priority. ``I don't know what they were
thinking,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-99 0137EST &QL; 
