<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5884 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT     12-01 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS WATCH A SUNRISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By RANDY HILL &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Clippers spent Tuesday evening attempting to
find out if perfect attendance accrues enough mojo points to fix a
report card.
</P>
<P>
   For the first game in two weeks, the team roll call was 100
percent ``Yo.''
</P>
<P>
   But when class started, the Clippers flunked shooting, they
earned an incomplete in passing and their `D' was minus all the
way.
</P>
<P>
   The final grade was an `L' administered by the Phoenix Suns, who
seemed as disinterested as the 10,233 subjects at Staples Center
who sat through a 94-80 Clipper defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Kidd had 20 points, 8 rebounds and 8 assists in dragging
the Suns to victory, with Tom Gugliotta adding 16 (to go with 11
rebounds) and Cliff Robinson throwing in 19 off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The Clips should have posed for a class picture while the
opportunity was hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to go out there and perform well,'' rookie forward
Lamar Odom (14 points) said of the class reunion, ``like we miss
each other.''
</P>
<P>
   But even with everyone attending, something was missing.
</P>
<P>
   Returning from a seven-game, foot-sprain vacation was Maurice
Taylor (15 points, 8 rebounds); point guard Eric Murdock's
disagreeable right knee was quiet enough for action; and Derek
Anderson's facial muscle inflammation was defeated by the miracle
of medication. Anderson, a likely free-agent-to-be, continued
playing himself out of town, scoring 25 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels weird,'' Anderson said of the Clips' relatively
healthy squad, ``because we have to bring it back together.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was a bit more convincing: ``I think we'll do all
right,'' he said, providing a pre-game forecast for the Clippers'
full house.
</P>
<P>
   They were miles from all right in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was busted for his second personal foul only three
minutes into his comeback.
</P>
<P>
   With their offensive sets resembling the final round of a Vogue
contest, the Clippers shot 35 percent from the field, demonstrated
enough love to hand out just four assists (they are - by far - the
NBA's worst in that category), but only entered the second period
down 25-21.
</P>
<P>
   With Kidd attempting to coerce his cronies into action, Phoenix
had led by as many as 8.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns' second unit held the Clips at bay for much of round
two, but when the starters returned, Anderson sparked a rally with
11 of his 13 first-half points in the period. A pass from Tyrone
Nesby led to an acrobatic, buzzer-beating Anderson layup that made
it 42-42 at intermission.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns actually fell behind shortly after the second half
began, but ran off to a 10-point lead and entered the fourth with a
67-59 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   But anyone thinking the Clippers were all set to make a serious
run already has flunked Clippers 101.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-99 0139EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
