<DOCNO> NYT19991201.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5885 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-BRICK-ATTACK-1STLD     12-01 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRICK-ATTACK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE CHARGE PANHANDLER IN BRICK ATTACK ON WOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Subs for inserts, rewriting throughout) 
(sw) 
 By JUAN FORERO and JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A panhandler with a criminal record that stretches
back nearly two decades was arrested on Tuesday and charged with
attempted murder in the Nov. 16 brick attack of a young woman on a
midtown Manhattan street, police officials said on Tuesday night.
The arrest was made after a witness to the assault identified the
man in a lineup, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The man, identified by the police as Paris Drake, 31, was
charged with attempted murder in the second-degree, assault and
weapons possession in the attack, which left Nicole Barrett, a
27-year-old office worker, with a critical head injury that
required two operations at Bellevue Hospital Center. Drake was
expected to be arraigned on Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir announced the arrest late
Tuesday night at the Midtown South Precinct station house on West
35th Street, where he heralded the work of detectives and said he
had told the Barrett family of the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stopped and saw the Barrett family before coming here,''
Safir said. ``I'm not going to tell you what they said, but you can
probably guess that they were relieved.''
</P>
<P>
   Police officials did not provide a motive for the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The highly publicized attack immediately led to speculation by
the police that a person who was homeless and possibly mentally ill
was responsible, and three days later, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's
administration announced that the homeless had no right to sleep on
city streets and would face arrest for refusing shelter. The police
have arrested more than 100 homeless people since the measure was
announced.
</P>
<P>
   The police said on Tuesday night that Drake sold drugs and was a
panhandler, and Safir described him as homeless. But other police
and city officials said on Tuesday that it was not clear if Drake
was homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Olga Beck, a spokeswoman for the city's Department of Homeless
Services, said there was no record that Drake had ever been in the
city's homeless shelter system, and investigators said he had
apparently been living with a girlfriend recently in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Safir also said there was no indication that Drake had a history
of mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor was returning from a trip to Texas on Tuesday night
and could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Drake became the prime suspect when an inmate on Rikers Island
told the authorities that Drake, who had been arrested on Nov. 23
on a low-level drug charge and was being held on Rikers, bragged
about the attack to the inmate, law enforcement officials said. The
inmate was released into the custody of detectives, who drove him
around midtown on Monday until he spotted Drake at the Port
Authority Bus Terminal and pointed him out, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Drake underwent hours of questioning by detectives, police
officials said, and did not confess to the crime. But on Tuesday, a
law enforcement official said one of several witnesses to the
attack brought in for a police lineup positively identified Drake
as Ms. Barrett's assailant. Investigators also believed that Drake
closely resembled the sketch of the suspect that was made public
after the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said Drake, with his long criminal
record, fit the profile of a violent and dangerous criminal. First
arrested in 1982 when he was 14, Drake was arrested 23 more times
over the years, mostly on drug-related charges. He has spent more
than 7 of the last 10 years in state prisons on charges ranging
from drug dealing to assaulting a prison guard. Officials said that
on every occasion, Drake's requests for early parole were denied
and he served the maximum sentence.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing a prison term in upstate New York this summer,
he was arrested four times, on charges including selling drugs and
assault, according to law enforcement officials. The latest arrest
was on Nov. 23, just seven days after the attack on Ms. Barrett,
when Drake was sent to Rikers on the drug charge.
</P>
<P>
   The police said Drake used a paving stone to bash Ms. Barrett
from behind as she prepared to cross Madison Avenue at 42nd Street,
an unprovoked assault that reminded New Yorkers that despite the
drop in crime in recent years, random violence can easily shatter
perceptions of a safe city. The attack also cast a public eye on
the issue of mentally unstable homeless people because officials
initially believed the attacker was homeless, like several other
mentally disturbed people who in recent years have committed random
violent crimes that have brought attention to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barrrett was admitted to Bellevue in critical condition. The
young woman received flowers and cards from hundreds of
well-wishers and was visited by Giuliani and Safir after the
attack. She has recovered dramatically and is now in stable
condition, alert and able to talk with her family.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
