<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5887 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-TRULOVE-CARWASH-LADN     12-01 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRULOVE-CARWASH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAR WASH ROMANCE NO MERE SOAP OPERA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Will also move on the California wire.)  
By Byavna Mistry  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sonny Knight should have caught on when Sharie
McGarray had her car washed two or three times a week at the car
wash he managed in Valencia, northeast of Los Angeles, but it took
him two years to realize she had taken a shine to him.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the two, who run Sonny and Sharie's Hillbilly Hot
Dog Stand in West Virginia, returned home to marry _ yes, at the
car wash.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was in as much as five times a week,'' Knight said, hours
before Tuesday's ceremony. ``She would make up reasons, like saying
she ran through the sprinkler or needed more gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``She did that just to be close to me. I didn't have a clue.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple opted for the deluxe wedding, with 130 guests. She
wore a white gown and cowboy hat. Her white boots had rhinestones
shinier than the polished rims on a '69 Camaro.
</P>
<P>
   Knight sported black jeans, a cowboy hat and a jacket, of
course. This was, after all, a formal affair.
</P>
<P>
   It was three years ago when Sharie McGarray started going to the
Valencia AutoSpa car wash _ drawn to Knight like a 16-year-old to
bubblegum-scented air freshener.
</P>
<P>
   She spied on him before the Valencia AutoSpa opened to see who
dropped him off, and drove by in the evening to see if he left with
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't ask anyone,'' McGarray said. ``I didn't know if he
was married or gay.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to be noticed, McGarray, 42, would make up excuses _ her
pedals perhaps weren't cleaned just right _ and she would ask to
see the manager.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until one day when local Judge Alan Rosenfield showed
interest in the AutoSpa's best customer after spotting a bottle of
wine in her trunk that Knight stepped into action.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said that she was waiting for the right person and that
that bottle of wine was for Mr. Right,'' Knight said. ``I was
almost jealous.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight told her then and there that he wanted to share the
bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfield threw in the towel _ in fact he married the pair, who
say it was he who ignited their spark.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good friend,'' Knight added. ``When I moved in, he
backed off.''
</P>
<P>
   AutoSpa owners Randy Cressall and Dave Wilke put on the wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are so much in love,'' said Randy Cressall, co-owner of
the AutoSpa. ``They are so devoted to each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sonny's like a member of the family,'' Cressall added. ``It's
not the most appropriate place but they had such a wonderful
experience meeting here.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, Knight said. It was the perfect spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people ski dive or jump out of airplanes,'' McGarray
said. ``This is what means the most to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's exchange of vows was the couple's second wedding. The
two were married at 9:09 on Sept. 9 at home in West Virginia, where
they moved last year. Knight's brother is in need of a lung lobe
transplant and he is on standby as a donor.
</P>
<P>
   A third wedding is planned for Friday in Texas, where more of
McGarray's family lives. While McGarray's wedding gown will stay
the same, she will get a new wedding ring for each ceremony _ a
three-ring marriage of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   Once back home in West Virginia, they'll go back to the business
of running Sonny and Sharie's Hillbilly Hotdogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to be together and we love hot dogs,'' Knight said.
``It's a great combination.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
