<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5889 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-CARO.HOMICIDE-LADN     12-01 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARO.HOMICIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER ARRESTED IN SONS' SLAYINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(will also move on California wire)  
By Lisa Mascaro  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Just hours before a scheduled night vigil for
three boys shot to death in their family's exclusive hilltop
mansion, their mother was arrested on suspicion of murdering her
sons.
</P>
<P>
   Following her arrest on Tuesday, Socorro ``Cora'' Caro was
transferred from a private hospital in Thousand Oaks, 40 miles
northwest of Los Angeles, to Ventura County Medical Center in
Ventura, another 20 miles west. She was listed in serious and
stable condition in the jail ward, recovering from a self-inflicted
gunshot wound to the head, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   She has yet to speak with authorities about the Nov. 22
incident, having asked for an attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was the first time authorities identified Caro as a
suspect, although they had said from the start that the case
involved domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on all the evidence we have . . . it all points to her
being the only one who shot,'' said Ventura County sheriff's
spokesman Eric Nishimoto. ``We have probable cause to point to her
as the only shooter.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials also believe she shot herself in the right side of her
head after firing a single bullet into the heads of three of her
four sons.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said late last week that ballistics tests showed
that a .38-caliber revolver found in the home was used for all the
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators do not know whether the mother, known for
volunteering at her sons' school, has retained an
attorney,Nishimoto said.
</P>
<P>
   He also declined to detail the evidence gathered during
investigations at the Caros' Presilla Road mansion, which have
continued since last week's shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect's family, some of whom live in a home she and her
husband own in Granada Hills, have declined to comment on the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   Cora Caro's arrest came a week after the boys' father,
rheumatologist Xavier J. Caro, found his sons _ Xavier ``Joey''
Caro Jr., 11; Michael Anthony Caro, 8; and Christopher Laurence
Caro, 5 _ dead in their beds when he arrived home about 11:20 p.m.
He found his wife wounded in another room.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor called 911 and was holding the couple's fourth son,
an unidentified toddler who was unharmed, when police arrived.
Police spent most of the next day, Nov. 23, interviewing the
52-year-old doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still investigating, or at least validating, his
whereabouts and activity,'' Nishimoto said. ``Obviously, we're
still waiting on a lot of information to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourners were planning to gather Tuesday evening for a vigil
service for the boys at Padre Serra Parish in Camarillo, where the
family attended church.
</P>
<P>
   A funeral for the boys is scheduled there today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm deeply saddened by it,'' said Leslie Randall, whose son
was in Joey's fifth-grade class at Santa Rosa Elementary School.
She said that a week after the tragedy, the community is still in
shock.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Norris, a board member of the Pleasant Valley School
District, said Cora Caro's arrest does not mean she is guilty of
the slayings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shocking thing is not that the mother was arrested but
that someone would kill children,'' Norris added. ``That was such a
tragedy. We have such a nice, safe community that that would happen
to our children is a shock.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-99 0148EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
