<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5891 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-WOMEN-BIZ-LADN     12-01 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-BIZ-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY SAYS WOMEN IN CHARGE OF HOUSEHOLD BUYS, SERVICES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(will also move on California and national wires)  
By Jason Z. Cohen  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Marketeers take note: Women _ especially those who
own businesses _ buy lots of things not normally associated with
women.
</P>
<P>
   That's the message behind a survey to be released today by the
National Foundation for Women Business Owners.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, the survey finds, it's a woman who is
behind a household's choice of Internet service providers, cable
television, telephone and insurance agents, among others. And women
_ especially business owners _ place a premium on service and
convenience, preferring to pay someone else to do a lot of
household chores that women a century ago were expected to
complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``The survey is finally pointing out that women business owners
are smart businesspeople,'' said Susan Eigenbrodt, president of
California's Ventura County chapter of the National Association of
Women Business Owners.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also shows women make buying decisions for the whole
house, Eigenbrodt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a much stronger buying force than people ever realized
and we are making decisions,'' Eigenbrodt said.
</P>
<P>
   The survey's results demonstrate that women business owners have
an increasing impact on the economy, said Vicki Eagleson Arndt, a
member of the Ventura County businesswomen's group. The foundation
estimates there are 9.1 million women-owned businesses in United
States and 1.2 million in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge buying unit. It's a huge opportunity for people to
focus in on the way women buy and the way women do business,''
Arndt said.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, which has a margin of error of 5.3 percent, was
conducted during June by Minneapolis-based CJ Olson Market
Research. A total of 370 women business owners and 365 working
women were surveyed by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   It's hauntingly accurate, said Arndt.
</P>
<P>
   Both women said the survey's findings bore an uncanny similarity
to their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety percent of it absolutely equals my life down to the
realization that I could spend seven hours cleaning my itty bitty
house or I could spend seven hours working, pay someone to clean
the house and be more economically efficient,'' Eigenbrodt said.
</P>
<P>
   As business owners and the principal organizers in their
households, both women said they place a premium on convenience.
</P>
<P>
   The survey shows women who own businesses are more likely than
women employees to hire someone to do their house cleaning and
their lawn care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will pay for convenience,'' Arndt said. ``I'll pay someone
to cut my lawn and clean my pool so I don't have to. It's a time
factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Women business owners also make more frequent use of the
Internet for purchases and investing than do their counterparts who
are employed by someone else, the survey revealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time effectiveness has become a major factor in my life. I run
my errands, as much of them online as humanly possible,''
Eigenbrodt said.
</P>
<P>
   Some marketers are already taking notice.
</P>
<P>
   Women factor heavily into the marketing plans of free Internet
service provider NetZero. The company strives to paint itself as a
good value and a convenient tool for navigating the Internet, said
Melissa Robinson, director of public relations for Westlake
Village-based NetZero Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not of the mind that women only care about shopping.
Women are more and more becoming involved in the stock market,''
Robinson said. ``We see women as a very significant part of our
audience. They're the ones, really, that a free Internet access
would appeal to because they're the ones that are writing the bill.
They are able to see first-hand the money they're spending on
Internet access.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-99 0152EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991201.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5893 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-WOMEN-BIZ-LADN     12-01 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-BIZ-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY SAYS WOMEN IN CHARGE OF HOUSEHOLD BUYS, SERVICES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
