conducted during June by Minneapolis-based CJ Olson Market
Research. A total of 370 women business owners and 365 working
women were surveyed by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   It's hauntingly accurate, said Arndt.
</P>
<P>
   Both women said the survey's findings bore an uncanny similarity
to their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety percent of it absolutely equals my life down to the
realization that I could spend seven hours cleaning my itty bitty
house or I could spend seven hours working, pay someone to clean
the house and be more economically efficient,'' Eigenbrodt said.
</P>
<P>
   As business owners and the principal organizers in their
households, both women said they place a premium on convenience.
</P>
<P>
   The survey shows women who own businesses are more likely than
women employees to hire someone to do their house cleaning and
their lawn care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will pay for convenience,'' Arndt said. ``I'll pay someone
to cut my lawn and clean my pool so I don't have to. It's a time
factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Women business owners also make more frequent use of the
Internet for purchases and investing than do their counterparts who
are employed by someone else, the survey revealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time effectiveness has become a major factor in my life. I run
my errands, as much of them online as humanly possible,''
Eigenbrodt said.
</P>
<P>
   Some marketers are already taking notice.
</P>
<P>
   Women factor heavily into the marketing plans of free Internet
service provider NetZero. The company strives to paint itself as a
good value and a convenient tool for navigating the Internet, said
Melissa Robinson, director of public relations for Westlake
Village-based NetZero Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not of the mind that women only care about shopping.
Women are more and more becoming involved in the stock market,''
Robinson said. ``We see women as a very significant part of our
audience. They're the ones, really, that a free Internet access
would appeal to because they're the ones that are writing the bill.
They are able to see first-hand the money they're spending on
Internet access.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
