r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     12-01 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS IMPOSE ORDER IN CHAOS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Politics and basketball converged in the Great
Northwest on Tuesday, and didn't it figure that Phil Jackson was at
ground zero of the fracas. But only in his role as Lakers coach,
not in a throw-back to his 1960s protesting youth.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson left the chanting and grandstanding to tens of thousands
of Generation X demonstrators, whose opposition to the World Trade
Organization convention clogged the downtown streets surrounding
the Lakers' hotel and threatened to cancel Tuesday night's game
against the Seattle SuperSonics.
</P>
<P>
   The sometimes-violent demonstrations prompted officials to
impose a 7 p.m. curfew and declare a state of civil emergency, but
the game went on without incident.
</P>
<P>
   And the Lakers, unfazed by clouds of tear gas, random vandalism
and occasional violence, made their own statement, of a decidedly
nonpolitical nature.
</P>
<P>
   They imposed an embargo on the Sonics' high-powered offense,
including L.A. import Ruben Patterson, and cruised to a 101-77
victory before 17,072 at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal played one of his shortest stints of the
season, 33 minutes, but compressed his production to finish with 27
points, 10 rebounds and four blocked shots. Patterson, the former
Laker and self-proclaimed ``Kobe Stopper,'' did put O'Neal in early
foul trouble with drives the hoop and led the Sonics with 19
points.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers had the game in hand by halftime. And by the
fourth quarter the only suspense left was whether the Lakers could
extend a recent trend of defensive dominance. They did, holding
their third consecutive opponent under 85 points, a feat not
achieved by the franchise since 1954.
</P>
<P>
   And they dealt Seattle its first home loss in seven games this
season. But this was no ordinary day at home for the Sonics, who
had to stay in a downtown hotel overnight because of the
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Strange days, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Different day,'' said Lakers guard Derek Fisher. ``But we
really didn't have much to do with that. We just continued to hope
we would remain safe within our rooms.... Hopefully, we can get out
of here safe now. The saga's not over.''
</P>
<P>
   And impossible for anyone here for the day to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   As much as the NBA is indeed a global commodity, the Lakers
never expected to find themselves mired in the middle of a protest
on free trade. Yet here was a pro basketball game transposed with
arrests, tear-gas clouds and police blockades _ all happening
simultaneously within several blocks of KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the NBA commissioner's office monitored the
activity all day and was prepared to cancel the game at the first
sign of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, political-minded and a confidant to presidential
candidate Bill Bradley, stayed abreast of events listening to
National Public Radio in his hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' bus ride to the afternoon shoot-around was delayed
by protesters filling the downtown streets near the Four Seasons
hotel, which also housed several international dignitaries. It took
a police escort to transport the Lakers safely to the arena for the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, police and Four Seasons security decided to
lock the doors for safety _ and momentarily trapped the Lakers'
unsuspecting public-relations director on the street.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Lakers reached the arena prior to the game, the
national guard had been mobilized. By an hour before tipoff, a
state of civil emergency had been declared.
</P>
<P>
   But most players were unaware of, and seemingly unmoved by, the
politics. If anything, they were annoyed by the constant
thunderclaps of tear-gas guns being fired in the streets as they
tried to nap in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Inside KeyArena, the only sign of the unrest was on the
television monitors broadcasting live coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't much of a murmur from (the players),'' Jackson
said. ``We had to turn around to face some protesters to back the
bus up the street. That was an interesting reaction, to going from
these people involved with world trade to figuring out it was the
Lakers in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't talk to (the players) about it, except to tell them
what the WTO was. I gave them an idea what it was and what it
involved. They didn't quite know what the significance was.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, a product of '60s activism himself, smiled his approval
of the protests, at least the peaceful ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really glad to see this age group motivated to protest
something,'' he said. ``I think it's great. I just hope that they
can carry this from such global perspective to individual action.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
