<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5895 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      12-01 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS, O'NEAL EXPOSE SONICS' CENTRAL FLAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Having failed to attract a massive outbreak of bubonic
plague for Seattle's first week of the holiday shopping season, the
local civic, business and political geniuses settled for their
second and third choices: the World Trade Organization and
Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   With leadership like this, can the Ebola virus be far behind?
</P>
<P>
   One must be careful in drawing comparisons, however.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal and the Los Angeles Lakers are required by the NBA to
show up here twice a year, making one of those appearances Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The WTO, well, somebody volunteered us for that.
</P>
<P>
   Wait till we find the clowns responsible for allowing downtown
to be gashed up. Bet they backed the bus tunnel and the Mariners
owners, too.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but that attitude smacks of protest. Many would say we've
had enough of that to last us the rest of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in this moment of the Grand Bellyache, if we are to
indulge a protest of the sporting kind, let's offer this one: The
Sonics must stop this business of playing basketball without a
center.
</P>
<P>
   Not necessarily today, or this month. Or even this season. We
want to be flexible here, particularly in the absence of gas masks.
</P>
<P>
   But sometime in the long, fruitful life of, say, club president
Wally Walker's 2-year-old daughter, it would be intriguing to
witness the simplicity of arcing a pass into a Sonics behemoth in
the low post and watch his backside overwhelm helpless opponents
like an avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   That scene took place almost endlessly Tuesday at KeyArena,
where O'Neal executed the Gluteal Smother with his peculiar
lumbering grace. He had 27 points in a 101-77 rout of the Sonics
that had lost the element of contest by halftime. There was more
fire in downtown dumpsters.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Sonics didn't deploy all available means against
O'Neal, including the WTO protesters, who made a ceaseless racket
outside the Lakers' downtown hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a loud day,'' said O'Neal afterward. ``Somebody had a
drum set outside, and they were at it the whole time. I tried to
sleep, but I couldn't. I'd lay there and tell myself, `I don't hear
it, I don't hear it.' But I was concentrating so hard on that, I
got a headache.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine what might have happened had O'Neal been rested and
ready. The National Guard would have had a second job.
</P>
<P>
   The damage wreaked inside KeyArena was hardly unfamiliar. The
Gluteal Smother was the primary weapon in dispatching the Sonics
when last they were in the playoffs. You remember the playoffs,
don't you?
</P>
<P>
   Back in the spring of Nineteen and Ninety-Eight, the Sonics were
savaged 4-1 in the second round by the Lakers in large part because
they couldn't get out from under O'Neal's large parts. Although
last season the Sonics and Lakers split the four-game
regular-season series, fact is, it didn't count for anything
because of the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, O'Neal is a vexation for every opponent. In the eight
games prior to Tuesday night, he had averaged 37 points, 14
rebounds and 4.7 assists, shooting 52 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is,'' said Sonics coach Paul Westphal, ``the best player in
the game. They can score because they can have a dry spell and
throw it into Shaq and get something good.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the essential difference between this year's Sonics and
Lakers. With the Sonics, everything and everyone must go well to
succeed. With Shaq, there's slack.
</P>
<P>
   A good big man can get his team points more easily. For the
Sonics, easy points left when Jack Sikma was traded to Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Sonics are built to concede the middle to O'Neal and
any like-size lummox who doesn't get in the way of his own feet.
The Sonics are the NBA's second-shortest team and have exactly zero
players who are big and mean enough to visit the paint regularly,
much less own it.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean they are a terrible team, as the 11-3 record
before Tuesday night attests. But with the Lakers, San Antonio
Spurs, Portland Trail Blazers and Sacramento Kings more than
adequately equipped in the galoot department, the Sonics'
impressive November mark is destined to shrivel once they engage
the Western Conference's passel of big uglies.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night was among the initial tests, and the Sonics
flunked. Horace Grant flailed nobly in the pivot, but he's no more
a center than Lucy Ricardo. He's a good power forward, and a good
enough center against the Clippers. But when the Sonics begin
Sunday a run against four quality teams, results are likely to go
more along the lines of Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if the Sonics are without heart. Ruben Patterson, a
one-year Laker, thrashed and crashed for 19 points to lead Seattle
Tuesday, evoking memories for a courtside visitor, Magic Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-Laker superstar, in the company of Starbucks chairman and
business partner Howard Schultz, ruminated on Ruben's participation
in informal pickup games at UCLA during the summer after his
drafting by the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game we played, he said, `I got Magic,''' Johnson said.
``That told me something.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd go after me every time. I always told him I was smarter
than he was. But you know, after I got done playing against him, I
had to take naps a few times.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Johnson said he admired the heart shown by
Patterson, Grant and Gary Payton.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means something,'' said Johnson, tapping his chest. ``I'd
like to see some of that on our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, heart goes only so far. Patterson is 6-foot-5,
O'Neal 7-1. In a league where size still matters, the Sonics can
dish all the heart they want. O'Neal remains much closer to the
basket.
</P>
<P>
   Some truths just don't go away.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
