<P>
   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-CHURCH-DOOR (Jerusalem) _ No repair is ever hastily
undertaken at the holy site where tradition says Jesus died and was
buried. In a venerated house of worship that is elaborately
divided, arch by arch, among three major Christian rites and
several other denominations, no repair or change is simple. It is a
matter of turf. What hope, then, can there be for Israel to
persuade the Christians to install an emergency exit and door
before an expected millennial rush of pilgrims? By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO-EXPELL-EDUC (Chicago) _ Beyond an intolerance for
weapons and drugs, the new ethos on conduct in schools has
profoundly changed views on what is normal, if annoying, behavior
by adolescents. No longer is the playground scrap or the kickball
tussle deemed a rite of passage. Known most often as the ``zero
tolerance'' code, aggression is viewed as violence, and teachers
are typically forbidden from simply resolving any physical dispute
with a lecture. Instead, they are instructed to file a report with
the school authorities, so that a uniform policy can run its
course, and no offending student escapes punishment. By Dirk
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   HOSPITAL-DEATHS (Undated) _ A news analysis: Why, after so many
years of public attention to medical malpractice, the National
Academy of Sciences wants to crack down now by creating a federal
agency to protect patients. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
