<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 02:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5911 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-WRITETHRU-     12-01 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS WIN AMID SEATTLE CHAOS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Amid one of the greatest civil protests in decades,
the Lakers took a cue from the rowdy demonstrations that surrounded
them.
</P>
<P>
   They blockaded, they disrupted, they raised fists and they
chanted a bit. They just didn't have to leave the safe confines of
KeyArena to do any of it.
</P>
<P>
   As tens of thousands protested world trade policies just down
the street, the Lakers imposed their own kind of embargo on the
hometown Seattle SuperSonics and their low-wage labor import, Ruben
Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive demonstration was a profound success, resulting in
a 101-77 rout Tuesday night in front of 17,072 protest-weary fans.
</P>
<P>
   It figured the Lakers would win this battle in the midst of a
global trade debate. They are led, after all, by 1960s child Phil
Jackson. The political-minded coach steered clear of the fracas on
the streets, though he enthusiastically approved of the
demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   It all made for a bizarre juxtaposition of sports and politics.
</P>
<P>
   Strange days, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Different day,'' said Lakers guard Derek Fisher. ``But we
really didn't have much to do with that. We just continued to hope
we would remain safe within our (hotel) rooms. . . . Hopefully, we
can get out of here safe now. The saga's not over.''
</P>
<P>
   And impossible for anyone here for the day to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters against the World Trade Organization clogged the
downtown streets surrounding the Lakers' hotel and the resulting
chaos threatened to cancel the game.
</P>
<P>
   The sometimes-violent demonstrations prompted officials to
impose a 7 p.m. curfew and declare a state of civil emergency, but
the game went on without incident and the arena filled to
near-capacity for the 7 p.m. tipoff.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Lakers, unfazed by clouds of tear gas, random vandalism
and occasional violence, made their own statement, of a decidedly
nonpolitical nature. They handed the Sonics their first home loss
in seven games this season.
</P>
<P>
   And in the process, they made a little history of their own,
holding their third straight opponent under 85 points, a feat not
achieved by the Lakers since 1954.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal played one of his shortest stints of the
season, 33 minutes, but compressed his production to finish with 27
points, 10 rebounds and four blocked shots. And they didn't let
Patterson, the former Laker and self-proclaimed ``Kobe Stopper,''
do too much damage. Patterson did put O'Neal in early foul trouble
with drives to the hoop and led the Sonics with 19 points. But the
Lakers had the game in hand by halftime, sporting a 13-point lead
on the Sonics' home floor.
</P>
<P>
   But this was no ordinary day at home for the Sonics, who had to
stay in a downtown hotel overnight because of the demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would've been more fun to go down to Nordstrom and protest
than to play that game,'' quipped Seattle coach Paul Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   Television coverage of the game was transposed with
round-the-clock coverage of arrests, tear-gas clouds and police
blockades _ all happening within several blocks of KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the NBA commissioner's office monitored the
activity all day and was prepared to cancel the game at the first
sign of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, a confidant to presidential candidate Bill Bradley,
stayed abreast of events listening to National Public Radio in his
hotel room. And he smiled his approval of the protests, at least
the peaceful ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really glad to see this age group motivated to protest
something,'' Jackson said. ``I think it's great. I just hope that
they can carry this from such global perspective to individual
action.''
</P>
<P>
   The players' awareness of events was limited to having their
mid-afternoon naps at the Four Seasons hotel disrupted by the
firing of police rifles shooting rubber bullets and tear-gas
canisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a drowsy day,'' O'Neal said. ``Drums, screaming, arguing.
I didn't get enough rest today.''
</P>
<P>
   Players watched the events on TV and out their hotel windows.
Then their bus ride to the afternoon shoot-around was delayed by
protesters filling the downtown streets near the Four Seasons,
which also housed several international dignitaries. It took a
police escort to transport the Lakers safely to the arena for the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, police and hotel security decided to lock
the doors for safety _ and momentarily trapped the Lakers'
unsuspecting public-relations director on the street.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Lakers reached the arena prior to the game, the
national guard had been mobilized. By an hour before tipoff, a
state of civil emergency had been declared.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers couldn't help but leave with a lasting impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was interesting,'' Fisher said. ``We travel a lot and we
see a lot of interesting things. But that's something that you go
through your career _ and talk NBA stories to tell the grandkids, I
mean, !ital!that's!off! a story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a little bit about the situation, kind of how some
of the (protesters) feel, but you never get your message across
with violence. It's unfortunate that in this world where we have so
much to be thankful for that we still almost have to go to war to
get our point across.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
