<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS ROMP AS SONICS SUFFER FIRST HOME LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ With World Trade Organization protests, civil unrest
and the need for the National Guard to patrol Seattle streets,
KeyArena figured to be a safe place.
</P>
<P>
   However, home was hardly a haven for the Sonics, who were
bulldozed by the Los Angeles Lakers, 101-77, Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   In their first loss this season at KeyArena, the Sonics were
smothered by an impressive Laker defense. The Sonics shot a dismal
39 percent and never got closer than 10 points after falling behind
52-39 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Much like those outside events, this one got ugly in a hurry.
The Sonics' usually high-octane offense managed just 16 points in
the second quarter and 18 in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Sonics point guard Gary Payton was so disenchanted by the loss
that he unleashed a verbal tirade in a corridor near the team's
locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Payton could be heard calling for his agent, Aaron Goodwin,
outside of Coach Paul Westphal's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``You better do something about these (expletive),'' Payton
could be heard screaming. ``I'm tired of these (expletive).''
</P>
<P>
   The commotion was so belligerent that teammates Horace Grant and
Vernon Maxwell sprung from the seats. They both rushed out of a
locker room filled with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were extremely frustrated by the loss,'' Westphal said in a
statement after the incident. ``Tempers flared. This was about the
fifth or sixth on the totem pole this year. I'm not going to worry
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   A witness to an earlier incident said that Goodwin approached
Payton on the Sonics' bench during the fourth quarter. Goodwin
asked Payton what was going on, referring to the blowout. Payton
then stood up, pointed to Westphal and said ``Ask him.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not the first time Payton exploded after a big loss.
Payton delivered similar fireworks after a 30-point loss at
Portland last season.
</P>
<P>
   Payton and his agent left without comment.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is curious why Payton blew up because of a defeat
just 15 games into an 82-game season.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is because Payton had to sit through a merciless
fourth quarter. Payton left the game after the third period with 12
points, six rebounds and five assists.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics trailed 75-59 at that point. Their biggest deficit
was 101-73 with 1:04 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Vin Baker was adamant about not using the game to gauge the
Sonics. They are 11-4 and the Pacific Division rival Lakers left
11-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to throw this away,'' said Baker, who finished
with 12 points and 10 rebounds. ``We're better than we played. We
were horrible. This team can't beat us by 30 points. We can beat
this team on any night.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe next time, the Sonics will at least have backup.
</P>
<P>
   Shammond Williams, Greg Foster, Rashard Lewis, Vernon Maxwell,
Chuck Person and Vladimir Stepania each came off the bench in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   None of them brought anything.
</P>
<P>
   That group combined to shoot 1-for-13 in the first half.
Maxwell, normally the offensive canon off the bench, was the
biggest culprit. He missed his first six shots.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell (1-for-10) is playing with sore right knee. He never
found his rhythm while the starters made 14 of 27 shots. It was
deflating considering the Sonics pounced on the Lakers early, and
built a 21-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Sonics undoing came in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead 35-33 with 5:54 left in the second, the Sonics managed to
score just one more field goal before halftime. The Lakers,
meanwhile, went on a 19-4 run that ended the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics were lulled into a slower tempo than they prefer
because of Laker center Shaquille O'Neal's presence down low. The
Sonics missed open shots and were unable to score easy baskets in
transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think they were on their feet,'' Lakers coach Phil
Jackson said. `` ... I heard they had to stay in hotels rather than
in their homes. That makes it kind of a road game for them so they
are still undefeated at home as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Canceling the game was never a consideration.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, WTO protests did not spill into the Seattle Center area
near KeyArena. Both teams arrived on time. None of the Sonics
experienced traffic problems because Monday night they stayed at a
hotel within a mile of the arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been more fun to go down to Nordstrom to protest
than to play that game,'' Westphal joked.
</P>
<P>
   It was about the only humor one could find.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
