<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DRIVER-OF-YEAR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JARRETT CAPTURES DRIVER OF YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Newly crowned NASCAR Winston Cup champion Dale Jarrett will
leave New York City with some additional honors this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett has been voted 1999 Driver of the Year, outpolling CART
rookie champion Juan Montoya for the award's 33rd edition. Jarrett,
who is in New York this week for festivities leading to the NASCAR
awards banquet at the Waldorf-Astoria on Friday night, will be
honored as the year's top driver during a luncheon at Le Cirque
2000 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett and Montoya were the only drivers named in final secret
balloting conducted by a 15-member panel of motorsports
journalists, including this reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, 43, is the fifth Cup champion in the past six years to
be voted the award, joining Dale Earnhardt (1994) and Jeff Gordon
(1995, 1997-98). NHRA Funny Car champion John Force won the award
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything comes out of this whole thing ... as much as
anything, I hope our story is a little bit of an inspiration to
others,'' said Jarrett, who joins car-owner Robert Yates and crew
chief Todd Parrott as first-time series champions. ``Perseverance
pays off and hard work and dedication. I think that's a story that
can be told by Todd, Robert and myself. Hopefully, it'll be
somewhat of an inspiration to these other aspiring drivers, owners,
crew chiefs and crew members alike, that if you work hard and
dedicate yourself to what you're doing, then you can become
champions. You're never too old.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, driver of the No. 88 Quality Care Service/Ford Credit
Taurus, won four races in 34 starts this year. But he racked up 24
top-five and 29 top-10 finishes en route to winning the
championship over native Texan Bobby Labonte by 201 points.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya, 24, of Colombia, won seven of 20 Championship Auto
Racing Teams FedEx Series events driving the No. 4 Reynard-Honda
owned by Chip Ganassi.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Cup rookie-of-the-year candidate Tony Stewart took
fourth-quarter Driver of the Year honors. Stewart, who won all
three of his record-setting Cup races during the fourth quarter,
earned 12 of 15 first-place votes and 120 points. Dale Earnhardt
Jr., who clinched his second consecutive NASCAR Busch Series
championship this year, was second with 37 points.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-99 0227EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991201.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 03:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5924 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     12-01 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 49ERS DYNASTY ISN'T COMING BACK  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Welcome to the Fannies, the awards show honoring
people who distinguish themselves in the field of athletics while
sitting on their ... fannies.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the award for the worst fans in sports. The envelope,
please.
</P>
<P>
   Runners-up: Denver Broncos' fans! They pack snowballs around
batteries and hurl 'em off the upper deck. Hilarious, cowardly and
potentially lethal! Rocky Mountains Fever _ catch it!
</P>
<P>
   Now the big winners. Drum roll, please!
</P>
<P>
   It's San Francisco 49ers fans!
</P>
<P>
   (Whooo! NIII-NURRR fans, we're No. 1! Yeahhh!)
</P>
<P>
   Today we salute their boorish and delusional sense of
entitlement. Niners fans had an 18-year dynasty dropped in their
nacho-stained and beer-soaked laps and assumed it was their
birthright.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, this is not an anti-booing screed. Boo away. An NFL
game ain't the junior high production of ``Our Town.'' The players
are mercenaries who are paid handsomely to suffer gruesome injuries
for your viewing pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   What's unbecoming is the whining and hand-wringing of 49ers
fans, the ``How could my team do this to me, a son of San
Francisco?'' It's the indignation and shame.
</P>
<P>
   Niners fans are caught in a time warp. The NFL has regulated
dynasties out of existence. The league targeted the 49ers like the
government went after Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   You've had your last 18-year orgy, 49ers fans. Wake up and snort
the coffee. Life is hard, the 49ers suck. Try to take it like a
man, or woman, or whatever.
</P>
<P>
   FORGET POKEMON: The hot toy for Christmas might be the Tyson
doll, the first gay black man doll.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson sells for $50.95 at Does Your Father Know, on Castro
Street, but hurry, because the heat is on. Boxer Mike Tyson's
people (famous boxers have ``people'') are threatening to sue the
dollmaker, and so are representatives of supermodel Tyson Beckford.
</P>
<P>
   I hear the Tyson Chicken Co. people are considering a lawsuit,
too, but their case will be weakened by the fact that all of their
chickens are white, straight and female.
</P>
<P>
   JUST IN TIME for the newish Millennium, Spenger's Seafood Grotto
is ready to step back into the past.
</P>
<P>
   The million-year-old Berkeley eatery reopens Saturday after long
renovation, and this could become the seafood capital of the known
universe.
</P>
<P>
   There's new stuff on the menu, but I am assured that all
traditions will be honored, too. Example: Martinis are stirred, not
shaken. Same with memories.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD CENTRAL: Yes, you get all your irrelevant eating news here.
A recent mention of weird food fusion led to these bits of tid:
</P>
<P>
   Susan Cochran reports a recent visit to a German restaurant in
Syracuse, N.Y., where she tried the Reuben egg roll _ corned beef
and sauerkraut in the rice wrap. ... Another reader says don't
forget about the old Berkeley joint, Robbie's Chinese-American
Hofbrau. ... And Ken Thompson dined at the English pub Fox and
Goose in Sacramento and ordered the Eggs Benedict Arnold. They
turned on him.
</P>
<P>
   PUZZLED by e-addresses? So was Grant Richards, who saw an ad
board on the side of a bus for ``gotahoe.com.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Got a hoe''? Is this a web site for a garden-tool store, or
for a pimp?
</P>
<P>
   THE DMV fines us if we're not up to date, so how do they explain
this:
</P>
<P>
   Debby Baizer overpaid her registration fee, so the DMV sent her
a refund check, along with a note on DMV letterhead that states
that the governor of California is Pete Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   The gov that keeps on giving. At least the DMV has used up all
its Reagan stationery.
</P>
<P>
   LOUSY TIPPER? Not Danny Glover, says taxi driver Alley Cat, in
response to item about Glover stiffing a local waiter. ``I took him
home from the airport, he gave me $40 on a $32 fare.``
</P>
<P>
   Other readers, and at least one local cabbie, tell me Glover's
gripe about New York cabbies not picking up black riders goes for
S.F., too.
</P>
<P>
   JUST IN CASE you have a body part free when you're driving to
work, cell-phoning, coffee-drinking, radio-punching, bird-flipping
and toenail-polishing, there's this: Commuter Aerobics. ``Don't
spin your wheels, squeeze your butt,'' says the ad, and for many
reasons I don't want to hear any more, OK?
</P>
<P>
   DULY NOTED: Construction workers who assemble the steel
framework of a building are not steelworkers, but ironworkers.
Steelworkers work in steel mills.
</P>
<P>
   I have no idea what's the proper way to refer to people who iron
shirts or steal steel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
