<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-AWARD02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dole to get UD's Leadership with Virtue Award
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ She served five U.S. presidents and tried to
become one herself. She led the nation's largest philanthropic
organization for nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Elizabeth Dole, included in Americans' list of the
world's top 10 most admired women, will add yet another distinction
to an already packed resume: She will receive the University of
Dayton's first Leadership with Virtue Award.
</P>
<P>
   Dole was selected from among more than two dozen nominees, said
Jack Proud, chairman of the virtue award selection committee and
past president of UD's national alumni association. The
association, along with the university, sponsors the award.
</P>
<P>
   Nominations came from UD alumni around the country and from
Miami Valley community members, Proud said.
</P>
<P>
   UD officials unveiled the Leadership with Virtue award in April,
saying it will be presented annually to leaders who blend a high
level of integrity, vision, inclusion and emotional balance with
their professional achievements.
</P>
<P>
   UD officials have scheduled a news conference Thursday to
announce Dole's selection. UD is organizing a leadership symposium
to accompany the presentation of the first award Feb.10.
</P>
<P>
   The university also plans to endow a one-year scholarship in
each recipient's name to be awarded to a UD junior.
</P>
<P>
   Dole ``really personifies the criteria we were looking for,''
Proud said.
</P>
<P>
   Dole has served as Federal Trade Commission member, secretary of
transportation and secretary of labor. For eight years, until
January 1999, she served as president of the American Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Women Executives in State Government gave Dole its
Lifetime Achievement Award for helping women and minorities break
through the ``glass ceiling.'' Later that year, she was inducted
into the Safety and Health Hall of Fame International for
accomplishments in transportation, workplace and blood safety
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Dole's name emerged last year when UD officials and alumni began
organizing the annual award, Proud said, but her name was removed
from the list when she announced her candidacy for the Republican
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Giving the award to an active political candidate would have
been viewed as overly partisan, Proud said. But when Dole bowed out
of the race earlier this fall, her name was restored to
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fisher writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
