<HEADER>
A6000 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-KELSO-COLUMN02-COX     12-01 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A license to bore: family e-mail tales
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ I've finally figured out the mystery of the
personal, lengthy and, yes, often dull family Christmas newsletters
I've been getting by e-mail from Dan Eggleston.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the wonders of e-mail, I've been receiving old
holiday newsletters from Eggleston for -- few months or so.
</P>
<P>
   But until Saturday, when I messaged him back by e-mail to ask
him about these holiday newsletters, I didn't know who Eggleston
is.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't e-mail great? Have you noticed how much of it makes you
wonder, ``Why the heck are they sending me this?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The year started off with lots of family and company
combined,'' begins a 1956 Yule newsletter Eggleston shipped me.
``Our cousin Frank Caldwell and his Hawaiian wife Emily sent us a
Christmas card from nearby and ended up living with us for several
months. The high spot of the visit was when Frank drove down to
Florida to bring back Emily's daughter Ilima and her three small
fry. While Ilima danced hulas with the Ringling circus tour,
Mahailani, Kaikili, and Keavi, ranging from 3 1/2 down to 1 1/2,
kept us busy and amused.''
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, except for Ringling, I have no idea who any of these
people are.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, these holiday greetings are the work of the
late Lester Allen Eggleston of San Antonio, a fire protection
engineer for Esso who sent out an annual Christmas newsletter to
300 to 400 people from 1955 to 1974.
</P>
<P>
   And now they are being recirculated via e-mail to 37 people by
his son, Dan Eggleston, 53, a math teacher at Lamar Middle School.
</P>
<P>
   And I am on the list. Some people are just born lucky.
</P>
<P>
   I should mention that each newsletter is thousands of words
long. Every French horn lesson, bout of tonsillitis and new
household appliance is chronicled.
</P>
<P>
   So why is Dan sending these things out? ``Ah, I feel they're
interesting and they sort of comment on our culture back in the
'50s and '60s,'' Dan said. ``So people our age, it would bring back
memories of what it was like back then.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, like real boring.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure the Egglestons are a wonderful family. And it's
thoughtful of Dan to share his family's history with me through his
dad's Christmas letters. Otherwise I wouldn't have known that in
1963 ``Pixie the Pup is as black as ever'' and ``trails after Polly
all day.''
</P>
<P>
   It's just that e-mail makes me wonder if the information age has
been misnamed. Maybe it should have been named the unsolicited note
age.
</P>
<P>
   I've even come up with a system that lets me identify trash
e-mail without even reading it. If the header listing the names of
the recipients is as long as the text, it's out of there. And any
``opportunity of a lifetime'' e-mail with $ signs sprinkled
throughout the text gets the ax immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``In August the deep freeze quit,'' the '56 Christmas newsletter
reveals. ``Getting a new one in the cellar was an undertaking!''
And if Uncle Ernie had gotten a hernia during the process, I'm sure
we would have heard about it.
</P>
<P>
   So how are these family newsletters received by the people who
get them? ``Some people just read them and don't say anything,''
Dan admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jkelso(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
