<HEADER>
A6001 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN02-COX     12-01 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Imploring saints has ring to it
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Call the insurance company, my husband would say
from time to time, after my wedding band walked away from the
nightstand one night.
</P>
<P>
   Jim thinks that a missing object should be declared forever lost
within, say, five seconds of its disappearance. I take a much more
hopeful view, preferring to wait at least five years. My jewelry
box is full of mismatched earrings, the sock drawer stuffed with
unmatched socks.
</P>
<P>
   This is not because I am the perennial optimist of the pair.
Quite the contrary. He's the one who had a happy-go-lucky, normal
childhood; I'm the one who developed the premature frown mark from
worrying about nuclear disarmament and world hunger.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that I grew up with St. Anthony, and Jim did
not.
</P>
<P>
   Jim is a Methodist. His church is glorious this time of year,
bedecked with greens, resplendent with ribbons and Christmas trees.
But it's also a bit lonely, with nary an icon or a saint to be
found.
</P>
<P>
   How do they manage? They can't invoke St. Anne when they need to
find a mate: ``St. Anne, St. Anne, send me a man.'' They can't bury
a St. Joseph statue when they need to sell their house. They can't
soothe toothaches by imploring St. Apollonia, or ease business
tension by calling on St. Raphael, patron saint of happy meetings.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the most useful saint of all: the 13th-century
St. Anthony of Padua, the patron saint of lost articles.
</P>
<P>
   No, we weren't one of those vulgar Catholic households in which
you chanted, ``Tony, Tony, look around, something's lost and can't
be found.'' But when something stubbornly refused to turn up, Mom
would start singing to St. Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   Is it pure superstition, mere quaint Catholic custom? Not so,
says Father Jerry Chinchar, a campus minister at the University of
Dayton. ``St. Anthony is my buddy; he helps me out a lot,''
Chinchar says. ``I like the image that the saints are our friends _
our friends who have already made it, and are face to face with
God. It's not as if we can't go to God, but sometimes it's easier
to go to a friend who might have an in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in the great Christian tradition that we're not alone in
our journey of faith, that we're in this together.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike our parents, Catholics of my generation are a bit
sheepish about the whole business. We call on St. Anthony only when
all other hope is gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call the insurance company,'' Jim said after the wedding band
had been missing for several months.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't want another ring,'' I whined. ``I want this one.
It has sentimental value.''
</P>
<P>
   I lost the ring in the house, so it had to be here somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   We did a top-to-bottom house cleaning, peering under every rug,
every love seat, every bureau. We vacuumed and sifted through the
vacuum bag. No ring.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I told myself, time for the heavy artillery: St. Anthony. I
said a silent prayer, even sang Mom's old song when Jim wasn't in
earshot.
</P>
<P>
   That night, before I flopped into bed, I fished once again in my
ring-holder, as I had 1,000 times before. I turned over my
lightning-bolt TCB pin. Underneath it, perma-bonded with something
green _ lollipop residue _ lay my wedding band.
</P>
<P>
   It had been in my ring-holder all along, stuck underneath my
lightning-bolt pin. TCB, for Taking Care of Business.
</P>
<P>
   As in Elvis.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, as in St. Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
