r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN02-COX     12-01 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hospital bureaucracy hinders doctors, kills patients
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ You have less to fear sharing the road with a
no-brakes, double-clutching 18-wheeler driven by sleep-deprived
trucker with white-line fever than you have checking yourself into
a local hospital.
</P>
<P>
   In U.S. hospitals alone, medical mistakes kill between 44,000
and 98,000 Americans. The nation's annual highway death toll is
about 43,450.
</P>
<P>
   This little bombshell was dropped on the American public Monday
in a new report by the National Academy of Sciences' Institute of
Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Equity in outrage needs to be directed toward deaths due to
medical errors compared to deaths due to highway accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that Mothers Against Drunk Driving is a respected
nationwide organization that works diligently to impose stricter
penalties against motorists who drive while impaired by alcohol.
MADD members deserve credit for changing pubic attitudes as well as
laws.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to MADD, Mothers Against Medical Mistakes, or some
similar name, would be a far larger organization if size
corresponds to risk.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 98,000 Americans are killed each year due to medical
errors in hospitals alone. That number (more than double annual
highway fatalities) does not count all the other Americans who die
due to medical errors committed outside U.S. hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   American patients killed each year due to medical errors likely
is double the number of Americans killed in the nine-year Vietnam
War.
</P>
<P>
   Health care in the United States, according to the report, ``is
a decade or more behind other high-risk industries in its attention
to ensuring basic safety'' to avoid such deadly errors as making
wrong diagnoses, removing wrong organs or prescribing wrong drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In a remark that hovered between sarcasm and despair, the
chairman of the panel that conducted the study, William Richardson,
said, ``These stunningly high rates of medical errors _ resulting
in deaths, permanent disability and unnecessary suffering _ are
simply unacceptable in a medical system that promises first to `do
no harm.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was Hippocrates, the ancient Greek physician recognized as
the father of medicine, who said, ``As to diseases, make a habit of
two things _ to help, or at least, to do no harm.''
</P>
<P>
   A doctor friend of mine, now passed on, once told me that
doctors would have nothing to fear from malpractice lawsuits if
they treated their patients as friends and practiced the medicine
they learned in medical school.
</P>
<P>
   He told the same thing to his colleagues at a county medical
society meeting during a discussion of malpractice lawsuits and
medical liability insurance. As a result, he lost all patient
referrals from fellow doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Hippocrates also lamented that the most distinguished art of
medicine ``through the ignorance of those who practice it, and of
those who casually judge such practitioners, it is now of all the
arts by far the least esteemed.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps now, more than two millennia later, we are back where we
started. Bad medical practices are giving health-care providers a
bad name.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that doctors caused many of their own problems.
Patients who have been talked down to by arrogant doctors do not
hesitate to sue just to get even, in my opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors nowadays are more like my old doctor friend, friendly
and respectful. Now, however, they are surrounded by infuriating
layers of arrogant bureaucracy in HMOs, clinics, and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Patient safety is jeopardized now less by the recklessness of
individual doctors or nurses than by the way clinics, hospitals and
pharmacies operate, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Many more Americans are killed in hospitals than in highway
accidents. Try to ignore that fact.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco,
Texas. E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
