<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991201.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 11:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6010 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-BIOTECH02-COX     12-01 2629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia seeking to cultivate new field
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In Georgia, biotech _ pardon the pun _ is growing.
</P>
<P>
   You could tell by the number of hands reaching out to greet
Russell ``Rusty'' French as he maneuvered slowly toward a table at
the Ritz-Carlton in Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 investors, professionals and company executives
had gathered at the tony hotel last month for the first-ever
investor forum for biotechnology in the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   French, a partner with the venture capital firm of Noro-Mosely,
was stopped every few feet to grasp another hand _ an entrepreneur
searching for an injection of capital or maybe a rival investor
like French hoping to strike biotech paydirt.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of companies wanted to be there, and organizers pared the
field down to 21 hopefuls, including a handful from Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't have done this conference five years ago,'' French
said. ``We wouldn't have had the critical mass. And five years from
now, it's just going to explode.''
</P>
<P>
   But that combustion depends on a kind of chain-reaction in the
region, he said. ``We need more successes to drive investment in
this region. This generates investment and investment enables
success.''
</P>
<P>
   In metro Atlanta, the process of building a biotech industry is
picking up speed. The question is, can the acceleration continue?
</P>
<P>
   Three factors are crucial: research, talent and money. That
brew, often seasoned with state funds, produced the spectacular
growth of all manner of technology in Silicon Valley. The same mix
is at work in pretty much every area where biotech is prospering,
including Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The standard biotech play is the same as any technology,''
said Dan Giannini, analyst with PricewaterhouseCoopers. ``The right
resources, the right research, the right people willing to invest.
Atlanta is a little behind the technology curve, but it is coming
into its own.''
</P>
<P>
   The climate is right: the economy of the region _ especially
Atlanta _ has been growing with an allure that persuades
professionals by the thousands to head south looking for better
weather and cheaper housing. Meanwhile, research ideas spill from
schools into the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   But to be commercialized, those notions need money _ patient
money.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the Internet dominates headlines, biotech
entrepreneurs and scientists are building a sector with growth that
is far slower, but with possibilities potentially even more
radical. The Internet seems poised to accelerate communication, to
reshape the economy and to transform how humans gather and use
information. Biotech, by contrast, may transform who we are.
</P>
<P>
   The sector for a while during the 1980s was the darling of Wall
Street, then slumped. Companies that needed federal approval for
for food products often took nearly a decade to move from lab to
market.
</P>
<P>
   The sector still has grand promise, but _ unlike the Net _ its
potential payback is measured in years, not weeks, days or hours.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Georgia began investing in infrastructure
and recruiting the experts needed to build a biotech industry.
Laboratories were funded and positions of ``eminent scholar''
established by the Georgia Research Alliance, a coalition of
government, university and industry.
</P>
<P>
   About half the GRA's investments are now in life sciences,
according to GRA President William J. Todd. ``There is great
opportunity, and we are at the very early stages of seeing a
return. All the indications are very positive. We think that it's
beginning to pay dividends.''
</P>
<P>
   With success of companies like Artherogenics, and Inhibitex,
Georgia will not be left out of the next wave of technology, Todd
said. ``We do believe that the next 20 years will be defined as the
age of biology, just the last 20 years have been the age of
information.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Georgia remains a bit player in biotech.
</P>
<P>
   In places like Silicon Valley and Boston, biotech has already
gone through several cycles of hype and disappointment, producing
hundreds of hopefuls and even _ in Amgen and Genentech _ a few
multibillion dollar companies. The nation has 1,283 biotech
companies, according to the Biotechnology Industry Association. The
deepest well of biotech is California, with several hundred
companies, followed by Massachusetts, New Jersey and the
Baltimore-Washington corridor.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, an informal survey produced the names of about 40
mostly small companies in Georgia with a biotech or biomedical
slant. Some, like Proxima Therapeutics are makers of devices. Some,
like Solvay Pharmaceuticals, are units of larger companies based
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Athens-based ProLinia, work at the very core of
biotech _ cloning.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the relatively modest collection of companies, money is
flowing to biotech in the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia has some of the key factors for biotech success _
chiefly an energetic system of universities that spin off biotech
companies and the research and talent needed to fuel them.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Georgia has programs in agriculture and
veterinary medicine that are among the world's largest.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech recently christened the Parker Petit Institute for
Bioengineering and Bioscience.
</P>
<P>
   Emory University has a nationally respected medical school and
solid science programs and plans a high-profile biotech center.
</P>
<P>
   Cadres of researchers toil at Georgia State and Clark Atlanta
University, whose graduates include many scientists and
technicians. The city also boasts one of the world's elite research
engines, the Centers for Disease Control.
</P>
<P>
   A glance at the biotech sector proves the interplay of commerce
and research.
</P>
<P>
   Among Georgia companies based on biomedical and biotechnology
developed at UGA are Abel Scientific, Aureozyme, AviGenics, EPD
International, Pharmamax Biomedical, Pharmasset, ProLinia,
Recombinant Peptide Technologies, Spay Safe, United AgriCorp., and
Zymex Scientific.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Georgia-based, biotech companies spun out by Emory are
AtheroGenics, CytRx, Neotonus, Novoste and Pharmasset.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the strong life sciences programs in the universities,
there is no surplus of talented, experienced managers. For them,
Atlanta's positives as a place to live are balanced with a career
risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to convince somebody to leave an area where, if their
job goes away, they know they will find another job quickly,'' said
William Johnston, president and chief executive of Inhibitex Inc.
``The downside of biotech in Atlanta is that I have to say (to a
potential executive) that I will give you a quality of life step up
that is worth the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   To trump that concern, companies can use enticements like stock
in the future as well as the lure of the area itself. Ultimately,
it is a career and a life decision _ and all sorts of choices are
possible, said AviGenics President and Chief Executive Officer Carl
Marhaver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are interested in taking on that risk, and some
people are not,'' shrugged Marhaver, who commutes to his Athens
office from Wichita, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   From research comes ideas, but without funding _ and the right
expertise _ those notions can stall.
</P>
<P>
   Consider ChemFree, which produces freeze-dried grease-eating
microbes that clean engines. When the company went looking for
money, it took a year of searching to find in Norcross-based
Intelligent Systems an investor to purchase a majority stake, said
Vice President Tom McNally. ``We approached a lot of conventional
sources. For most of the venture capitalists, it was too far out
five years ago. The idea of using bugs to eat grease was pretty
bizarre.''
</P>
<P>
   But one year's bizarre idea could be the next year's
conventional wisdom. That interchange between entrepreneur and
investor is the way the deal is done, no matter the technology or
geography, said Lothar Krinke, principal in the health industries
practice of consultant A.T. Kearney. ``The engine has always been
and will continue to be good ideas and good people. But cash right
now is tight. All the venture capital money is going to e-business,
not biotech.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not all.
</P>
<P>
   Alliance Technology Ventures was created in the early 1990s to
pump capital to promising companies, especially in metro Atlanta.
The fund last year gave $76 million to 11 companies. Among the
fund's $100 million in investments are several in biotech,
including EnSurg, Inhibitex and AtheroGenics.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Henos, a general partner in ATV, says the Southeast has
made progress, although remaining far behind the venture centers of
Boston and Silicon Valley. ``Atlanta and the Southeast _ the region
is a strong No. 3 or No. 4.''
</P>
<P>
   At least some money now is looking for biotechnology, coming
from within the South _ and outside.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Atlanta-based Noro-Moseley, investors at last
month's conference included Alpharetta-based Cordova Ventures,
Intersouth Partners of Durham and California-based Silicon Valley
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's more established players can serve as a source of
scientists and support for newcomers to the sector.
</P>
<P>
   But some of those in the emerging sector still fear for its
future.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston praised the state's focus on getting companies afloat
but warned that many may founder when released from the protection
of the university incubator. ``Atlanta is not a fertile environment
right now to take a company from the incubator to the next step.
That's a gap, and the big issue is capital.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of a large cluster of companies handicaps development,
he said. ``It's very hard to find lab space or get somebody to
build a lab building for you. In Boston, a developer knows that if
the (biotech) company goes out of business or moves, somebody else
will take the space. Until we get a critical mass here, it is going
to be difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Atlanta doesn't boast spectacular numbers of research
institutions, endless oceans of venture capital or hundreds of
already flourishing biotech companies, the area does have all three
components in more modest supply _ and that is often enough.
</P>
<P>
   Look at Proxima Therapeutics, based in Alpharetta mostly by
happenstance and yet apparently happy to stay and grow. Proxima
makes devices _ catheters _ that can deliver concentrated radiation
to a limited area after surgery for brain or breast cancer. The
technology is now in clinical testing at five locations, including
Emory, but it was developed by a doctor at Johns Hopkins.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Patrick, Proxima president and CEO, said he was hired
when it was still a ``virtual'' company. He happened to be in
Atlanta. So he built the company here. When he looked for someone
to test the brain tumor procedure, he found Dr. Jeff Olson at
Emory. When it was time to test the breast cancer procedure, the
work was done at the University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   About half the top executives were recruited from elsewhere,
Patrick said. ``We have had excellent luck attracting people to
Atlanta. We have 16 employees and virtually no turnover. The few
issues that we have in Atlanta are outweighed by positives.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Proxima is has found the money it needed. A 1997
financing brought $4 million. A second round last year raked in
$11.8 million, Patrick said. ``We have raised more than $16
million. None of it from Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   M. Christine Jacobs, the chairman, president and CEO of
Buford-based Theragenics, argues that the region will not become a
biomed or biotech hotbed until the sector becomes a priority.
Schools and government could do more, she said. ``No university has
ever met with us and said, 'what kind of student could we help you
with?' Instead, they just crank them out and let us decide if they
fit our mold.''
</P>
<P>
   Theragenics, which makes tiny radioactive ``seeds'' that are
implanted in prostate cancers to deliver radiation locally, is an
oldster by biotech standards, founded in 1981 and taken public in
1987. But its experience buttresses the notion that the South is
not yet fully funding its entrepreneurs. ``The reality is that when
we really needed money and support we had to go somewhere else,''
Jacobs said. ``To a new company, I would say, fight to keep
yourself in the South, but be ready to travel to get your money.''
</P>
<P>
   For those accustomed to the blitz of Internet hype or the
multibillion deals of the huge telecommunications companies,
biotech may seem like a slow-moving curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   But despite their languid development, biotech companies look to
provide valuable tools to some large, lucrative markets. While
their time horizon may be long, many of their targets translate
into billions of dollars in treatments and diagnoses.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Proxima Therapeutics hopes to be in the market in
a year, and that market is potentially lucrative.
</P>
<P>
   There are 1.2 million new cases of cancer diagnosed in the
United States each year. About 800,000 of them are ``solid'' tumors
that might be candidates for removal and follow-up radiation _ and
the more effective the radiation, the better the chance for a cure
without side-effects.
</P>
<P>
   Once Proxima succeeds, the company would likely stay, Patrick
said. Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``Inertia,'' he said. ``We've got relationships with lawyers and
advisers. We've got a solid team, and people like it here. I can't
imagine telling people that in six months we are moving to Silicon
Valley. You've been living in a new house and now you'll only be
able to afford an apartment. Or to Boston. People would picture a
much smaller house. With snow on the roof.''
</P>
<P>
   AtheroGenics is developing new drugs to treat cancer and
atherosclerosis. Russell Medford, CEO, president and co-founder of
the 48-employee firm, says the economics are potentially huge.
</P>
<P>
   While optimistic, Medford said the company is still shy of
making a profit on its technology.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Schering-Plough has bet that it will work on humans,
signing a contract with ArtheroGenics worth an estimated $189
million. Schering-Plough, an $8.1 billion-a-year company, obtains
the right to develop, manufacture and market the AtheroGenics drug.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of arrangement _ or even an outright acquisition _ is
a common goal for start-up biotech companies, since they cannot
hope to develop the muscular worldwide distribution system of a
giant pharmaceutical company. But first, a company must mount
convincing evidence that its technology works _ and that takes
money.
</P>
<P>
   AtheroGenics is currently flush, having announced $15.9 million
injection of cash earlier this year by Cordova Ventures and other
investors.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, grease-eating microbe producer ChemFree, the
17-person company founded in 1993, sees a huge, largely untapped
market and an immediate opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is cloning.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Stice was lured from a Massachusetts company by the
GRA's offer of an eminent scholar position at the University of
Georgia. Stice founded ProLinia, a company devoted to development
of technology for cloning animals, enabling farmers to multiply the
best animals in their herds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the lab cloning right now,'' Stice said. ``We expect
about 50 to 100 animals next year. We'll be selling product next
year. We'll be selling calves.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the Southeast starting so far behind the nation's
biotech centers, is there reason to hope that the region can
compete?
</P>
<P>
   Proxima Therapeutics' CEO Patrick says the region and the
biomedical sector need each other. ``I think it's important for
Atlanta to have some very successful biomed companies. I would like
to think it could be us.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
