r l BC-TECH-CHICKEN02-COX     12-01 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-CHICKEN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Firm covers chicken and the egg
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It used to be that when you mentioned incubators and
chickens, you were likely to mean the heaters that kept baby chicks
warm so they could grow up to lay the eggs that made more chickens.
</P>
<P>
   Now, you might be referring to the offices and labs of a company
that is genetically engineering the chickens and that's growing up
in an incubator that nurtures new companies.
</P>
<P>
   AviGenics Inc. occupies part of an incubator for small biotech
companies at the University of Georgia. The company is working on
technologies aimed at producing both better chickens and more
nutritious and healthy eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Like the baby chicks in a traditional poultry farm, AviGenics
represents a kind of hope. The company is far too young and small
to produce revenue _ let alone profit. But the Georgia Research
Alliance, a coalition of state, industry and academia, is nurturing
AviGenics in partnership with the University of Georgia. The hope
is that AviGenics and similar companies will within a few years
produce products that will improve the work done by Georgia
agriculture, while benefiting consumers.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, it is hoped they will be growing, healthy,
profitable companies whose success will ripple through the
community.
</P>
<P>
   AviGenics was born in the research lab of UGA scientist Robert
Ivarie.
</P>
<P>
   Although the company also plans to clone superior chickens for
food, AviGenics believes its technology can be used to produce
generic pharmaceuticals when the patents expire on many of the
lucrative drugs now on the market.
</P>
<P>
   The company's growth reflects the range of needs in Georgia
biotech.
</P>
<P>
   First: talent.
</P>
<P>
   AviGenics has been advertising four job openings with vastly
different criteria. A vice president of strategic planning must
have more than five years' experience in a ``medium or large life
sciences company.''
</P>
<P>
   A research associate for cell biology needs a bachelor's of
science or master's degree as well as several years experience in
``tissue culture.''
</P>
<P>
   A technician needs a bachelor's degree in one of the right
sciences _ experience with DNA cloning preferred.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, AviGenics is seeking a poultry caretaker, someone with
experience caring for and breeding chickens.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the 18-employee company has hired locally but has also
recruited talent from as far away as Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   President and Chief Executive Carl Marhaver praised the
University of Georgia for producing high-caliber graduates, but
acknowledged that the area is not flush with experienced biotech
talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Athens (Georgia) is not the perfect spot, but we are not going
to let that be an obstacle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Second: money.
</P>
<P>
   The company raised $4 million last year in venture funding and
is now looking for a $10 million injection. Marhaver said he often
hears talk of investors ignoring biotech in order to jump on the
latest ``dot.com'' with an Internet scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think they don't care anymore about a diversified
portfolio? There is still venture capital for good returns on an
investment in biotech.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many struggling start-ups, AviGenics would also be pleased
to have a large pharmaceutical company buy a majority stake,
Marhaver said.
</P>
<P>
   Third: research.
</P>
<P>
   AviGenics works in labs built as part of an effort by the
Georgia Research Alliance and the University of Georgia to lure and
nurture biotech. Among the other tenants is ProLinia Inc., a
company that is focused on cloning.
</P>
<P>
   Marhaver said the efforts at nudging along biotech have made a
difference for AviGenics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The GRA and UGA have made it easy for us to stay and to be
successful,'' Marhaver said. ``Without them, a lot of us wouldn't
get as far as we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
