<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 11:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6013 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TECH-FUNJOB02-COX     12-01 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-FUNJOB02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Surfing the Net to save you time
 &HT;    By Maria Mallory
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bonnie Bertram can thank a novel for her job.
</P>
<P>
   On a six-hour flight from Silicon Valley to Atlanta, Bertram was
locked in a debate about the book with a guy sitting next to her.
She liked it. He didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fought the entire plane ride, across the country,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Still arguing at the time they reached baggage claim at
Hartsfield International Airport, the guy _ Jim Lanzone, co-founder
of Atlanta-based eTour.com _ liked Bertram so much he offered her a
job.
</P>
<P>
   Lanzone pictured Bertram as the new editor in chief for eTour, a
Web-surfing guide that combs the Internet for what it deems the
best, quirkiest and most creative Web sites. As Queen Surfer,
Bertram would lead a group of young and scrappy professional Web
surfers who sift the Internet in search of ``cool'' sites.
</P>
<P>
   It was a job that paid $60,000 to $90,000 annually, plus stock
options. It was a great offer.
</P>
<P>
   Bertram wasn't interested _ at first.
</P>
<P>
   With more than a decade of journalism experience, Bertram was
covering the Internet when she met Lanzone. A 1986 graduate of the
University of California at Berkeley with dual degrees in English
and humanities, she had steadily worked her way up the ladder. Her
first job was as an editorial assistant (read: glorified secretary)
for Seventeen magazine, after which she went on to land jobs that
included an assistant editor spot at Premier magazine and a
producer's post at ``NewsStand: CNN &AMP; Fortune,'' the television
program that sent her on assignment to Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   With this career path behind her, eTour was a detour that
Bertram didn't care to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``I initially said no because I had always thought that
interactive jobs were for people who couldn't cut it in the
traditional media,'' she admits.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bertram was intrigued with the Web. ``It was
such a fascinating world, and I felt like I was an outsider,'' she
recalls. ``I wanted to be a part of the news, not just covering it.
I thought if I could be on the ground floor, why not?''
</P>
<P>
   Bertram officially took the Surfer Queen throne in September,
after unofficially trying the job for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, the move from producer to surfer wasn't the step down
she had once figured. ``I was totally wrong,'' Bertram says. ``The
Internet is the story now. We just skip the step of writing the
story and bring (Web sites) directly to you.''
</P>
<P>
   The surfers for eTour claim to harvest the best of the best for
their more than half-million members. Unlike some services that use
computer programs or Artificial Intelligence to track high-traffic
Web pages, Bertram says her staff does the work of judging what's
worthy to be included on the eTour database.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not just taking you to where the traffic is, we're
taking you to good sites,'' contends Bertram, who spends much of
her time supervising site selection.
</P>
<P>
   ETour scans ``best sites'' lists such as those published by
Artigen, New York magazine, The New Yorker and Mademoiselle
magazine, in addition to wading through the nooks and crannies of
the Net in search of sites. The surfers look for sites that aren't
too commercial, don't take too long to download and that are
creative, fun _ and clean, says Bertram.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be careful,'' she laughs. ``The sites that seem
totally innocent, you have to click through like four times because
you never know what's in there.''
</P>
<P>
   ETour arranges its best recommendations in broad categories that
span areas such as arts and entertainment, news, shopping and
sports. The firm plans to add African-American, Hispanic and other
special interests by mid-December.
</P>
<P>
   Subscribers to this free service customize their interest lists
by choosing to receive sites within more than 100 categories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll say to you, `You like gardening? Cooking? We'll give you
the best gardening, cooking sites out there,' '' says Bertram.
</P>
<P>
   Bertram and crew tackle current events in much the same way. In
their new Watercooler feature, they pull together a hodgepodge of
related sites.
</P>
<P>
   A recent example: Following a federal judge's finding of fact
declaring Microsoft a monopoly, eTour produced hyperlinks that
ranged from excerpts from speeches delivered by Microsoft Chairman
Bill Gates to the wacky ``Mr. T Takes on Bill Gates'' Web page.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every real story has an online component,'' says Bertram.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
