<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-REINDEER02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    So, you don't believe in Florida reindeer? Read onBy Tim
O'Meilia
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ So there's no miniature sleigh with
eight tiny reindeer. And no little old driver, so lively and quick.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, this is South Florida. You get two reindeer, not so tiny,
and be happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm Beach Zoo at Dreher Park is doing you and your kids a
favor.
</P>
<P>
   Your tropical-born offspring have never seen genuine
antler-growing, lichen-eating, sleigh-pulling reindeer?
</P>
<P>
   Meet Chelsea and her 8-month-old calf, Mistletoe. (Dasher,
Dancer, et al. were otherwise engaged). On the weekend, have your
picture taken with Chelsea. $6. BYOS (Bring Your Own Santa).
</P>
<P>
   ``Reindeer only come through here once a year, usually at
night,'' explained zoo curator Dave Wood scientifically.
</P>
<P>
   The zoo has created a mock-up of the Teller Station, 72 miles
north of Nome, Alaska, where reindeer research is done, to make the
reindeer (a.k.a. caribou) feel comfy in their sand corral.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's Rudolph?'' 4-year-old Heather Doolin of Stuart wanted
to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudolph is still at the North Pole. He's exercising for the
big trip,'' explained Assistant Education Curator Kristen
Christensen, who also knows what are reindeer games and whether
reindeer do, in fact, live at the North Pole.
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea and Mistletoe are from Snowmass, Colo. The Flying Deer
Ranch rents them out for the season _ $4,700 a pair through Dec.
31.
</P>
<P>
   But then the semi-permanent snow-white tent built to withstand
140 mph winds and the pair of air-conditioners keeping the reindeer
chilled at 54 degrees cost $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Alvin and Peggy Brown, longtime zoo supporters, donated the tent
which will remain and be used for money-raising events, lectures
and education classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we break even or keep our attendance up, then it will be a
success,'' Wood said. Volunteers are selling reindeer antler
headbands and other trinkets. Kids can touch genuine reindeer
antlers and examine food that reindeer eat.
</P>
<P>
   Adults can learn a little, too. Reindeer are raised for food by
the Inuit, the people once called Eskimos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very much like beef, but it's 22 percent protein and 3
percent fat,'' explained zoo volunteer Chris Fisher. Lean beef is
about 10 percent fat. ``It has the taste and consistency of beef.
The Inuit prefer it to chicken or beef.''
</P>
<P>
   Reindeer a la Rudolph. Goes best with a nice cabernet.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know that:
</P>
<P>
   _ Montgomery Ward department store invented ``Rudolph the
Red-Nosed Reindeer'' in 1935?
</P>
<P>
   _ Reindeer antlers are like fingerprints, unique to each? And
that antlers fall off each year and grow back more elaborately?
</P>
<P>
   _ It wasn't until 1949 that cowboy singer Gene Autry recorded
the first version of Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer?
</P>
<P>
   _ The wide hooves of reindeer act as snowshoes in the snow and
as paddles when they swim?
</P>
<P>
   _ Reindeer didn't become part of the American scene until
Clement Moore wrote A Visit from St. Nicholas in 1823?
</P>
<P>
   Tim O'Meilia writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: Timomeilia(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
