<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS02-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    TAKE ONE OF TWO
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: Several months ago, I read in two newspapers that Bob Barr
had been fined for fund-raising irregularities. Details of the
settlement differed in the two articles. Can you clarify?
</P>
<P>
   A: The settlement between Barr (R-Ga.) and the Federal Election
Commission was for just over $28,000. The complaints stemmed from
Barr's first election to Congress in 1994 and his subsequent 1996
re-election campaign. The FEC found that Barr had accepted some
$100,000 in contributions during the two elections that exceeded
the $1,000-a-person limit that individuals can give. The commission
also found that Barr had failed to report certain contributions
every 48 hours, failed to identify occupations of some of his
donors, and failed to itemize some of his contributions.
</P>
<P>
   FEC spokeswoman Sharon Snyder said the conciliation agreements
called for a $12,055 civil penalty in the 1994 campaign and a
$16,000 civil penalty in the 1996 campaign. Details can be found
online at the Federal Election Commission Web site _ www.fec.gov _
by looking under news releases and clicking on ``August 27, 1999 _
Compliance Cases Made Public.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr's attorney, Benjamin Ginsberg, said at the time that Barr
didn't intentionally violate the FEC rules. The congressman has
hired a full-time staffer to make sure that future contributions
meet the rules, and his computer software has been updated to
double-check his donor lists.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I find the bluish-purple headlights on newer cars blinding
and very dangerous at night. What makes them so bright, and are
they legal?
</P>
<P>
   A: The high-intensity-discharge headlights use xenon gas to
produce an azure-white light that approximates dayight. As
explained in the April issue of Consumer Reports, both the National
Highway Traffic Safety Administration and the American Automobile
Association have reported mounting complaints from motorists who,
like you, find the lights distracting, especially head-on.
</P>
<P>
   While NHTSA confirms that the new headlights meet all
requirements and aren't any brighter than old ones, glare can be a
problem. The sharp contrast between lit and unlit areas also may
give oncoming motorists a temporary sense of being blinded.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Reports advises motorists whose vehicles have such
lights to keep them properly aimed by a professional.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have misplaced my 16-year-old daughter's Social Security
card, and I'm amazed at how many times in the recent past I've been
asked to show it. How do we go about getting another one?
</P>
<P>
   A: Call Social Security's toll-free number, 1-800-772-1213, and
ask for an application for a replacement. Be prepared to provide
original or certified copies of approved identity documents. Check
www.ssa.gov for online information.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Someone where I work told me that Mary Kay Bergman died. She
was doing voices for the TV program ``South Park.'' Do you have any
details?
</P>
<P>
   A: She died Nov. 11 of a self-inflicted shotgun wound to the
head, according to the Los Angeles Coroner's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman, 38, who gave voice to the mothers of such ``South
Park'' characters as Stan, Cartman and Kenny, was found dead by her
husband, Dino Andrade, in their home near Venice, Calif. Her
attorney, Robert Harrison, told The Associated Press that her death
was a complete surprise, and that she had shown no signs of
depression. ``She did leave a note, a reason, but it didn't make
any sense,'' he said. ``She was a victim of mental illness and no
one knew.''
</P>
<P>
   The veteran voice-over performer was heard on both the ``Comedy
Central'' TV series and the movie ``South Park: Bigger, Longer and
Uncut.'' Her credits also included supplying voices for the ``Star
Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' video game and for movies
such as ``The Iron Giant'' and ``Mulan.'' In recent years, she had
inherited the role of Daphne in the new ``Scooby-Doo'' videos.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has the controversial estate of the late Howard Hughes ever
been settled?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. It was finalized in October 1990, 14 years after the
reclusive billionaire's death. When the dust settled from one of
the most protracted estate battles in American history _ mainly
because Hughes left no will _ Hughes' 22 cousins and their
descendants were named to receive $1 billion. According to a report
in Forbes, legal fees involved in the resolution of the affair
amounted to $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   William Rice Lummis, a Houston lawyer whose mother was Hughes'
aunt and his closest remaining relative, was the court-appointed
administrator. He reportedly convinced the cousins to quit
squabbling and agree on a potential division of the spoils. Lummis
himself borrowed $190 million to reinvest in Hughes' helicopter
business, turned it around, and sold it for $470 million, according
to Forbes. He also settled claims against the estate by the
Internal Revenue Service and California and Texas, where Hughes had
business interests.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the cash settlements, it was reported that the
cousins and descendants retained stock in Hughes-related companies
that are developing real estate projects in Nevada and California.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does the M in Texas A&AMP;M stand for?
</P>
<P>
   A: When it opened on Oct. 4, 1876, the school was named
Agricultual and Mechanical College of Texas. In 1963, the name was
changed to Texas A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read that photo ID is needed to board an airplane. Do I
have to comply?
</P>
<P>
   A: Some airlines won't let you board if you refuse to provide
it. So why create a problem? The Federal Aviation Administration
recommends that everyone _ minors excepted _ have photo ID to
expedite check-in procedures. If you don't have a photo ID, the FAA
says to be sure you have two pieces of identification, one of which
must be issued by a government authority. Otherwise, you may face
additional security scrutiny. And that will slow things down.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Jimy Williams of the Boston Red Sox has been named the
American League manager of the year. What can you tell me about his
early background, and how can I write him?
</P>
<P>
   A: Williams was born Oct. 4, 1943, in Arroyo Grande, Calif. He
graduated from Arroyo Grande High School and Fresno State
University in California, where he was an All California Collegiate
All-Star during his last two years. In 1963-64, he played at
Sturgis (South Dakota) in the semi-pro Basin League, and in 1964 he
also played for the Alaska Goldpanners. He then went to Waterloo
(Iowa) of the Midwest League, followed by the St. Louis Cardinals
of the National League. He has always played shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   A shoulder injury in the winter of 1969 shortened his pro
playing career, and he retired as an active player in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, he obtained his first managing job with the
Angels Quad Cities of Midwest League. Over the next 32 years, he
had coaching and managing jobs with several minor league teams,
followed by stints with the Toronto Blue Jays, Atlanta Braves, and
Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Write him in care of the Boston Red Sox, Fenway Park, 4 Yawkey
Way, Boston, MA 02215.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A report on state divorce rates said that except for Nevada,
most were in the South. Will you list all the states and their
ranking? Surely some of the other high-ranking states were outside
the Bible Belt.
</P>
<P>
   A: Here's the list as compiled by the Associated Press, based on
1998 statistics from the U.S. Census Bureau and the National Center
for Health Statistics. As reported, Nevada has the highest divorce
rate. Following Nevada, this is the order:
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee; Arkansas; Alabama; Oklahoma; New Hampshire; Wyoming;
Idaho; Kentucky; Arizona; Florida; Alaska; West Virginia;
Washington; Texas; North Carolina; Missouri; Mississippi; Georgia;
Oregon; New Mexico; Delaware; Virginia; Vermont; Utah; Maine; Ohio;
Kansas; Hawaii; Michigan; Nebraska; South Carolina; Montana; South
Dakota; Wisconsin; Illinois; Iowa; North Dakota; Minnesota;
Pennsylvania; Rhode Island; Maryland; New Jersey; Connecticut;
Massachusetts; New York.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics weren't available on Colorado, California, Illinois
and Louisiana. And the ranking of Texas is based on statistics from
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read that the Federal Reserve instituted a ``neutral bias''
toward interest rates. Isn't that an oxymoron? Wouldn't ``neutral
stance'' be more correct?
</P>
<P>
   A: It may sound oxymoronic, but it's the conventional phrase
used to describe the Fed's deliberate decision not to lean one way
or the other on interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A program on the History Channel referred to something called
the ``Paris gun,'' but didn't give any details. I know it was used
in World War I, but I'd like to know more about it. Can you help?
</P>
<P>
   A: The term ``Paris gun'' was given to any of three long-range
210mm German guns used to bombard Paris between March 23 and Aug.
7, 1918. Most of the emplacements were in the St. Gobain Wood near
Laon, 70 miles from Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The gun _ Pariskanonen in German _ had a barrel almost 120 feet
long, and could fire a 275-pound projectile to a range of about 80
miles. When the guns' first shells landed on Paris, people thought
they had been dropped from German bombers.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Paris guns fired 203 shells against the city, but
they failed to produce the panic and population exodus that the
Germans hoped to achieve. The advance of the Allied armies in
August 1918 ended the shelling.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
