<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS02-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    TAKE TWO OF TWO
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: When did American Samoa, Guam and Puerto Rico become part of
the United States?
</P>
<P>
   A: American Samoa, a U.S. possession, was acquired by the United
States in stages between 1900 and 1925. Guam was ceded by Spain to
the United States in 1898 after the Spanish-American War, and
became a territory on Aug. 1, 1950. Puerto Rico, a U.S.
commonwealth, was surrendered by Spain to the United States, also
in 1898, under the Treaty of Paris, with the first U.S. civil
governor appointed under the terms of the Organic Act of 1900,
known as the Foraker Act.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the book ``Band of Brothers,'' about E Company, 506th
Regiment, 101st Airborne, in France during World War II, author
Stephen Ambrose relates how a Pvt. Fritz Niland lost three brothers
in combat in one week. As a sole surviving son, he was ordered back
to the United States. Was this incident a basis for the movie
``Saving Private Ryan''?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Accounts of this incident were in the news in the summer
of 1998 when the movie was receiving so much publicity.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Ambrose stated that the narrative kernel for
the fictional account of Private Ryan was taken from ``Band of
Brothers,'' which documented the case of Fritz Niland of Tonawanda,
N.Y. Two of his brothers were killed in the D-Day invasion, and a
third was killed in Burma. Their mother received three telegrams
from the War Department (the Defense Department didn't yet exist)
within a short time frame notifying her of her sons' deaths. So her
fourth son, fighting in France, was snatched out of the front lines
by the Army and sent home.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read that ``Peanuts'' creator Charles Schulz has cancer.
How can his fans send him get-well messages? What is the outlook
for future cartoon strips?
</P>
<P>
   A: Mail can be sent to Schulz at his home, One Snoopy Place,
Santa Rosa, CA 95403-2665. The cartoonist, who turns 77 today, was
diagnosed with colon cancer after undergoing emergency surgery Nov.
16 to clear a blocked abdominal aorta. Newhouse News Service
reported that Schulz will undergo chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   United Feature Syndicate, which distributes the Peanuts comic
strip, said Schulz has worked ahead, so his daily strips are
completed for this year, and Sunday strips are completed through
Feb. 14. The syndicate added that it ``hopes and expects'' Schulz
will be able to produce new material for 2000, but if he chooses
not to do so, Peanuts strips commencing with those from 1974 will
be substituted.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it possible to order a videotape of a PBS program?
</P>
<P>
   A: In some cases, yes, but all programs aren't available on
tape. There are two ways to check the complete listing of videos
offered through PBS Home Video: online at http://shop.pbs.org/ or
by calling PBS Home Video at 1-800-645-4727.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've heard several stories over the years about Ronald Reagan
and his military service, or lack of it. Can you set the record
straight for me?
</P>
<P>
   A: On April 14, 1942, Reagan, by then an actor with such movies
as ``Love Is on the Air'' and Dark Victory'' to his credit, entered
the Army Air Corps as a second lieutenant of cavalry in reserve.
</P>
<P>
   The book ``Facts About the Presidents'' says his poor eyesight
disqualified him for combat duty. Between 1942 and 1945, he made
training films for the Army. On Dec. 9, 1945, with the rank of
captain, he received an honorable discharge.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent article reported that Georgia's first governor, John
Adam Treutlen, was brutally murdered after he moved to South
Carolina. It quoted the author of a new pamphlet about him as
saying he was drawn and quartered in front of his family. What
happened to cause such an awful event?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are few reliable details on Treutlen's murder, and the
``why'' is complicated, said Helene Riley, professor of German at
Clemson University and author of ``John Adam Treutlen: The European
Heritage of Georgia's First Governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Treutlen had many enemies as well as supporters, Riley said.
Among his enemies was William Henry Drayton of South Carolina, who
actively pursued South Carolina's efforts to annex Georgia. As
governor, Treutlen issued a proclamation offering a reward of 100
pounds for the capture of Drayton or his followers, Riley
explained. There also were disputes between rival factions of the
immigrant Salzburger community of Lutherans at Ebenezer, Ga., where
Treutlen and John Caspar Wertsch were leaders of the factions.
</P>
<P>
   When the English invaded Georgia, Treutlen fled to South
Carolina. His murder took place between January and April 1782 when
several Tories or refugees ``cut him to pieces with a sword,'' as
Riley put it. His fate wasn't reported until May 1783. The episode
is documented in the December 1965 Georgia Historical Quarterly,
No. 4, available at libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've read about the Cold War Memorial for those who served in
the military, but not necessarily during wartime. I didn't keep the
information, and now I need it. I believe it's different from the
World War II Memorial, a la Tom Hanks. Can you refresh my memory?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's not a memorial, in the manner of the proposed World War
II Memorial. What you're thinking about is the Cold War Recognition
Certificate. Established by Congress as part of the fiscal 1998
National Defense Authorization Act, the certificate is symbolic,
with no financial or other type of reward.
</P>
<P>
   All members of the armed forces and federal government civilian
personnel ``who faithfully served the United States during the Cold
War era'' are eligible. The specified dates for service are Sept.
2, 1945, to Dec. 26, 1991. The easiest way to request a certificate
is by using the request form at this Web site _
http://coldwar.army.mil/ _ but it also can be accomplished by
sending an application letter, along with documentation proving
service during the period, to Cold War, 4035 Ridge Top Road,
Fairfax, VA 22030; or faxing it to 1-800-723-9262 or 703-275-6749.
</P>
<P>
   Acceptable documentation includes any government form _ copy,
not original, because it can't be returned _ that includes the
applicant's name and Social Security number (or military service or
foreign service number) and dates of service. Expect a six-month
delay before receiving the certificate.
</P>
<P>
   For recorded information, call 703-275-6279.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the comic strip Dilbert, what is the name of Dilbert's
pointy-haired boss?
</P>
<P>
   A: The boss character has no name.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What American microbeers does Michael Jackson, described as
``the world's top brew expert,'' rate the highest?
</P>
<P>
   A: The 57-year-old Briton, heralded by the Encyclopedia of Beer
as ``the world's pre-eminent authority,'' is impressed with, to
name a few microbrews nationally, Tuppers' Hop Pocket Ale and
Tuppers' Hop Pocket Pils, Anchor Liberty Ale, Sierra Nevada Pale
Ale and Celis White.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My swimming instructor at the YMCA taught me what she called
a Trudgen stroke. She couldn't explain the origin of the name. Can
you?
</P>
<P>
   A: This is the stroke in which the swimmer uses a double
over-arm motion and a scissors kick. It's named after British
amateur swimmer John Arthur Trudgen (1852-1902), who introduced it
to Europe in 1893 after seeing it used in South America. The stroke
is regarded as the first successful above-water arm action used in
swimming. Trudgen popularized the idea of minimizing water
resistance by bringing both arms out of the water, which paved the
way for the now-common front (or Australian) crawl.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The printer printed our company Christmas cards wrong and we
have 500 that we can't use. I remember reading about a place to
send old cards where children cut off the fronts to make new cards.
Do you have that information?
</P>
<P>
   A: St. Jude's Ranch for Children, a Nevada community focusing on
the needs of abused, abandoned and neglected children of all races
and faiths, is the place.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Jude's Born Again Recycling Program started more than 30
years ago with children taking the fronts of used cards and gluing
them to preprinted card backs, then selling the cards to the
public. Children earn 15 cents for every card they make. Used
Christmas cards form the bulk of the program, but other greeting
cards are welcome, too, so it's a year-round operation. St. Jude's
requests that people send the card fronts only, with no writing on
the reverse. They need to be a size that can be trimmed to fit
5-by-7-inch card backs. Send the card fronts to: St. Jude's Ranch
for Children, 100 St. Jude's St., Boulder City, NV 89005.
</P>
<P>
   Those who wish to buy ``new'' cards made by the children can
call 1-800-492-3562. The cost for 10 cards in a package is $6.50.
Telephone orders are charged to a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm interested in Ship 41, Delta's refurbished DC-3. Is it
available for viewing by the public?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. Delta's James Ray said the plane will be used only for
major air shows and Delta-sponsored events. Its recent introductory
flight was for the benefit of Delta employees and others involved
in this particular aircraft during its initial operation by the
airline. Ship 41, named for the last two digits of its original
identification number (28341), was the second DC-3 purchased by
Delta and the first, in 1940, to carry Delta passengers on a
regularly scheduled flight.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who is the the actor who portrays Officer Davis on the TV
series ``Third Watch,'' and what is his background? Where can fans
write to him?
</P>
<P>
   A: Coby Bell plays Ty Davis Jr. A native of Orange County,
Calif., Bell is the son of Broadway veteran Michel Bell (``The
Civil War''). Before signing on for ``Third Watch,'' Bell was in
the cast of ``L.A. Doctors,'' playing Patrick Owen.
</P>
<P>
   Bell is an honors graduate of San Jose State University in
California. His first TV role was on NBC's ``ER,'' and he also has
appeared on ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,'' ``Players,'' ``Smart
Guy'' and ``The Parent Hood.'' His bio says that during his down
time, Bell enjoys playing basketball and tennis. He also sings and
plays keyboard in a band. He's active in the Big Brother mentoring
program, too.
</P>
<P>
   Bell lives in New York, where ``Third Watch'' is filmed. Write
him in care of NBC, 30 Rockefeller Plaza, New York, NY 10112.
</P>
<P>
   Q: While driving through South Carolina recently, we noticed
every single overpass on I-85 had a big red bow on it. Is this for
the holidays, or does it symbolize something else?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's intended to be a more serious message than ``happy
holidays,'' said a spokeswoman for the South Carolina Department of
Transportation. The bows are meant to call attention to the dangers
posed by drunk drivers. They were furnished by Mothers Against
Drunk Driving (MADD).
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
