<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6022 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-PARTY-TRAYS02-COX     12-01 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARTY-TRAYS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tray chic: know your options before purchasing a holiday party
platter
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It's party season. Make that party tray season,
when office managers and party hosts order a time-saving platter of
meats and cheeses for holiday celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   Every supermarket offers them. We wondered about differences in
price and quality. The natural question is which is the best, or at
least the best value.
</P>
<P>
   So we ordered six trays from five supermarkets and a deli. To be
sure of comparing similar party trays, we ordered the standard
meat-and-cheese platter at each business. Prices ranged from $18.95
to $54.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the trays were billed as serving 10 to 14, with one
serving eight to 10. At the two stores that sell the trays with a
per-person price, we ordered a tray for 12. However, when all the
trays were weighed it was obvious the stores' definition of
portions varied. Total tray weights ranged from 4 pounds, 6 ounces
to 7 pounds, 8 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   We ordered the party trays anonymously a day in advance and
weighed them on a postal scale. We scrutinized them and tasted
them.
</P>
<P>
   Our conclusion: You get what you pay for.
</P>
<P>
   The party tray from DiSalvo's Deli &AMP; Italian Store offered the
best quality, with generous servings of top-grade meats and the
bonus of a mound of house-marinated imported olives tucked inside a
border of marinated tomatoes. The cheeses were arranged on a
separate tray. This party tray also was the most expensive, at
$4.50 per person, or $54 for a tray to serve 12. That price may be
deceptive since DiSalvo's meat and cheese trays weighed in at 7 1/2
pounds, considerably more than all the others _ and obviously able
to feed more guests. The ham and the roast beef, cooked to a
blushing medium, won high marks from tasters.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the budget-priced trays included lower-quality
meat.
</P>
<P>
   Of the lower-priced trays, one from Cub was a good value. The
quality of some of the meats and the amount (the platter weighed 5
pounds, 10 ounces) made the $24.99 price attractive. The only
drawback is that the meat and cheese were piled high on a small
platter, making it difficult to extract a single piece.
</P>
<P>
   One tip: Before you decide, ask questions about the products
used and be specific when you order. What's billed as ``turkey
breast'' may turn out to be either real turkey breast meat or
processed turkey slices. The ham may be sweet or it may be smoked.
Or it may be chopped and reformed into something resembling a ham.
Roast beef and corned beef are risky to order unless you are paying
top dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Below is an assessment of the six trays. Compare these prices
with stores in your own area.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  DiSalvo's Deli and Italian Store: Meat and cheese deli tray,
arranged on separate trays, with a choice of three Boar's Head
meats and two cheeses. $4.50 per person, $54 for 12. The combined
trays weighed 7 1/2 pounds. Added attractions: The meats and cheese
arranged on separate platters are ideal for vegetarians. Imported
olives, marinated with rosemary, are a bonus, as is a border of
marinated sliced tomatoes. The customer picks the assortment and
can opt, as an example, for house-marinated and roasted beef. There
is an extra fee for imported meats such as prosciutto.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dorothy Lane Market: $4 per person, $48 for 12. Weighed 5
pounds. Boar's Head ham, roast beef, turkey breast, corned beef and
Swiss and colby cheeses, garnished with three cherry tomatoes. The
meats are folded into individual cornets, making for an attractive
presentation _ marred by a huge lettuce leaf plopped on top with
the three cherry tomatoes. Moist turkey and roast beef are
appealing, but the ham was quite sweet. Boar's Head has other ham
options, so it's important to specify which one you want.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cub: ``Meat and Cheese Splendor,'' $24.99 to serve 10 to 14.
Weighed 5 pounds, 10 ounces. Includes real turkey breast, ham and
hard salami, as well as a tasteless roast beef and corned beef.
Swiss and American cheese round out the assortment. It is piled
high on a 12-inch platter, too small to be user-friendly. Garnished
with cherry tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Meijer: ``Meat and Cheese Buffet,'' $18.95, serves eight to
10. Weighed 4 pounds, 6 ounces. Includes roast beef, ham, turkey
and corned beef, with Swiss and American cheese. Piled high on a
small platter. Garnished with a mound of sweet pickles and bottled
pimiento olives. The turkey is processed, the squares of chopped
ham tasteless and the slippery beef was rubbery and salty. The
corned beef, surprisingly, had an appealing flavor.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chmiel's: ``Meat and Cheese Platter,'' $2.40 per person;
$28.80 for 12. Weighed 4 pounds, 6 ounces, spread out on a 16-inch
platter, garnished only with a tomato rose and two leaves. This
platter included tasteless beef, boiled ham, processed turkey,
Swiss and hot pepper cheese. Corned beef and salami, colby and
provolone were other choices.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kroger: ``Crowd Pleaser,'' $23.95, serves 10 to 14. Weighed 6
pounds. Assortment of luncheon meets and cheeses, including pickle
and pimento loaf, chopped ham, chicken breast, salami, American,
hot pepper and Muenster cheese. This is the heavyweight of the
modestly priced trays, but these are budget deli meats. Even the
chicken breast (not turkey) fell into shreds.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
