r e BC-DINO-TRAILER02-COX     12-01 0406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINO-TRAILER02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Silence speaks volumes as Disney hypes `Dinosaur'
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If your trek to see ``Toy Story 2'' follows the path of many
other moviegoers, you're apt to hear a wee voice in the audience
ask, ``Hey, Mom, where's Woody?''
</P>
<P>
   That's because one of the longest promos in movie history _ the
roughly 4.5-minute teaser for Disney's monster-size computer
animated film ``Dinosaur'' _ is playing prior to showings of the
record-setting box-office hit ``Toy Story 2.''
</P>
<P>
   The long promo for ``Dinosaur,'' scheduled to debut in May, is a
wordless visual eye-opener with realistic-looking computer animated
dinos strutting their stuff on Earth during the Mesozoic period.
</P>
<P>
   ``That trailer's pretty cool,'' said Lew Breeding, 47, of Sandy
Springs, who saw ``Toy Story 2'' over the weekend. ``It kept going
on and on and on. The scene that blew me away had you following
this pterodactyl, and then it flies over this mesa and here were
all these herds of dinosaurs. It was spectacular.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney executives declined to talk about the film's preview. But
long promos have precedent at Disney: Five years ago, the studio
showed a three-minute, 58 second teaser to ``The Lion King''
featuring Elton John's song ``The Circle of Life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because they really do have a captive audience and it's little
kids, they want to work that to death,'' says Michael Schau, editor
of New York's Entertainment Marketing Letter. ``While people were
assuming they were coming into the middle of a 10-minute cartoon,
all it was saying was, `Watch for us in May.'''
</P>
<P>
   Schau said most movie trailers last about 2.5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the kids watching are 5, 6, 7 or 8, but they will be
fascinated,'' he said. ``Disney is just a primo marketer. It seems
like if they do it, they can get by with it.''
</P>
<P>
   And the ``Dinosaur'' trailer's lack of a voiced message?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's more a trend in overall advertising,'' Schau said.
``It's more about the form, lifestyle or look of something.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the ``Dinosaur'' trailer, the movie will have spoken
words from well-known actors voicing the dinos. Among them: Alfre
Woodard, Ossie Davis, D.B. Sweeney, Julianna Margulies, Joan
Plowright and Della Reese.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
