<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6025 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-RADIO-JOYNER02-COX     12-01 2084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIO-JOYNER02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waking and shaking up America
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ By 7 a.m. the parking lot is packed, the politicians
are in place and volunteers are neatly stacking voter registration
cards in the Atlanta Civic Center lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Onstage, a self-styled activist named Tom Joyner is clutching a
microphone and explaining the importance of affirmative action and
the need for greater economic empowerment to an all-black audience.
</P>
<P>
   It's pretty heady stuff. That is until Joyner flips the script
and tells his DJ to cue up the Commodores' funky ode to
well-endowed women.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a brick . . . HOOOOOUSE ,'' booms from the Civic
Center's house speakers, as Joyner and about 1,000 people who have
answered his wake-up call begin lip-syncing and swinging their hips
to the old-school classic. ``She's mighty, mighty. She's letting it
all hang out.''
</P>
<P>
   Five days a week on KISS 104, ``The Tom Joyner Morning Show'' is
where thousands of Atlanta radio listeners let it all hang out with
a broadcasting icon who is giving the term ``political party'' a
whole different meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Joyner, whose nationally distributed broadcast is based in
Dallas except during frequent ``sky shows'', does much more than
spin records and crack jokes. In the last several years Joyner and
his co-stars have racked up a series of successful boycotts against
companies targeted for their treatment of black consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Joyner has also positioned himself as a potential kingmaker in
African-American political circles. He claims more than 7 million
weekly listeners, including about 225,000 in metro Atlanta. And
while his ratings lag behind younger-skewing Frank Ski at V-103 in
the ``urban contemporary'' market, Joyner is pied piper among
middle-class, middle-age, middle-of-the-road listeners who are most
likely to vote.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, Vice President Al Gore, former South African
President Nelson Mandela, NAACP President Kweisi Mfume, and the
Rev. Jesse Jackson have been guests on the show. During his Atlanta
visit, Joyner shared the stage with Mayor Bill Campbell, city
Councilman Michael Bond and state Rep. Vernon Jones. More than 200
people signed voter-registration cards.
</P>
<P>
   `` `The Tom Joyner Show' is the single most important mass media
connection to the African-American community,'' Jones tells a
reporter backstage. ``When we're trying to get the word out about
anything, this is one of the best ways to do it. If you're
mentioned on `Tom Joyner Morning Show,' it's a tremendous boost to
your candidacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyner has been wooing listeners with a mix of '70s-era funk
standards, unabashed political advocacy, and broad humor told by
on-air cohorts, including comedians J. Anthony Brown, George
Wallace, Myra J and an outrageous psychic called Miss Dupree.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm doing is what good black radio has always done,''
Joyner says after polishing off a couple of butter crunch cookies
backstage. ``When we were growing up, the disc jockey was
entertaining you, but he was also telling you what was going on in
the community. Back in the civil rights era, that's how we were
getting the message out.''
</P>
<P>
   But during the early '80s, Joyner says, pro-social messages got
lost, as the ``more music, less talk'' format swept the radio
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of activism left black radio,'' Joyner says.
``I'm just trying to bring it back. I have to, because that's how I
was raised.''
</P>
<P>
   While ``The Morning Show'' still plays its share of mindlessly
funky hits by groups such as the Bar-Kays, Zapp and Sister Sledge,
a typical broadcast is leavened with issues-oriented commentaries
by BET talk show host Tavis Smiley, who often teams up with Joyner
to rally listeners around a cause.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting for a cause is what brought Joyner to radio in the
first place. He grew up in Tuskegee, Ala., and graduated in 1968
from Tuskegee Institute, a historically black university. After
college, Joyner got involved in a local movement that changed his
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every weekend there wasn't a lot to do in Tuskegee except go
to protest marches,'' Joyner recalls. ``One day we marched because
the radio station wasn't playing enough black music. We were in an
all-black town, and they played all-white music. The station
manager agreed and said, `Who wants to do a show on Saturday?' I
raised my hand, and that's how I got in the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyner has worked nonstop in radio ever since, at stations in
Montgomery, Memphis and St. Louis. In the mid-'80s, while he was a
morning drive-time jock at KKDA-FM in Dallas, he got a lucrative
offer to do an afternoon show. But there was a catch: The new job
was 900 miles away in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of quitting his gig in Dallas, Joyner commuted every day
by plane between the two cities, earning him the nickname ``The Fly
Jock.'' The name stuck, although the slang definition of the term
``fly'' _ to be cool _ doesn't seem to suit him at first glance.
</P>
<P>
   In person Joyner wears fashionably draped clothes that hide a
modest middle-age paunch, and at times he speaks in a low burble
that makes him seem shy. But if he's trying to prove a point or
make a joke, his voice quickens and his eyes flash with the
mischievous glint of a teenager who's been joy riding in Dad's new
Buick.
</P>
<P>
   His infectious on-air personality and growing listenership
caught the attention of the ABC Radio Networks, which syndicated
his show in 1994. Still based in Dallas, the show is heard in 99
markets and has become a national bully pulpit to influence
institutions Joyner believes have treated blacks unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his earliest major campaigns, Joyner organized an
on-air protest against Christie's auction house in New York in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were going to auction off some slave memorabilia, as if
slavery is memorable,'' Joyner remembers with a wry smile. ``I
heard they had this policy of not auctioning off anything from the
Holocaust, and I felt that wasn't right because slavery was a
holocaust too.'' Listeners deluged the upper-crust auction house
with calls, convincing Christie's and the consignor to donate the
items to a museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made us aware of how certain groups looked at this,'' says
Christie's spokeswoman Vredy Lytsman. ``It was better this way, and
everybody was happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Another victory came in 1998 when Joyner exposed an internal
memo circulated at the New York ad-buying firm Katz Media Group,
which advised its clients not to advertise on minority-owned radio
stations because they should be looking for ``prospects, not
suspects.'' Katz Radio President Stu Olds eventually apologized for
the memo on Joyner's show and promised to personally solicit
companies to advertise on black stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pick the fights we think we can win. We don't ever want to
lose,'' Joyner says. ``Every time we do one and we win, it further
empowers people to think they can make a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyner's latest coup was perhaps his biggest, but also his
messiest.
</P>
<P>
   In October Joyner set his crosshairs on CompUSA, a national
computer retailer he criticized for failing to advertise in black
media outlets. He urged his listeners to call, write and e-mail the
company to complain. Later he told fans to send in receipts to
prove they had purchased merchandise from
</P>
<P>
   CompUSA stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``This went on for two weeks, and I got no response from them,''
Joyner said. ``Then one day I got this fax on CompUSA's letterhead
and it was a nasty memo about black people, and I said `Dang, this
ain't cool.' '' Incensed, Joyner read the fax on the air. After
being contacted by a reporter, Joyner found out the memo was bogus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked legit to me, but nobody checked it,'' he said. ``It
pointed out a vulnerability in our way of doing things. It was a
cheap shot and I was blindsided.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyner also apologized after learning his claim that the company
had no black board members was incorrect.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he continued the protest. ABC threatened to take him off the
air, claiming fear of a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was scary. They said they were going to unplug the show,''
Joyner said. ``I told them I was coming to work. It was a
showdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyner went on the air that day, and so did the CompUSA protest.
After 10 weeks, company President James F. Halpin met with Joyner
and Smiley in Dallas. Halpin later appeared on Joyner's show, where
he agreed to hire a black advertising agency and offered a 10
percent discount to listeners who mailed in store receipts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our actions were absolutely influenced by the campaign,''
acknowledged Suzanne Shelton, CompUSA's director of public affairs.
``Besides, we like all our customers and thought it was the right
thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Lobbying for more business for black media might seem
self-serving, but Jeff Axelrod, assistant managing editor for trade
paper Records &AMP; Radio, says Joyner's campaigns are legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stations with minority formats have not gotten the same share
of ad dollars as white stations,'' Axelrod says. ``When he raises
awareness about this issue, he may benefit indirectly, but he's
also making things better for thousands of radio employees across
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Some fans say it's that kind of take-no-prisoners integrity that
has made Joyner a bona fide leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``He keeps me informed about what's going on in America, and I
know I can trust him,'' said Lorine Singleton Hall, a 32-year-old
Decatur real estate agent. ``He has so much power in the community,
but he's still so down to earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall got more than a daily dose of information at the Civic
Center show. She also won a pair of round-trip airline tickets for
dancing to ``Shake Your Rump to the Funk.''
</P>
<P>
   William Boone, a professor of political science at Clark Atlanta
University, doesn't do much rump-shaking these days, and he didn't
attend the Atlanta show. But he tunes in sometimes on his way to
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom Joyner has been able to hit a certain group of black baby
boomers who are not tuned in to traditional black leaders, and I
think he's done that by mixing the serious and the non-serious,''
Boone says. ``I guess there is a concern that the serious message
will get clouded or glossed over, but to get that message across
you have to talk to people where they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyner says his duty is to keep white companies on their toes
when it comes to his on-air constituency. But what about
black-owned companies and politicians?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't criticize them,'' Joyner says squarely. ``Any
problem I have with a black person, I deal with personally. We need
to settle whatever problems we have with each other behind closed
doors and come out united.''
</P>
<P>
   Boone sees an inherent risk in that approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a problem with not being self-critical,'' he
says. ``You run the risk of portraying everything black as good and
everything white as bad, which allows you to be exploited by your
own people. Even in the interest of solidarity, you can still be
self-critical.''
</P>
<P>
   But other longtime listeners don't seem to mind. Ronnie
Crawford, 32, of Buckhead says there are few entertainers like
Joyner who are willing to put their careers and their reputations
on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to show him support and show him that we have his
back,'' said Crawford, a management specialist for cemeteries and
funeral homes. ``If we don't support him, black people will lose
out as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Joyner has been devoting more of his time to a pet
project: an eponymous, nonprofit foundation that raises money for
black colleges and universities. Run by his sons, Thomas Jr. and
Oscar, the Tom Joyner Foundation hopes to raise more than $1
million next year.
</P>
<P>
   Joyner said he plans on continuing his radio crusades, although
nobody is raising his dander at the moment. For now he's talking up
the 2000 Census, urging listeners to be counted, and trying to
raise awareness about the upcoming presidential election. Who
knows, maybe he'll invite the candidates for an on-air debate and
an electric slide contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at you, if you can entertain you can influence
people. If you can influence them, you can empower them. If we were
all serious, people would tune us out. If I throw a party every day
and get them laughing, I can tell them something important.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
