r d BC-TRAY-SAFE02-COX     12-01 0174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAY-SAFE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More about party trays
 &HT;    (EDS: SIDEBAR to PARTY-TRAYS02-COX.)
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You don't want to hear this, but the rules of food safety apply
to party trays, too.
</P>
<P>
   That means that the food on the party tray _ the meats, cheeses
and dips _ should not stand at room temperature more than two
hours. After that, the food should be pitched because it's been in
the danger zone when bacteria breed for too long.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that some of those meats may be laced with
preservatives doesn't protect them. The bacteria may have been on
the meat slicer or the employee's hands.
</P>
<P>
   If pitching food sounds wasteful, plan ahead and hold some food
back. Refill the tray or have a spare tray already made up to take
to the table after two hours. If possible, position the party tray
on a bed of ice for extended shelf life.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
