<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6027 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-WINE-COLUMN02-COX     12-01 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Around the world with knockout reds
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a hot-air balloon, you can go around the world in 80 days _
if you're Rex Harrison, and you've got money to burn.
</P>
<P>
   At your local wine shop, you can go around the world in 80
seconds, and it won't cost you anywhere near as much.
</P>
<P>
   Now that winter-like temperatures have finally arrived, let's
use red wines to take that worldwide trip. Reds just seem to taste
better when you can see your breath outside. Or inside, depending
on your home ventilation system.
</P>
<P>
   Let's focus on a handful of wines that are fairly widely
available.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1998 Rosemount Estate Shiraz (Diamond Label) from Australia,
$10.99-$11.99: This is a relatively one-dimensional wine, but wow,
what a dimension! There is amazing concentration of fruit, to the
point that even the bubbles that form alongside the glass after a
robust pour appear Welch's-purple. Shiraz is the Australian term
for the syrah grape of France and California, grown in warmer
climates and producing rich, sturdy dry reds. This Australian red
has been remarkably consistent over the years, but the '98 packs a
little more oomph than usual. If you're a fan of rich, red
zinfandels but balk at the rising price of zins, check out this and
other shiraz-based wines from Down Under.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1995 Veramonte Cabernet Sauvignon from Chile, $7.99-$9.99: I
haven't tried newer vintages of this wine, but the '95 is a
knockout. A totally different wine from the Shiraz, this dry red
offers complexity in both the aromas and flavors _ a lot of
different things going on in the glass that add up to more than the
sum of its parts. The nose is almost Bordeaux-like, with hints of
cedar, and the wine wears its few years of age very well.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Marietta Old Vine Lot 24 from California, $14.99: Marietta has
made a name for itself as a winery that packs great value into
every bottle, and this nonvintage offering from a field blend of
several types of red-wine grapes (zinfandel, petite sirah,
carignanne, gamay) is no exception. Sturdy, with lots of backbone,
this newest release would drink well now with a hearty meal, but
could also improve with a couple of years of additional aging. If
you're lucky, you might find a few bottles of the Lot 23 around,
perhaps for $12.99, and it's every bit as good as the Lot 24.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1999 Georges Duboeuf Beaujolais Nouveau, from France, $9.69:
We mentioned this last week before tasting it, and were pleasantly
surprised. All of this year's nouveau wines from the Beaujolais
region are a cut above the nouveaus of the last few years, and
that's a welcome development, because interest in the
third-Thursday-in-November release of the just-fermented Gamay
grape juice seems to be on the wane. Duboeuf's version appears to
be the most widely available French nouveau and is at or near the
top of this year's crop, of which there are several. The wine is
fresh and grapy, but has a little more backbone than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Shew! Four continents, evenly split between the Northern and
Southern hemispheres, for what, $40 and change? Now if only we
could rack up frequent-flyer miles this way.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fisher writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: markfisher(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-99 1121EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
