<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Thursday, December
2, 1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors can focus on one day's budget, CoxNet
produces themed features budgets each day. Here is the schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive, personal finance and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   Thursday for Friday: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion and science &AMP; health
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   THE LAYOUT'S DONE FOR YOU: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are
available for purchase in paginated form:
http://nytsyn.com/syndicate/pageex
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   TECH-FUNJOB _ Bonnie Bertram is a professional web surfer for
eTour.com. We'll profile Bertrum and find out just how this
professional does a job that seems like fun and games. (MMallory,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-CHICKEN _ A profile of the Chicken People for the biotech
package. Lured from San Jose to beautiful Athens, Ga., this company
is bio-engineering chickens to produce eggs with more protein.
(Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BIOTECH _ The terms biotech and biomed cover a lot of ground; a
look at some of the cutting-edge ways in which metro Atlanta
companies are using the life sciences. (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 40.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-REINDEER _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ So there's no
miniature sleigh with eight tiny reindeer. And no little old
driver, so lively and quick. Hey, this is South Florida. You get
two reindeer, not so tiny, and be happy about it. The Palm Beach
Zoo at Dreher Park is doing you and your kids a favor. Your
tropical-born offspring have never seen genuine antler-growing,
lichen-eating, sleigh-pulling reindeer? Meet Chelsea and her
8-month-old calf, Mistletoe. (Dasher, Dancer, et al. were otherwise
engaged). On the weekend, have your picture taken with Chelsea. $6.
BYOS (Bring Your Own Santa). ``Reindeer only come through here once
a year, usually at night,'' explained zoo curator Dave Wood
scientifically. With reindeer fact box at bottom of file.
(O'Meilia, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS-QUESTIONS _ Q&AMP;A on the news, in two takes. (Bessonnette,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (EDS: Moving on l (Lifestyle) and a
(General News) categories.) MOVED IN TWO TAKES.
</P>
<P>
   BUYER'S-EDGE _ How to put together six holiday looks for under
$150. (AHill, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING-GUIDE _ A weekly feature telling how to locate
hard-to-fnd items. This week: Halco light bulbs, Nantucket Nectar
and Stewart's Key Lime Soda. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING-DESTINATION _ A weekly feature about fun places to shop
in the Southeast. This week: Things made by hand fill the shops in
charming Dillsboro, N.C., which still evokes a 19th-century
ambience. (Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-RECIPESWAP _ A weekly recipe exchange column. This week:
Cranberry-Caramel bars. (Langhenry, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-INSEASON _ A weekly column featuring recipes for seasonal
produce. This week: Clementines with recipe for Spinach and
Clementines. (Hizer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution freelancer; not
for use by New York Times clients.)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-VERSATILEVEGETARIAN _ A weekly column featuring vegetarian
recipes. This week: Vegetable plates. (Hizer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution freelancer; not for use by New York Times
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-CYBERSPICE _ A weekly column looking at the plethora of
recipes on the Internet. (Parham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN _ Michael Skube's beer column will not be
available this week.
</P>
<P>
   PARTY-TRAYS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ It's party season. Make that party
tray season, when office managers and party hosts order a
time-saving platter of meats and cheeses for holiday celebrations.
Every supermarket offers them. We wondered about differences in
price and quality. The natural question is which is the best, or at
least the best value. So we ordered six trays from five
supermarkets and a deli. A comparative price/ingredients box at
bottom of file. (Heller, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TRAY-SAFE _ How to serve the freshest party tray possible.
(Heller, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-COLUMN _ In a hot-air balloon, you can go around the world
in 80 days _ if you're Rex Harrison, and you've got money to burn.
At your local wine shop, you can go around the world in 80 seconds,
and it won't cost you anywhere near as much. Now that winter-like
temperatures have finally arrived, let's use red wines to take that
worldwide trip. Reds just seem to taste better when you can see
your breath outside. Or inside, depending on your home ventilation
system. (Fisher, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   DINO-TRAILER _ A quick explainer on ``Dinosaur,'' the long
trailer being shown before ``Toy Story 2.'' It's a dinosaur movie
coming from Disney in May with state-of-the-art computer depictions
of the Mesosoic period. (BLongino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
9.
</P>
<P>
   RADIO-JOYNER _ Tom Joyner is already one of the most popular
syndicated radio personalities in the nation with a wild-and-crazy
morning show that offers ribald humor, soap opera spoofs, and 70's
era funk music. But Joyner has also become a potent political and
economic force who has led several successful boycotts against
white companies he felt discriminated against black consumers.
Recently Joyner won concessions from CompUSA which has since
promised to buy more ads in black media. And because of his
popularity and influence, Joyner is shaping up as a kingmaker who
rubs shoulders with President Clinton, as well as a host of local
black Atlanta pols who view his show as an important political pit
stop. (Harris, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 52. WITH PHOTOS.
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-WEST _ Video of the week: ``Wild Wild West.'' (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-SPOTLIGHT _ Spotlight on Will Smith. (Murray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-MINIS _ Minireviews of recent videos, including ``William
Shakespeare's A Midsummer Night's Dream.'' (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-NEXT _ Coming soon: ``Deep Blue Sea,'' ``Inspector
Gadget,'' ``Trippin','' ``The School of Flesh.'' (Murray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AUDIO-KORN _ Review, of new Korn album, ``Issues.'' Grade: B
(Dollar, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AUDIO-QTIP _ Review of new album by Q-Tip, ``Amplified.'' Grade:
C (SoMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AUDIO-MINIS _ Mini-reviews of Alanis Morissette's ``MTV
Unplugged'' (Grade: B-); NAS' ``Nastradamous'' (Grade: B+) and
``Broadway's Leading Ladies'' (Grade: C+). (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET-WRESTLING PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: The weekly CoxNet wrestling page is now available. Keying
to the Monday wrestling events, It's good for publication any day
through Sunday. Here are the elements on the page, which are also
moving on the entertainment wire:
</P>
<P>
   WRESTLING-TOYS _ Step into the aisles of wrestling toys in local
stores and the lights seem to go just a bit dimmer. That's because
you're surrounded by black. You're surrounded by the glaring,
sinister faces of wrestling figures dressed as fiends. Psychotic
murderers. Death's heads. They reach out with hands that are too
big for their bodies, the better to strangle opponents. They even
snarl at you when you press their buttons. ``You cannot kill what
is already dead!'' bellows one World Wrestling Federation star in a
toy known as Wall Talker. Many of these toys are directly modeled
on shows that are rated TV-14 for violence and sexual innuendo. Yet
nearly all, including Wall Talker, are labeled ``for ages 4 and
up.'' (Hulbert, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WRESTLING_TOYBOX _ Is this toy good for your preschooler.
(Hulbert, Cox Ndews Service)
</P>
<P>
   WRESTLING-GRAPEVINE _ News and notes from the wrestling
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
