<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Call the insurance company, my
husband would say from time to time, after my wedding band walked
away from the nightstand one night. Jim thinks that a missing
object should be declared forever lost within, say, five seconds of
its disappearance. I take a much more hopeful view, preferring to
wait at least five years. This is not because I am the perennial
optimist of the pair. The difference is that I grew up with St.
Anthony, and Jim did not. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Up to 98,000 Americans are
killed each year due to medical errors in hospitals alone. That
number (more than double annual highway fatalities) does not count
all the other Americans who die due to medical errors committed
outside U.S. hospitals. American patients killed each year due to
medical errors likely is double the number of Americans killed in
the nine-year Vietnam War. Many more Americans are killed in
hospitals than in highway accidents. Try to ignore that fact.
(Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ I've finally figured out the
mystery of the personal, lengthy and, yes, often dull family
Christmas newsletters I've been getting by e-mail from Dan
Eggleston. Because of the wonders of e-mail, I've been receiving
old holiday newsletters from Eggleston for -- few months or so. But
until Saturday, when I messaged him back by e-mail to ask him about
these holiday newsletters, I didn't know who Eggleston is. Isn't
e-mail great? (Kelso, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
