<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6071 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MURRAY-COLUMN02-COX     12-01 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES:
 &HT;    Seventh in a series
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AIX-EN-PROVENCE, France _ Here I am in a town called Aix, as in
``X'' marks the spot, at a hotel named Le Pigonnet, as in ``Voila!
Here comes another of zee fat pigeons for us to pluck.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now I'm at the hotel bar, nursing a glass of the local
wine and trying to make friends, which is not so easy where there's
hardly any English spoken.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, my wife is in our room, nursing a headache, most
likely lying down with a cold washcloth on her forehead and the
drapes closed. Most definitely, the drapes are closed
</P>
<P>
   The room, on the third floor, looks out through French doors and
over a small balcony to a garden below. There are no rooms directly
across from ours. But if someone in the adjacent wing were to lean
out far enough ...
</P>
<P>
   Which was exactly what happened, my wife said, while I was in
the bathroom and she was reclining on the bed.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that she looked up just in time to see a gentleman of
Japanese appearance hanging from his hotel window and snapping away
with a camera focused in her direction.
</P>
<P>
   C'est ah so.
</P>
<P>
   So it was, all by myself, that I was sampling the Coteaux
d'Aix-en-Provence, what is considered the ``aco'' wine in the Cote
de Provence region. A-OK by me, as far as it goes. That's the
trouble with wine. It takes it awhile to get you where you're
going.
</P>
<P>
   Not so for the fellow standing a few steps down the bar from me,
sipping Scotch and soda, no ice. Hollywood handsome, he was, almost
to the point of being pretty. Picture James Bond's sissy younger
brother. It didn't help that he was wearing an ascot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where you from?'' I asked, friendly like.
</P>
<P>
   ``England,'' he replied, studious of his glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``What part?'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``South,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I became intent on securing something more than an answer of a
single word. After all, that's my business - getting people to
talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from Texas,'' I allowed, hooking a thumb in my belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bravo,'' he allowed, still not looking up.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Cooper never said ``Yep'' with more finality.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't help wondering, but refrained from asking, how'd he
like to try to finish his drink with that ascot shoved down his
throat.
</P>
<P>
   But why bother? It was a lovely evening in a lovely place, a
city of much history and great beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Aix, tourists are told, was founded as Aquae Sextiae in 112 BC
by the Roman conqueror Sextius Calvinius. In 45 BC, Caesar declared
Aix a colony. Thermal baths were developed around 15 BC from local
hot springs.
</P>
<P>
   But skipping ahead, in 1838 the painter Paul Cezanne was born in
Aix. Le Pigonnet was his country house, later converted to a hotel
and has been operated by the same family since 1924.
</P>
<P>
   Aix today boasts a population of some 150,000. Thanks to the
local university, young people fill the sidewalk restaurants and
book shops along tree-lined streets. Always, it seems, there is a
public fountain just around the next corner:
</P>
<P>
   The great fountain (1860) at La Rotonde in the Place General de
Gaulle ... the Fountain of 9 Cannons (1691) halfway up the Cours
Mirabeau avenue ... the Fontaine des Quatre Dauphins (1667) in the
Mazarin district.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, Aix! A lovely place, a lovely evening. Indeed, why bother?
</P>
<P>
   Because! That's why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't suppose you have any tequila hid back there?'' I asked
the young bartender.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may be in luck, monsieur,'' he said. Sure enough, reaching
back among the lower shelves, he produced a half-filled bottle.
``We don't sell much of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK,'' I said. ``I don't drink much of it.''
</P>
<P>
   I had him pour a straight shot and then, per my instructions,
was provided with salt and a lime wedge.
</P>
<P>
   I hoisted the glass high, without so much as a glance toward the
Englishman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's to Lafayette, Woodrow Wilson and Franklin Delano
Roosevelt!'' I proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after barely managing to down it without choking, I added,
halfway under my breath for whoever might care to hear:
</P>
<P>
   ``Le bravo.''
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. Mailing address is PO Box
151108; email, jmurray(AT)lcc.net)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
