<HEADLINE>
INTERNET LAW EXPERT RETURNS TO ANTITRUST CASE  
LEARNING TO LIVE WITH YEAR 2000 CONCERNS  
A SCHWAB MANAGER REVIEWS `Y2K: THE MOVIE' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's back.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Lessig, a 38-year-old Harvard professor and Internet
law expert, has been recruited for the Microsoft antitrust case
once again. When U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson
prodded the two sides toward settlement talks and appointed a
mediator on Nov. 18, he also said he wanted Lessig to write a
friend-of-the-court brief on his behalf on the issue of
technological tying.
</P>
<P>
   Lessig was removed from the case last year, after serving three
months as a special master _ an outside expert with a broad
mandate. Microsoft had protested, saying Lessig had a ``clear
bias'' against the company. Without addressing the bias claim, an
appeals court removed Lessig, ruling that the case was not an
appropriate one for a special master. This time, Microsoft has not
yet said whether it will object to Lessig.
</P>
<P>
   Reached last week in Berlin, where he has a research fellowship,
Lessig said he was eager to weigh in on the subject of so-called
product tying, which he called ``the toughest issue in the case.''
Jackson asked him to write a 50-page paper on it.
</P>
<P>
   The government has accused Microsoft of tying its Internet
browser to its monopoly product, the Windows operating system, in
an illegal tactic to stifle competition. In his findings of fact on
Nov. 5, Jackson echoed the government's accusation.
</P>
<P>
   But antitrust experts say the tying issue could be vulnerable on
appeal, and that an appeals court in a related case last year said
Microsoft should be free to fold browsing software into Windows if
there was a ``plausible claim'' of consumer benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Lessig isn't saying, but antitrust experts expect him to make
the intellectual case for taking software tying seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Code is law'' is the Lessig refrain. In his new book, ``Code
and Other Laws of Cyberspace'' (Basic Books), he suggests that the
technological architecture of software is an appropriate subject
for government scrutiny, though traditional regulation would be
misguided. ``My argument is not for some top-down form of
control,'' he writes. ``My claim is not that regulators should
occupy Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   Lessig's views are difficult to dismiss as simply
anti-Microsoft. He gives more weight to the competition Microsoft
faces, for example, than did Jackson, who found that the Linux
operating system was a fringe technology and not likely to
challenge Microsoft anytime soon. ``By 1998,'' Lessig writes, ``it
had become apparent to all that Linux was an important competitor
to the Microsoft operating system.''
</P>
<P>
   _ STEVE LOHR &QR;
</P>
<P>
   LEARNING TO LIVE WITH YEAR 2000 CONCERNS
</P>
<P>
   Managers and technical experts working on year 2000 computing
projects are becoming increasingly optimistic, despite delays and
program weaknesses that ought to worry them, according to an
informal coalition of year 2000 analysts who have polled such
professionals in June, September and again this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y2K experts remain remarkably optimistic even though many of
them report they are not yet completely ready,'' said Edward
Yardeni, the Deutsche Bank economist who has predicted that year
2000 computer disruptions are likely to lead to a worldwide
recession next year.
</P>
<P>
   The latest poll results, which will be released today, show the
number expecting glitches in their own critical systems edging down
to 33 percent from 34 percent in September.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 66 percent are confident the power will stay on, up
from 61 percent in September, and 64 percent expect no problems
with phones, up from 59 percent in September.
</P>
<P>
   On the personal front, the more than 1,200 respondents are
slightly less inclined to stock up on food and cash than in
previous polls. And those who are doing so will put aside less than
they had planned in September or June.
</P>
<P>
   But such feelings are a triumph of ``hope and trust'' over
facts, according to Yardeni, who developed the poll with Gary
Beach, publisher of CIO magazine, and the Information Systems Audit
and Control Association, a trade group for professionals working on
quality control in the computer world.
</P>
<P>
   The pollsters said the disquieting responses included the 57
percent saying they were still working on year 2000 problems. In
the September poll, only 43 percent had expected to still be
trouble-shooting by now. And in this most recent poll, only 31
percent were far enough along to have actually tested contingency
plans.
</P>
<P>
   The pollsters also noted that many repair projects had not been
independently tested and that respondents had relied heavily on
unverified assurances of readiness from suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   The poll responses were gathered from Nov. 10-21. The results
are posted at www.peoplepolls.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ BARNABY J. FEDER &QR;
</P>
<P>
   A SCHWAB MANAGER REVIEWS `Y2K: THE MOVIE'
</P>
<P>
   You had to be generously willing to suspend disbelief to accept
the plot of ``Y2K: The Movie,'' the recent NBC thriller in which
computing's millennium bug leads to industrial apocalypse and
triggers a nuclear meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   But last Monday, the day after the movie aired, a manager at
Charles Schwab&AMP; Co. rushed to calm the gullible.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail memo that day to some 140 employees, Kathy
Childers, a manager involved with Schwab's year 2000 preparedness
effort, assured employees the year 2000 movie ``would not be the
typical scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Although no one knows exactly what will happen, I would like
to set your mind at rest that everything has been done to make
certain that the scenario you saw Sunday will NOT happen,'' Ms.
Childers wrote in her memo.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, the note elicited a few derisive snorts from
the tech-savvy employees at San Francisco-based Charles Schwab, who
said they hadn't necessarily been hunkering down with canned goods
and armaments in anticipation of industrial Armageddon on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Gable, a Schwab spokesman, said that, however Ms. Childers'
warning may have been perceived, she had intended it to have a
tongue-in-cheek tone _ even if the note did go on to discuss some
of the serious efforts Schwab has made to cope with year 2000
issues, like making contingency computer plans.
</P>
<P>
   The message invited employees of Schwab to Ms. Childers' office
to learn more.
</P>
<P>
   It then concluded, ``I would venture to say that if you are
prepared for an earthquake, then you are prepared for Y2K.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be small solace, of course, for anyone who has ever
seen the devastation nature wreaked on Los Angeles in the movie
``Earthquake.''
</P>
<P>
   _ MATT RICHTEL &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-28-99 1803EST &QL;
</P>
