<HEADLINE>
WEB SITES AND RECORDING LABELS AT IMPASSE ON FEES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A growing number of Web sites are offering customized music
programming _ song sets created in response to the personal tastes
of listeners. What the listeners are not hearing is a
behind-the-scenes dispute between the sites and major record
labels, in which tens of millions of dollars may be at stake.
</P>
<P>
   The basic issue is how much these Web sites should reimburse
record labels each time they play recordings owned by the labels.
Months of discussions between trade groups representing the two
sides recently petered out, so the issue is set for arbitration
next year. Meanwhile, some Webcasters have been negotiating
individual royalty licenses with the recording industry.
</P>
<P>
   Because the sites are permitted to continue playing music until
arbitration is completed, the issue may seem insignificant to the
growing number of Internet listeners. But the question may not be
so insignificant to investors in the Web sites, which include
Launch Media, NetRadio, SonicNet (owned by Viacom's MTV) and
Spinner.com (owned by America Online). The royalty fees paid to the
record industry ultimately could become a substantial business
expense.
</P>
<P>
   The stage for the royalty dispute was set in late 1998, when
Congress passed and President Clinton signed the Digital Millennium
Copyright Act. Like broadcast radio stations, Webcasters are
required to pay licensing fees to copyright owners through Ascap or
BMI, which collect royalties. But on the assumption that digital
distribution raises additional intellectual property issues because
it allows for high-quality copying, the new law requires Webcasters
to pay a licensing fee to record labels that is not required of
broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   The law did not set a rate for royalty payments by the Internet
companies but did provide for arbitration if the two sides could
not reach an agreement. Trade groups for both sides say the
negotiations, which began early this year, never went much beyond
exploratory talks.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the two sides are scheduled to file position papers next
month with a three-person arbitration panel to be appointed by the
U.S. Copyright Office. A request by the recording industry for a
deadline extension, filed last week, is still pending.
</P>
<P>
   People involved in the discussions between individual Web sites
and record companies have said the royalty percentages being asked
by the labels range as high as 15 percent of a site's gross
revenues. Lobbyists for the Web sites say they are arguing for as
low as 1 to 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There are also open questions about how a Web site would even
measure revenue for purposes of royalty payments _ whether the
count would include advertising, transactions or subscription
revenue, or some combination of the three.
</P>
<P>
   Steven M. Marks, senior vice president for business affairs for
the Recording Industry Association of America, which is
representing major record labels, declined to say what percentage
the industry hopes to secure in the arbitration process. But he
said the figure should reflect the music's value to the Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're paying for the right to build a business using the
content that's been created by record companies and artists,''
Marks said
</P>
<P>
   The Web companies contend that they already are putting money in
the pockets of the recording industry because they are helping to
spur album sales. Further, the sites argue that the royalties
should only be paid on revenue directly related to the use of a
copyrighted song, such as from a banner advertisement displayed
while a song is played.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're paying for a performance right, we're not paying for the
right to be in business,'' said Jonathan Potter, director of the
Digital Media Association, a trade group that includes many of the
large music Webcasters. Potter said the recording industry had
approached individual Webcasters asking for 15 percent of gross
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   What both sides agree upon is that customized, Internet-based
``radio'' is a growing force. The concept is that Web sites poll
listeners for their music preferences, both artist and genre. The
sites then create hundreds of radio ``stations,'' each reflecting
the musical tastes of a narrow category of visitors to their sites.
The categories listed under Vintage Rock on Spinner.com, for
example, include British invasion, psychedelic and surf.
</P>
<P>
   A survey published two weeks ago indicates that online radio
listening is popular among college students. Webnoize, an online
publication covering the new media music industry, found that of
4,000 students surveyed, 63.4 percent were interested in Internet
radio for niche programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be a great demand for these services,'' said
Joanne Marino, editor in chief of Webnoize, who said Web
communities like Yahoo or Geocities may find it necessary to add a
personalized radio component to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Marks, from the Recording Industry Association of America, said
the record industry had signed many licensing deals with Webcasting
companies, but declined to provide a figure.
</P>
<P>
   The association provided the name of only one company with which
it had reached a deal: Musicmusicmusic Inc., which operates a
service called RadioMoi.
</P>
<P>
   Besides that agreement, Potter of the Digital Music Association
said he knew of no other such licensing deals. He contends that the
record industry wants to make it seem that more deals have been
signed to induce Webcasters to negotiate individually, rather than
as a group through arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-28-99 1725EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
