<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6090 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-INTERNET-NAMES-(T     12-01 1423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-NAMES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOMAIN IDENTITIES ERODE AS GROUPS CROSS DOT-SUFFIX LINES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DAVID F. GALLAGHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It used to be that you could tell a lot about a Web site just by
looking at the letters after the ``dot'' in its address. But as
competition for prime Internet addresses intensifies, the most
popular dot suffixes for domain names _ .com, .net and .org _ are
losing the meanings they once had.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, .com was designated for businesses, while .net was
for groups or companies involved in network access to the Internet
and .org was associated with nonprofit organizations. But not
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since about two or three years ago, there is no distinction
between .com, .net and .org,'' said Christopher Clough, a spokesman
for Network Solutions, the largest Internet name registrar. ``It's
all up to the registrant and self-selection.''
</P>
<P>
   And now that the business of registering names has been opened
to competition, other registrars are all too happy to ignore the
informal rules to keep customers satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, companies wanting a snappy Web address that may no
longer be available in the popular .com category are pushing into
.org and .net territory. In other cases, major companies have
registered across the board to protect trademarks, and nonprofit
organizations, politicians and government agencies are going for
the cachet and easy recall of a .com address.
</P>
<P>
   Until last summer, when it lost its government-sanctioned
monopoly on .com, .net and .org registrations, Network Solutions
made most decisions about who should get which address. Clough said
that in the past the company informally reviewed new domain
registrations to verify that they were appropriate for a particular
category. But in 1995, as new registrations increased, he said, it
became clear that the screening practice was slowing down the
registration process too much. So the company stopped checking.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Network Solutions encourages customers to register multiple
names to cover all three suffixes. ``Anyone may register Web
addresses in .com, .net, and .org,'' says the help section of the
company's Web site (www.networksolutions.com). ``In fact, the best
way to protect the uniqueness of your online identity and brands is
to register or reserve Web addresses in all of the top-level
domains.'' It may also be the best way for Network Solutions to
make money because it charges $35 a year for each name.
</P>
<P>
   This blurring of the lines can be confusing because Web surfers
often rely on suffixes for clues to the nature and source of a Web
site. The prospect of an unscrupulous commercial enterprise posing
as a nonprofit fund-raiser by using the .org domain, for example,
worries some experts _ even if there is no evidence yet of such
hoaxes.
</P>
<P>
   Michael M. Roberts, interim president and chief executive of
Icann _ the Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers,
the network's new governing body _ said the notion that .com, .net
and .org were now all the same was ``not a universally popular
view.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When Network Solutions started giving people names without
asking any of the old questions, things just got very muddy,''
Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies, especially larger ones, have followed Network
Solutions' advice by covering all the domain-name bases. The
Coca-Cola Co., for example, has registered cocacola.org, coke.org
and coke.net _ all of which send surfers to Coke's home page,
www.coke.com.
</P>
<P>
   And many registrants who might have fit better into another
category have chosen .com addresses. A growing number of political
campaigns are taking this option, on the assumption that .com is a
better-known designation than the .org suffix that presidential
candidates used in the 1996 campaign. This year, many have selected
.com addresses, which they are promoting in their print and
broadcast advertising. The list includes georgewbush.com,
mccain2000.com, algore2000.com and billbradley.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on all the advertising that Yahoo and Amazon and
everyone else has done, .com has permeated the culture in a way
that .org has not,'' Lynn Reid, an Internet political strategist
who is a senior adviser to Bill Bradley's campaign, said.
</P>
<P>
   But with some .com addresses having sold for more than $1
million, and with nearly six million .com names already taken, some
businesses are opting for .net or .org addresses.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And a small Internet consulting firm outside Chicago was
confident enough in its choice of .org to make the address part of
its name: the Sitebuilder.org Co. Christopher Bickford, director of
technical services for Sitebuilder.org, said the company was
formerly called ZY Solutions. Then an employee stumbled across the
name sitebuilder.com, which is used by a German company, and
learned that the sitebuilder.org address was available.
</P>
<P>
   Bickford said some of the company's executives opposed the name
because of its nonprofit connotations. ``But the marketing guys and
the sales guys said, `Hey, Sitebuilder! People know what a site
builder is,''' Bickford said.
</P>
<P>
   And he said customers generally did not have problems with the
name. ``We don't represent ourselves as anything but a for-profit
company,'' Bickford said.
</P>
<P>
   The last few years, Joseph Butcher of Seattle has registered a
number of generic-sounding .org and .net names, including
books.org, auction.net, travel.org and computers.org, which he said
he planned to use for either nonprofit or commercial ventures.
Already he has set up a Web site called surplus.net, which is run
as a nonprofit trade association for companies in the
surplus-materials business, which share marketing costs and a
central Web directory. He makes his money by operating the site and
charging the members for services like the designing of Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Using any of his .org names in this way would be ``reasonably
true'' to the perception that .org is for nonprofits, he said. But
Butcher, who described himself as ``an old Net guy from way back,''
said he would no longer be opposed to using .org names for strictly
commercial sites.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone likes the direction the trend is flowing.
Richard Forman, president and chief executive of Register.com, one
of the new registrars of domain names, said that most people still
assume that .org denotes a nonprofit. That is why he contends that
a company using a .org address ``is misleading the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Network Solutions Web site, Register.com suggests
registering a name across the three main domains. But the site's
help pages also list the ``basic rules'' for the various suffixes,
noting for example that .org is recommended for not-for-profit
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Though use of .com, .net and .org is now a free-for-all, the
registration of addresses with some other suffixes is still tightly
controlled. Some countries, for example, are strict about handing
out addresses bearing their two-letter country codes. In Japan, for
instance, an organization or company can register only one .jp
name.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, .mil is reserved for the military, .gov is
for federal government sites and .edu is for colleges and
universities and other schools. But that has not stopped government
agencies and branches of the military from getting .com addresses
for sites intended to attract the public. Workers at the U.S.
Postal Service have e-mail addresses ending in usps.gov. But the
Postal Service promotes usps.com as its Web address and sells
stamps at Stampsonline.com.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And the Army has a recruiting site at goarmy.com. Gary Bishop,
Web administrator for the Army Recruiting Command in Fort Knox,
Ky., said the address, which appears in broadcast and print
advertising, was chosen by an advertising agency. ``The .com gave
it more of an advertising flavor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Icann, the Internet governing body, plans early next year to
discuss proposals for new domains, like .firm and .arts, Roberts,
the group's president, said. One question will be whether to keep
the new categories closed, forcing applicants to meet certain
qualifications. But Roberts said it was unlikely that there would
be a move to enforce or encourage any such rules for existing
domains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The horse has gone from the barn on .com, .net and .org,''
Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-28-99 2019EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
