<HEADLINE>
FOR HOLIDAY SHOPPING, A BAG WORN LIKE A BACKPACK  
 NEW SOFTWARE  DETERMINES COPYRIGHT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the holidays approach, shopping for gifts and festive meals
becomes a major undertaking for many people. Just about everyone
knows what it is like to leave a store laden with shopping bags,
and since few do their holiday shopping with a backpack, a wheeled
cart or a valet, the plastic handles on those bags often end up
creating new indentations in fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Mentken, a New York inventor, thinks shops and stores
should make it possible for customers to walk out with the weight
of their purchases evenly distributed across their shoulders. He
has patented a shopping bag that has back pack straps instead of
handles.
</P>
<P>
   Mentken's bag is built like a conventional grocery or shopping
bag. It is made of heavy paper, squared, with a flat bottom. It
opens to one big compartment. Called BakSak, it folds and unfolds
in the traditional fashion, and weighs about four ounces.
</P>
<P>
   But the bag has straps that are woven through the lip around the
opening. The straps project from one of the long sides of the
opening and extend in a half-loop to the bag bottom, where they are
secured with fasteners. The straps are flat and adjustable. A
cashier can put purchases into the bag and then shoppers can slip
their arms through the straps and hoist the bags onto their backs.
</P>
<P>
   Mentken believes that merchants should like his shopping bags
even more than the ones now in use because the bags will raise
their logos and brand names to eye level. Shoppers all over the
country could become walking advertisements with department store
and designer label bags on their backs. And their hands will be
free for more shopping. Mentken won patent 5,957,354.
</P>
<P>
   NEW SOFTWARE DETERMINES COPYRIGHT
</P>
<P>
   The Copyright Office no longer requires that material be
registered in order to gain copyright protection. Placing a
copyright symbol or notice on a written work, art work or
photograph, for example, serves the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
   But in the electronic age, when original works can be wholly
reproduced with the press of a computer key or the click of a
mouse, people who have created singular sites on the Internet
sometimes want greater reassurance that their compositions are
safeguarded against copying.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan Glogau, a Nanuet, N.Y., inventor has patented a software
program that evaluates the contents of a Web site and yields the
relevant registration forms for the U.S. Copyright Office.
</P>
<P>
   Glogau's software examines a site's structure and its features,
such as text, graphics or photographs, to determine what type of
work category each falls into. It accomplishes this by looking at
``tags'' on Web site files and file extensions _ the kind of codes
that identify, for example, whether a file contains a photograph.
The software then decides whether the registration form should be
accompanied by a printed copy of the Web site features involved.
</P>
<P>
   After breaking down the site, the software asks the user whether
he wants to register each feature individually. The user can also
choose to include each component in the registration of the entire
site as one copyrighted entity. Glogau received patent 5,983,351.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-28-99 1728EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
