</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-REPORT30-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Online buying is out of line for some products, services
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ All the talk about the online revolution is still
mostly that ... talk. It might be nice to know you can buy a car
from a Web site. But most people still like to do it the old way.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine Yahoo Internet Life has a recurring feature called
Old Way/Net Way that puts the Internet to the test. The idea is to
take a task _ like buying a book _ and determine if it is easier to
do on the Internet or the traditional way.
</P>
<P>
   The December issue's version of the feature takes a look at
three things: securing a home loan, finding Pokemon stuff and
buying dog food.
</P>
<P>
   The home loan search was a wash. Both methods were relatively
simple. But it took the author a while longer to qualify for the
loan Internet-style.
</P>
<P>
   The best place to find Pokemon is online, where the price and
selection are better than in stores, according to the article.
</P>
<P>
   Dog food is best hunted the old way. The author saved more than
$10 on a 40-pound bag. The shipping costs for heavy items negated
any online cost or time savings.
</P>
<P>
   The issue also asks people what the future holds for the Web.
</P>
<P>
   In that article, ever-present attorney Alan Dershowitz offers
his thoughts on the future of law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today every handful of haters is integrally linked to every
other handful,'' Dershowitz wrote. ``Together they form a dangerous
network of potential terrorists capable not only of inspiring one
another but also of working in a coordinated matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Film critic Roger Ebert weighs in on what the next millennium's
censorship might include, which is, apparently, very little: ``Is
the regulation of the Internet possible? The practical answer is
`no.'''
</P>
<P>
   BAD CUSTOMER SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   The dwindling amount of customer service in the real world
apparently is alive and well on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   A study from Jupiter Communications said more Web sites are not
responding to their customers' e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterly study sends e-mails requesting simple support to
125 Web sites in five categories _ content, consumer brands,
travel, retail and financial services. Of those, 46 percent took at
least five days to respond, never responded or didn't have an
e-mail address available on the site. In the same period last year,
38 percent of the sites failed to respond in five days.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping sites were a bit better. More than half the sites
tested responded within one day. But 40 percent took at least five
days, up from 28 percent in the same quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite Web ventures' claims last year that they were going to
focus on customer service as a primary investment and implement
major advances in automated assistance packages, the state of
online customer service continues to decline,'' said Cormac Foster,
a Jupiter analyst. ``Many Web ventures are ignoring the opportunity
to communicate with existing and potential customers, discouraging
brand loyalty and opting out of a user-initiated, one-to-one
relationship by delaying, eliminating or not offering responses to
e-mail. ``
</P>
<P>
   SCORE ONE FOR JOBS
</P>
<P>
   Steve Jobs finally beat Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   The December issue of Upside magazine lists ``the people who
really matter most,'' a ranking of the 100 most influential people
in the digital world. Jobs, co-founder, chairman and chief
executive of Apple Computer, heads the list, followed by Microsoft
Chairman and Chief Executive Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   The top 10 is rounded out by AT&AMP;T Chairman and Chief Executive
Michael Armstrong; Masayoshi Son, founder, president and chief
executive of Softbank; John Chambers, chief executive of Cisco
Systems; Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen, who now heads Vulcan
Ventures, an increasingly influential venture capital fund; John
Doerr, a partner in the granddaddy of all venture firms, Kleiner
Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers; Lou Gerstner, head of IBM; David
Wetherell, who runs CMGI, which owns search engines Lycos and
AltaVista; and Scott McNealy, co-founder, chairman and chief
executive of Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Betty, president and chief executive of EarthLink, which is
set to merge with Atlanta-based MindSpring Enterprises, ranked
36th.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
