<HEADER>
A6097 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CPT-PIRATE-MUSIC30-CO     12-01 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-PIRATE-MUSIC30-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Pirating music files problematic for record companies, schools
 &HT;    By John Keilman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Record stores haven't gotten much business from
one 23-year-old University of Dayton senior lately _ and he may
never give them a penny more.
</P>
<P>
   He gets his music free from the Internet. Using the university's
high-speed computer lines, he and his friends download songs known
as MP3 files from web sites that post them illegally. He says his
roommate has built a trove of 2,000 songs, and that he has created
his own compact discs from Internet music.
</P>
<P>
   ``About everyone I know does it,'' says the senior. ``I know
people who are filling up their hard drives (with pirated music).''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to a 21st century headache for college administrators.
Schools have invested millions to create cutting-edge computer
infrastructures, opening new frontiers of research and learning.
However, those same networks have made it easy for students to
trample copyright protection laws.
</P>
<P>
   Untold thousands of digital, CD-quality music files are floating
across the World Wide Web. Some are offered by their creators, who
hope to spur interest in their work by giving away a sample. But
many are copied and traded illegally, depriving musicians and
record companies of money that, according to the Recording Industry
Association of America, is probably exponentially greater than the
$1 million a day lost from bootleg tapes and CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone with an Internet connection can download these files, but
cyber-swiping appears to be especially rampant on college campuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got young people with free time, lots of access, and
they're curious,'' says Barbara Deschapelles, a network
administrator at UD. ``It's kind of a climb the mountain thing:
`What can I get away with?'''
</P>
<P>
   The answer is almost anything.
</P>
<P>
   Dormitories and computer labs at UD, Wright State University,
Sinclair Community College and Antioch use network connections that
are up to 200 times faster than the 56k modems standard on home
computers. That means instead of taking a half hour to download a
5-minute MP3 song, students can do it in seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Once they store a song on their computers, they can play it
whenever they like. They also can put it on their personal Web
sites for others to copy.
</P>
<P>
   That's usually how students are caught with pirated music.
Recording industry agents constantly search for web sites that
illegally post copyrighted songs, notifying colleges when such
material is on their networks. That has happened four times at UD
over the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Those nabbed with bootlegged music can lose network access and
suffer other penalties, such as fines or community service. But
such busts, rare to begin with, may soon become nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   Students say they rarely put MP3s on their Web pages these days.
They usually store the music on their computers' hard drives, which
cannot be accessed by Internet snoopers.
</P>
<P>
   They swap tunes using e-mail and Zip disks, or, in the case of
students at Wright State, through private networks accessible to a
limited number of people. One 18-year-old freshman says that has
allowed him to quickly build a huge collection of MP3s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have almost 1 gigabyte, and that's probably over 10 hours,
probably around a couple of hundred songs,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   College administrators say they're aware of the vast MP3
exchanges on campus, but maintain there's little they can do about
it. They don't know what students have on their computers unless
they spot a guilty Web site or get tipped off by a foolish action
(one UD student was caught when he tried to send an e-mail
containing a whopping 100MB of MP3s; the transmission failed,
giving technicians a copy of the message).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to spread the word that this is illegal and
people are being caught,'' said UD's Deschapelles. `` ... Most
people probably aren't thinking. I think if they did, it would
occur to them that it was illegal and immoral. It's theft of ideas
and theft of property.''
</P>
<P>
   That comes as news to one 20-year-old UD junior.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's illegal?'' he says. ``That definitely changes things.''
</P>
<P>
   He and his housemates have hooked a computer loaded with 1,500
MP3 files to a sound system, using it to supply the music during
parties. They also burn songs onto recordable CDs.
</P>
<P>
   The junior says MP3 search engines and television commercials
for products such as CD burners made him think downloading bootleg
music was OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's such a new thing that people haven't gotten used
to it being illegal,'' he says. ``It's like, `I never have to go to
Best Buy again.'''
</P>
<P>
   Other students, well aware that they are stealing music, have
mixed feelings about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, I think we should be able to do it, because
it's our freedom,'' says an 18-year-old Wright State freshman.
``But I'm in a band. I think, `What if we eventually put out a CD
and everyone copied it?' That thought is there, and to be honest,
it probably is hurting the music business.''
</P>
<P>
   UD and Wright State are rewriting their computer ethics
guidelines to be more specific about copyright violations, and both
vow to increase their educational efforts and punish those they
find with illegal files. Meanwhile, the recording industry is
trying to establish a new standard for digital music that will
ensure security.
</P>
<P>
   MP3s, however, are not the final frontier of piracy. Bootleg
software programs and digitized, full-length movies are showing up
on some university networks. UD administrators recently caught one
student offering several downloadable films on his computer,
including one that is still in theaters.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that the huge movie files download slowly, even
on super-fast networks, and don't run smoothly. That discourages
many students from pursuing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not worth it,'' says the UD senior. ``Not yet anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
