<SLUG> BC-CPT-NETWATCH30-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    There'll always be an England, a fine place to snag unique gifts
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The British are coming! The British are coming!
</P>
<P>
   Well, actually, the British are here, selling everything from
books to breakfast tea on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   I discovered the wonders of British shopping at the most
American of Web retailers, Amazon.com. I was hoping to buy several
copies of the new Bridget Jones novel for gifts, only to find the
book hadn't been published in the United States. However, Amazon,
superstore that it is, always adds related music, video or auction
categories that complement whatever product you are looking up.
Scrolling down the page, I saw that the Bridget Jones book was
available on Amazon's auction site. Fifty copies of ``Bridget
Jones: The Edge of Reason'' were available from a San Diego seller
with a top bid of $32. ``Just published abroad!'' the description
trumpeted, ``but you can get it now!''
</P>
<P>
   Now, I'm ready to bid online for vintage Madame Alexander dolls
and Kentucky Derby memorabilia, but there is absolutely no way I'm
going to bid on a book that was published just last month. Then it
hit me: Why not go straight to the source?
</P>
<P>
   Among the many offerings Amazon has is a British branch at
www.amazon.co.uk. Before you could say ``Buckingham Palace,'' I was
on Amazon's British site, and guess what? It had plenty of copies
of ``The Edge of Reason'' in stock. In fact, it was Amazon.co.uk's
best-selling book that week. Another quick click, and I found the
book was available immediately. The cost to U.S. shoppers including
shipping was about $20, less than the asking price from the
California auctioneer. Needless to say, several copies are now
winging their way to my home in plenty of time for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   I was also hoping to order several paperback volumes of the
popular Harry Potter children's books not yet available in the
United States, but Amazon.co.uk only permits one copy of any Harry
Potter book per U.S. address _ lest they turn up on some online
American auction block, one would imagine.
</P>
<P>
   Smug from my initial success in the international Internet
shopping arena, I've been surfing and browsing some of England's
best-known merchants in search of offbeat holiday gifts.
</P>
<P>
   For unusual and classy gifts, make an online visit to Harrods
(www.Harrods.com), England's most famous department store. Harrods
knows that American shoppers still make up the bulk of online
shoppers and has done a lot to make them feel at home. This
includes everything from the ``.com'' address instead of the
unfamiliar ``.co.uk'' address to pricing items and shipping costs
in U.S. dollars. The range of items is limited but well-chosen and
gives American shoppers the flavor of what the British store is all
about. Shoppers can order everything from cashmere cardigans to
elaborate food baskets, a Harrods' millennium watch, and teddy
bears and other gifts for the kids.
</P>
<P>
   Hamley's, Britain's answer to FAO Schwarz, has a delightful Web
site (www.hamleys.com) that captures the magic of a really, really
big, wonderful toy store, with amusing toys and games for kids and
families. A shopping guide helps select toys by age, price range
and other factors, with surprisingly good results. Pricing is
available in U.S. dollars for American customers.
</P>
<P>
   For home design and accessories and maybe a gift for yourself,
there's no place like Liberty of London
(www.liberty-of-london.com). Known for centuries for its
distinctive patterns that cover everything from wallpaper to
scarves, stationery and umbrellas, the company makes just looking a
treat. Prices are in British currency, with American prices listed
``for comparison only.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some things to keep in mind if you do decide to shop
from international merchants, aside from the usual privacy and
security requirements. Not all merchants provide prices in U.S.
dollars. So to make sure you know just how much you're spending,
use an online currency converter such as J.B.'s Currency Converter
(www.yi.com/home
</P>
<P>
   /BerensJean-Claude/currency
</P>
<P>
   .htm).
</P>
<P>
   Americans tend to forget the ``world'' in the phrase ``World
Wide Web.'' However, an international online shopping trip can
yield wonderful surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
