 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Atlanta steps up chase for tech capital
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta is not Silicon Valley when it comes to finding
venture capital for start-up computer and Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   But the city is doing much better at attracting high-tech
investors than several years ago. Or so says the latest issue of
Digital South magazine. It features a cover story on the South's
new ``holy rollers'' _ the so-called angel investors helping
start-up Internet and computer companies in Atlanta and the rest of
the South.
</P>
<P>
   Meet some of the companies leading the way in harnessing digital
technologies to cut costs and streamline operations. They are
featured in the cover story of the December issue of PC Computing.
The results of the magazine's survey may surprise you, for many of
the companies mentioned are neither involved with the Internet nor
computers. Among the entities featured are REI, McKesson HBOC,
Catalog.com, Webcor Builders and the Nature Conservancy.
</P>
<P>
   ON CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   If the rate of the new games being released for it is an
indicator, Sega's Dreamcast video console must be doing well.
There's a new title announced almost every week. The latest is
``Touring Car Challenge.'' The game is a simulation of British
touring-car racing. There are seven modes of play, eight teams to
drive for and a network play option for those with an Internet
connection.
</P>
<P>
   Another new Dreamcast game is ``Sega Sports NBA 2K.'' Developed
by Visual Concepts for Sega, this professional basketball game has
realistic-looking players and fans. Graphics are so detailed you
can even see players' eyes blink. The game includes replicas of all
current National Basketball Association teams, their arenas and
playbooks.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   Keep up with college basketball at the official site of the
NCAA. The site offers information on all the teams and ways for you
to customize a page to track your favorite team. Merchandise for
sale and a page for kids are also featured. You'll find this site
at www.ncaabasketball.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
