<SLUG> BC-CPT-JOB-FAIR-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE LAPTOP, WILL UPLOAD FOR DINNER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Phillips wanted to go home. An animation artist, he had
worked in New York for MTV and in Berlin for a film studio, but he
couldn't get Barrie, a town 60 miles north of Toronto, out of his
mind. ``I missed being able to drive a short distance to the
wilderness,'' said Phillips, 25.
</P>
<P>
   So, despite the paucity of animation work there, home he went
this year and began trolling the Internet for work. That is how he
discovered eLance, a jobs bazaar (www.eLance.com) where freelancers
can list their skills and search for work. And though he named a
price that was more than 50 percent above what a New York employer
wanted to pay, he landed an assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips is the beneficiary of an economic boom that has driven
unemployment in the United States to its lowest level since
astronauts were landing on the moon and has made employers
desperate for skilled workers. To cater to them, an entirely new
kind of job fair is springing up, run not out of a convention
center but in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ELance and its rivals are the information-age equivalent of the
medieval town square where workers-for-hire called out their
skills. Today's job seekers do the same, but through their computer
keyboards. And whether they are computer programmers in Atlanta or
Finnish translators in San Diego, they can find work without
traveling. For their part, employers gain access to a new pool of
freelancers without having to give them office space or fringe
benefits. Across the economy, said Berrud Sheth, the chief
executive of eLance, ``the supply is sitting all over the world,
and demand is where it is,'' often unable to move.
</P>
<P>
   Though small, the sites tap into three of today's hottest
employment trends: the rise of outsourcing, the Internet revolution
and the surge in people working at home as telecommuters or
small-business owners. In 1998 alone, the number of Americans
identifying themselves as self-employed rose 15 percent, to 10
million, according to the Bureau of Labor Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest jobs bazaar is Monster Talent Market, a part of
Monster.com, the most popular Internet job-hunting site. After five
months in business, Monster Talent Market says it has signed up
110,000 independent contractors and more than 7,500 employers.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, one of the newest players in the field,
FlexMind.com, is deliberately elitist. The Massachusetts start-up
wants to register only students at a dozen or so of the most
selective universities in the country, assuming that employers
would love to hire them for part-time assignments and that the
students who otherwise might have to wait tables would jump at the
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice way for a company to have a low-commitment preview
of an employee,'' said FlexMind chief executive Julius Mokrauer. In
FlexMind's first two months, about 500 students and 40 companies _
including American Express and barnesandnoble.com _ have registered
on the site, Mokrauer said. He left his job as a trader at Lehman
Brothers to start the company last year after hiring a Harvard law
student for $35 an hour and realizing what a bargain that was for
his employer.
</P>
<P>
   FlexMind charges employers 20 percent of whatever they are
paying to the freelancer. Monster takes about 10 percent but no
more than $1,000. ELance, which is now free for both freelancers
and companies, will begin charging next year.
</P>
<P>
   With so many job openings going begging these days, the
freelance Web sites can be a boon to employers. Susan Patnaik, for
example, was having trouble finding an artist in New York to
illustrate a graphic novel _ a type of comic book for adults _ that
she was producing. She had called artists she knew and asked for
recommendations but was striking out.
</P>
<P>
   So she listed the assignment on eLance for $350. Bids started
arriving the next day, and she chose Phillips, even though he
wanted $550, because she was impressed with the samples she had
downloaded. Presto: talent-hungry Ms. Patnaik had her worker, and
job-hungry Phillips had his 25-hour assignment, even though they
live hundreds of miles apart, do not know anybody in common and may
never meet.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, $550 is hardly enough for Phillips to live on, and
thus far he has not landed any other jobs through eLance. The site
has not attracted enough companies to offer a primary source of
income for anybody. Even on Monster Talent Market, only two or
three deals are made each week.
</P>
<P>
   From an employer's perspective, the sites can create as many
problems as they solve, since virtually anyone can post a resume.
On eLance, Phillips said, ``It seems like there are a lot of young,
inexperienced artists applying for jobs.'' And HotJobs.com, a rival
to Monster, does not offer an auction site, the company says,
because its clients _ big companies _ have shown little interest.
</P>
<P>
   But there are a few big success stories. Benita Kenn quit her
job as a public-relations manager for a California technology
company this year to spend more time with her folk band. She put
her resume on Monster Talent Market and got two jobs. The first,
with a golf merchandise site, began in August and is just ending,
while the other, with a seller of personalized T-shirts and mugs,
began in October. Ms. Kenn has been working an average of 20 hours
a week at pay that she says is typical for a public-relations
consultant. (That would be about $100 an hour, said people in the
industry.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, she uses her old contacts because she said she cannot
rely solely on the auction site. ``Ideally, there would be hordes
of people bidding for me,'' Ms. Kenn said. ``But that's not where
it's at at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-30-99 1903EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-01-99 1200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
