<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, Dec. 1, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following for Thursday. If
you have questions, please call Mark Helm at 202-298-6920.
<TEXT>
<P>
   (All stories have ``HNS'' in the keyword line.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-NY-POLITICS (Albany, N.Y) _ New York state, with
comparatively few women in key advisory jobs in Gov. George
Pataki's administration, ranks in the bottom third among states
where females play significant roles in government policy,
according to a new report.
</P>
<P>
   SCOUTS-GAYS (San Francisco) _ Leaders of a Petaluma, Calif.,
church and a powerful member of its congregation, Rep. Lynn
Woolsey, D-Calif., are expressing outrage over the Boy Scouts of
America's refusal to let them sponsor a new troop. The Scouts
rejected the United Church of Christ's petition because the new
troop was proposed by, and might have been led by, Scott Cozza, who
heads a group that's been advocating for an end to scouting's ban
on gays. By CAROL NESS.
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-CASINO (Albany, N.Y.) _ The Oneida Indian Nation, which
is examining the idea of opening a second casino in New York state,
says its first casino is contributing more than $158 million to the
state's economy. By JAMES M. ODATO.
</P>
<P>
   S.F.-ECONOMY (San Francisco) _ This city's economy is riding
high, pumping an unanticipated $20 million more into city hall's
budget surplus, according to City Controller Ed Harrington. Fueled
by a skyrocketing housing market, eager consumers and more tourism,
Harrington said tax revenue grew 7.8 percent from the year before _
more than double the original projections. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FUNCTIONAL-FOODS (Albany, N.Y.) _ For years, supplements have
been the standard way to get extra vitamins and minerals. The
newest trend is to use food as a way to achieve specific health
benefits, like the prevention of osteoporosis or heart disease.
Functional foods, as they're called, are among the hottest items
today on supermarket shelves, appealing to health-conscious
consumers who want to maximize the power of good nutrition. By
SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   LATKES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Latkes, the quintessential Hanukkah
dish, are grabbing attention everywhere. They're showing up not
only in books, magazines and newspapers, but also in restaurants
and catering operations. By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   ROASTED-ROOTS _ Foods that grow underground have by nature a
very earthy flavor. That doesn't mean they taste like dirt. That
means they have a flavor more robust, deep and rich than ethereal
vegetables like spinach or broccoli. A look at parsnip, rutabaga
and celeriac. By LAWRENCE SOMBKE.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MACINTOSH-SYSTEM _ The Macintosh Operating System, since its
October release, generated more frenzy than any recent Mac OS
upgrade. But while the OS 9 itself seems fairly stable when cleanly
installed on the right hardware, third-party software still is a
crapshoot. By MICHAEL SEINBERG.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MAYOR-49ERS-FBN (San Francisco) _ Mayor Willie Brown says he
wouldn't be surprised if San Francisco 49ers owners Denise and John
York sell the team to local investors. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ The New York State Legislature
returns to town this month to finalize health care funding. If
those 211 lawmakers decide also to toughen the Empire State's
laughably lenient ethics law and breathe new life into the state
lobbying commission, New Yorkers can thank Phillip Morris lobbyist
Sharon Portnoy. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
