<SLUG> BC-CPT-STAPLES-WEBAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACKER NAILS STAPLES ONLINE AD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By SHELLEY MURPHY   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shopping on line may be the best way to avoid holiday crowds,
but customers visiting Staples' Web site one day last month
encountered a unique problem when they unwittingly found themselves
in a competitor's store.
</P>
<P>
   A hacker broke into the Framingham, Mass. office supply
retailer's Internet site, www.staples.com, on Oct. 9 and posted
advertisements for one of the company's major competitors, Office
Depot.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers clicking on Office Depot products were immediately
linked to the home page of Staples' major competitor, which is
based in Delray Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Unamused officials at Staples, Inc. filed a lawsuit in US
District Court in Boston Monday charging that ``John Doe,'' the
unidentified hacker, illegally accessed the company's Web site and
damaged the company by stealing e-commerce business.
</P>
<P>
   The suit says the hacker is believed to live in or near
Massachusetts and that the company expects to identify him shortly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider it highly unlikely that one of our competitors
were involved in any way,'' said Shannon Lapierre, public relations
manager of Staples, speculating that the changes to the Web site
may have been a prank.
</P>
<P>
   But Staples, which just announced third-quarter Internet sales
revenue of $24 million, is taking the Web-site intrusion seriously
and is determined to identify the culprit and report him to federal
authorities, Lapierre said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, federal authorities have been on the lookout for
Internet fraud. Federal law prohibits unauthorized access to a
computer and calls for up to 10 years in prison if damage is
recklessly caused as a result of the breach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously e-commerce is a very important part of our business
and very important to the company,'' said Lapierre, noting that
Staples' goal is to have a million on-line customers and a billion
dollars in Internet sales by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Staples, which did $7 billion in sales last year and operates
more than 1,000 office superstores, launched its Web site a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   While monitoring the site Oct. 9, officials noticed that
products advertised throughout the Web site had been deleted and
replaced with products bearing the Office Depot logo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a dead giveaway,'' Lapierre said.
</P>
<P>
   The suit says the Office Depot advertisements contained links to
the Florida company's Web site, meaning Staples visitors who
clicked on the illegally advertised products were redirected to the
competitor's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers were diverted from Staples to Office Depot for about an
hour before the problem was corrected, Lapierre said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to lost business, Staples alleges it cost the
company time and money to repair its Web site and determine the
extent of the security breach.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to Office Depot, the world's largest seller of office
products, were referred to the company's vice president of public
relations, who couldn't be reached for comment late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Lapierre said the problems created by the hacker were had never
happened to Staples before. ``It's an interesting time we live
in,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Staples' stock rose 1/4 Monday to close at 23-13/16 in trading
on the Nasdaq market. Office Depot closed at 11 1/2, down 1/8, on
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-29-99 2008EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
