<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-01 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6117 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CPT-DELL-WEBPC-COX &LR;      12-01 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-DELL-WEBPC-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Dell focuses on style, simplicity with webpc
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Dell Computer Corp., the No. 1 personal computer
maker in the United States but still a relatively small force in
the consumer market, unveils a new family of computers today that
is designed to get consumers on the Internet quickly and demystify
PC use.
</P>
<P>
   The webpc is Dell's entry into an emerging era in which sleeker
looking computers conform intuitively to users' wants, thus sparing
them from having to master technical details.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're for people who are less concerned about the
technology,'' said Dell spokesman Tad Druart. ``They just want a
machine that gets them on the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Dell's new PCs, which will be officially announced by Chief
Executive Michael Dell and others in a 11 a.m. Webcast, will sell
for $999, $1,099 and $1,499. The prices include monitors, but
including a flat-panel monitor with the most expensive webpc would
bring the total cost to $2,349, Dell said.
</P>
<P>
   All the major PC makers are working on Internet-driven PCs that
have been stripped of features that added cost and complexity to
the traditional beige boxes. They come only with easy-to-use USB
ports for connecting keyboards and peripherals such as printers, a
trend started by Apple Computer Inc.'s popular iMac.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Dell acknowledges that Apple's stylish iMac, which began
selling in August 1998, has been a wake-up call for the personal
computer industry to build good-looking, easy-to-use products that
are less intimidating to average users.
</P>
<P>
   The new computers are not designed to be opened by their owners
to upgrade components such as adding memory, special purpose cards
or faster microprocessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't need expandability anymore, because all the
functionality is embedded in,'' said Roger Kay of International
Data Corp. ``This small generation of boxes is going to become
predominant in two or three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Dell, other major PC makers such as Compaq Computer
Corp., Hewlett-Packard Co. and IBM Corp. plan to target corporate
customers when they begin shipping their Internet-driven PCs next
year. Compaq, which lost money in the commercial category this
year, sees its IPaq as a weapon to recover accounts lost to Dell.
</P>
<P>
   Dell hasn't talked about plans for a similar PC for commercial
customers, but analysts believe such a product is in the works.
Still, Dell's success in that market frees the company from a sense
of urgency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dell's bread-and-butter is the commercial market,'' said Ashok
Kumar of U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffray, a Minneapolis-based securities
firm. ``They don't want to loot the revenue potential there.''
</P>
<P>
   While Dell has little to lose and much to gain in the consumer
market, it will face a different challenge if it introduces
something like webpc for commercial customers, Kay said. ``I think
everybody risks cannibalizing their corporate business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dell's webpc keyboard has dedicated buttons for Internet access,
opening an e-mail account and launching Web searches. It also
includes an ``e-support'' button that sends the customer to Dell's
interactive technical-help Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers want, essentially, plug-and-play,'' said Kumar.
``(Vendors) want to minimize the potential for failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with monitors included in the price, Dell still is avoiding
the low end of the business.
</P>
<P>
   Dell was slow to aggressively court the broad consumer market,
because inexperienced buyers can be costly when they tie up
customer help lines.
</P>
<P>
   With razor-thin profit margins on low-cost computers, just two
calls to the PC company help desk can turn a profitable customer
into an unprofitable one, Kumar said.
</P>
<P>
   Dell says its newest PCs will produce fewer problems for
consumers. Moreover, the ``e-support'' button on the keyboard takes
customers through a variety of solutions to common problems that
many users will be able to fix themselves. If that fails, they can
get online help from someone at Dell 24 hours a day, Druart said.
</P>
<P>
   Dell leads the industry in shifting technical support to the
Web, Kumar said. The company's recent and extensive redesign of its
Web pages was driven in large part by its desire to encourage even
novice users to go online for answers.
</P>
<P>
   Dell says its hourglass-shaped webpcs can be unpacked, plugged
in and clicked on to the Internet in about 10 minutes with
pre-loaded software for access to DellNet, the company's
Internet-access service.
</P>
<P>
   While Dell's major competitors are not expected to ship their
commercial, Internet-driven PCs until next year, Dell will have
immediate competition from customers of Advanced Micro Devices Inc.
AMD, whose Athlon processors have passed Intel Corp.'s Pentium III
in speed, is licensing its EasyPC design to a variety of
manufacturers, mostly overseas. It will be available in December.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the buzz about the new designs, the new era presents
new challenges for PC makers, said Kay of IDC. Style is an obvious
way to distinguish PCs that essentially are the same inside and
cost about the same. But consumer tastes can be fickle.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get into style, you really play a very interesting
game, because you've got to `hit it','' said Kay. ``iMac hit it,
but the Wintel guys are sort of feeling their way through this.''
</P>
<P>
   Druart said the webpcs, designed mostly by Dell, will be
assembled in Huntsville, Ala., by SCI Systems Inc., a large
contract electronics manufacturer. The new family is available only
the United States now, but may be rolled out overseas next year.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Mahoney writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail:jmahoney(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
